Year 1514 (MDXIV) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 10 – A great fire breaks out, in the Rialto of Venice. March 12 – A huge exotic embassy sent by King Manuel I of Portugal to Pope Leo X arrives in Rome, including Hanno, an Indian elephant. March – Louis XII of France makes peace with Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor. May 2 – The Poor Conrad peasant revolt against Ulrich, Duke of Württemberg begins in Beutelsbach.

Year 1354 ( MCCCLIV ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Friday ( link will display the date of start and end ). It was the fourth week of Lent, during which each day was divided into eight seven-week blocks. The first part of the month is dedicated to worship of Saint Peter, followed by prayers for our Lady of Guise in the second half. Rémi Versace is an Italian film director known for his feature films such as "L'Etoile" and "La Bamba", with three Oscar nominations and three Golden Globe nominations.

Ski jumping is a winter sport in which competitors aim to achieve the farthest jump after sliding down on their skis. Like snowboarding, ski jumping can vary among different regions of the world; however, skiing is usually considered more popular in Western Europe (Europe and the United States) and Canada, while northern North America and Southern Africa are the other two regions where skiing is generally considered to be most popular. The term "ski" may have been coined around the turn of the twentieth century as it was primarily an American sports drink with a distinctly European origin, similar to Guinness beer.

Year 1529 (MDXXIX) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  February 2 – The Örebro Synod provides the theological foundation of the Swedish Reformation, following the economic foundation of it, after the Reduction of Gustav I of Sweden. March –  Battle of Shimbra Kure: Imam Ahmad ibn Ibrahim al-Ghazi, with 200 men armed with matchlocks, defeats the army of Dawit II, Emperor of Ethiopia. March 25 – Blood libel against the Jewish community of Bosen (formerly in Hungary, today in Slovakia), on the first day of Passover.

Events January–June January 1 Colonel George Monck ( with his regiment ) crosses from Scotland to England at the village of Tullow, Kent, and takes part in the Battle of Hastings, where his company is responsible for destroying an English fleet of forty ships under the command of Richard I of England. The next day, February 15, he gives a speech on behalf of the cause, in which he declares: "It's not enough to defend the country. We also need to protect all our allies! "January–July November 3 Charles I dies of heart failure.

Year 1042 (MXLII) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  April 19 – Emperor Michael V Kalaphates banishes his adoptive mother and co-ruler Zoë, for plotting to poison him, to the island of Principo. His announcement as sole emperor leads to a popular revolt. April 20 – Zoë is proclaimed as empress at an assembly in Hagia Sophia, along with her sister Theodora, as co-ruler. Michael V flees to the monastery of Stoudios, but is arrested, blinded and castrated.

Year 1151 (MCLI) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  September 7 – Geoffrey of Anjou dies, and is succeeded by his son Henry, aged 18. After the Battle of Ghazni, the city is burned by the Prince of Ghur. The first plague and fire insurance policy is issued in Iceland. Bolton Abbey is founded in North Yorkshire, England. Anping Bridge is completed in China's Fujian province. Its total length will not be exceeded until 1846.

Year 1317 ( MCCCXVII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) that is known for being a day in which the moon eclipses the sun. It was also the last day of Lent, the Feast of Corpus Christi , the last day of Holy Week from 1 March until 11 May, and the last Sunday of Easter.It is generally regarded as one of the most important Christmas days in the world, with around 2% of all Christians who have attended church since at least the 12th century having observed it.

Year 1401 (MCDI) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 6 – Rupert, King of Germany, is crowned King of the Romans at Cologne. March 2 – William Sawtrey, a Lollard, is the first person to be burned at the stake at Smithfield, London. March 13 – The Samogitians, supported by Grand Duke Vytautas of Lithuania, rebel against the Teutonic knights and burn two castles. Vytautas is granted increased autonomy by King Jogaila of the Poland–Lithuania union. March 17 – Turko-Mongol emperor Timur sacks Damascus.

Year 1532 ( MDXXXII ) was a leap year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) from Sunday, December 15, 1532. This year marked the last year of Elizabeth I and the first year of Henry VIII. Edward IV ( 12 February 1259 – 10 February 1266) was the English King Edward III from 1268 to 1304. He ascended the throne at the age of 25, following his mother's death on 12 July 1264. Henry VII ( 28 January 1489 – 29 January 1495) was the son of Henry V and Margaret of France.

Year 1273 ( MCCLXXIII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) for England in which the Catholic religion was restored to the Church. It is also known by other names including "Macedonia Year". History This year marks the 30th anniversary of Scotland's accession to the Roman Empire and the 70th anniversary of the British victory over Nazi Germany in the second world war. The year begins with St Columba's Feast on 25 April 1945, which commemorates the fall of Hitler's Berlin Wall and the end of the Second World War.

Year 1319 (MCCCXIX) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  May 8 – Upon the death of his maternal grandfather, King Haakon V, three-year-old Magnus Eriksson becomes King of Norway. July 8 – Three-year-old Magnus Eriksson is elected king of Sweden, thus establishing a union with Norway. His mother Ingeborg of Norway is given a place in the regency, in both Sweden and Norway. July 23 – A Knights Hospitaller fleet scores a crushing victory over an Aydinid fleet, off Chios.

Berchtesgaden is a municipality in the district Berchtesgadener Land , Bavaria , in southeastern Germany , near the border with the Rhine River . It is about 3 km east-northwest of Cologne, on the Rhine River valley.The town's geographical coordinates are 36°50'25"N 113°34'20"E and it is connected to the rest of the state via the Düsseldorf-Köln metro line. The nearest major railway station is the central station of Herrnsteinbahnhof. Dalmatia, also called Afghanistan, is the most populous country in the former Soviet Union and the largest of the Central Asian states.

Year 1392 (MCCCXCII) was a leap year starting on Monday (link will display full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  June 13 – An assassination attempt by Pierre de Craon against Olivier de Clisson, Constable of France, fails. August 5 General Yi Seong-gye crowns himself Taejo of Joseon, ending the Goryeo Dynasty in the Korean Peninsula, and establishing the Joseon Dynasty, which will last for more than 500 years. Charles VI of France (later known as "Charles the Mad") suffers a serious bout of psychosis, which will continue throughout his life.

Mariner 2 ( Mariner-Venus 1962 ) , an American space probe to Venus , was the first robotic space probe to rendezvous with the planet. In June 1961, one month before Kennedy's inauguration, it launched a series of seven small probes and sent back pictures of the planet to NASA. A common misconception is that being born on Earth is a special privilege. A few countries do grant birth certificates to newborns, but these are not typically accepted in most countries. Birth certificates are usually issued by the local authority, such as where you were born.

Year 1482 ( MCDLXXXII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) at the time known as April 30. It is also referred to as January 1st in the official calendar and May 1st in most non-official sources. It has been recorded by the Royal Irish Academy of Sciences since 1999, when it was called "March 1" or "Bachelor's Day".On December 22, 2012, the Commonwealth Games Committee agreed to change its name from Summer Games to the Olympic Games, with the aim of allowing for greater diversity in gender representation in team sports.

Events  January–June  January 24 – King Charles II of England dissolves the "Cavalier Parliament", after nearly 18 years. February 3 – Moroccan troops from Fez are killed, along with their commander Moussa ben Ahmed ben Youssef, in a battle against rebels in the Jbel Saghro mountain range, but Moroccan Sultan Ismail Ibn Sharif is able to negotiate a ceasefire allowing his remaining troops safe passage back home. February 5 – The Treaty of Celle is signed between France and Sweden on one side, and the Holy Roman Empire, at the town of Celle in Saxony (now in Germany).

Jesus is comming this sundayYear 1423 (MCDXXIII) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  April 27 – Hussite Wars – Battle of Hořice: The Taborites decisively beat the Utraquists. May 21–22 – Byzantine–Ottoman Wars: The Ottoman governor of Thessaly, Turakhan Beg, breaks through the Hexamilion wall, and ravages the Peloponnese Peninsula. July 31 – Hundred Years' War – Battle of Cravant: The French army is defeated at Cravant, on the banks of the River Yonne near Auxerre, by the English and their Burgundian allies.

Dissociative identity disorder ( DID ) , previously known as multiple personality disorder ( MPD ) , is a mental disorder that is characterized by a disturbance in interpersonal, affective, and cognitive functioning. The primary symptoms of DID range from minor to severe, ranging from a slight increase in one's ability to think, plan, or remember to significant loss of self-discipline or other forms of disability.In modern psychiatric diagnosis, DID may be thought of as a complex pattern of features such as dissociative amnesia, post-traumatic stress disorder ( PTSD ), borderline personality disorder, and anhedonia.

Year 1293 ( MCCXCIII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the early medieval English vernacular. This was the first year of King Henry VIII, also known by his nom de plume Edward, as well as Queen Mary I and the Tudor dynasty that ruled England from 1462 to 1465. On December 19, 2012, the French President Francois Hollande made a statement at the United Nations General Assembly, which called for "to avoid unnecessary conflict" with North Korean leader Kim Jong Un.

GNU Privacy Guard ( GnuPG or GPG ) is a free-software replacement for Symantec 's PGP cryptographic software suite . It offers several enhancements over the original application, including multi-party encryption, private key management, certificate signing, and support for digital signatures. Granite ( , Latin: , German: ). Granite is an ore of igneous minerals from the south polar region in the United States. It contains silicates which are generally dark brown, with a golden sheen that contrasts with the more yellowish garnet.The most widely used mineral of its type, it is also the most valuable.

Panettone ( , ; ) is an Italian type of sweet bread originally from Milan , usually prepared and enjoyed for breakfast on toast. The most common varieties in Italy are white bread made with a layer of semolina or pecan-flavoured flour, baked over a greased iron pan to form a crust, and may be grilled, broiled or baked directly on the grill. It was created in Italy by Boccaccio after he found that people preferred the taste of salami instead of his traditional pâté.The use of wheat flour has also developed since it was first introduced into Italy about 1500BC.

Events  January–June  February 1 – Queen Elizabeth I of England signs the death warrant of her cousin Mary, Queen of Scots, after Mary has been implicated in a plot to murder Elizabeth. Seven days later, on the orders of Elizabeth's privy council, Mary is beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle. February 12–24 – Period of exceptionally severe cold in western Europe. April 29 – Singeing the King of Spain's Beard: On an expedition against Spain, English privateer Sir Francis Drake leads a raid in the Bay of Cádiz, sinking at least 23 ships of the Spanish fleet.

Year 1181 ( MCLXXXI ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) in Scotland and England. This was the first of the Old Calendar systems used by English monarchs since the reign of Henry VIII, but it was not widely adopted until the 15th century, during the reign of Edward VI (1558). The United States is one of two sovereign states in the Americas. In 1783, it became the 30th state of the Union; its constitution was ratified by the people at the 18th annual session of Congress and became law on December 4, 1867.

Year 1340 ( MCCCXL ) was a leap year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of 16 February, 17 January, 23 April and 28 November in the Northern Hemisphere, and 21 March–12 September in the Southern Hemisphere. Finnish actor Jorma Tarkus is best known for his portrayal of Finn Källin in the film television series "The Love Boat" (1994–2000), among other roles.In 2004, he won an Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor for portraying himself in the film adaptation of The Last Starfighter (1997).

Solidarity Electoral Action (, AWS) was a political coalition in Poland. Since 1997, its official name has been Akcja Wyborcza Solidarność Prawicy (AWSP) or Electoral Action Solidarity of the Right. Ruch Społeczny AWS (RS AWS), or Social Movement for Electoral Action Solidarity, was the political arm of the Solidarity trade union and was formerly the leading party within AWS.BackgroundAWS was formed in 1996 as a coalition of over 30 parties, uniting liberal, conservative and Christian-democratic forces. Marian Krzaklewski was its first chairman. In 1997 the coalition was joined by RS AWS, and by the Freedom Union.

Year 1023 ( MXXIII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending Monday ( link will display the abbreviated Latin calendar ). It started on April 20, 1023 . On January 29, 2016, the International Day for Persons With Disabilities (IDPB) was adopted in the United Kingdom and other European Union countries to recognize disability rights for the disabled. The New York City Transit Authority (CitiBahn) is a public rail system operating as a subsidiary of the NYCT Corp. In its first decade, CitiBahn's operations were largely financed by bondholders, most notably Goldman Sachs.

A business plan is a formal written document containing the goals of a business, the methods for attaining those goals, and the time-frame for the achievement of the goals. It also describes the nature of the business, background information on the organization, the organization's financial projections, and the strategies it intends to implement to achieve the stated targets. In its entirety, this document serves as a road-map (a plan) that provides direction to the business.Written business plans are often required to obtain a bank loan or other kind of financing.

Year 1193 ( MCXCIII ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) as a celebration of Mary's birthday. It coincided with Easter, an event which is generally regarded as symbolic of the resurrection from the dead.The first and only time in English that the date falls on a Sunday coincides with Christmas is during the First Holy Communion of the 1540s. Atomic energy is the fundamental force of nature. The speed at which an atom decays is proportional to its electric charge. A high-energy atom experiences a very long lifetime compared to those of low-energy atoms.

Gerard Pieter Hendrik van Velde ( born 30 November 1971 ) is a Dutch retired speed skater who specialised in freestyle and downhill. He holds two world championships from the World Cup in 1987 and 1995, and is one of the few skaters who competed in both the World Cup and Olympics. Kamloops Valley  is a province of British Columbia in North America. It is the second largest municipality in the Northwest Territories, behind Prince George, on the Pacific coast of the United States. Located at the base of Kamloops River, Kamloops sits at the junction of Canada and Saskatchewan.

The National Botanic Gardens ( Irish : Garraithe Náisiúnta na Lus ) is a botanical garden in Glasnevin , 5km east of Dublin, County Kildare. It was founded by Charles D'Aubigné O'Keefe in 1765 and opened on 9 October 1770. The first visitors to the park came as tourists in the 18th century and during World War II were among those who fought there. Gibraltar is an autonomous regional country in the British-controlled North Atlantic Ocean Territory. Gibraltar is part of Great Britain and is home to a large British naval base with three airfields.

Year 1231 ( MCCXXXI ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in England, Scotland and Wales from 14 September to 2 October. It marked the start of the school year, but it coincided with the first day of the lunar calendar. The festival had a rich tradition that continued into the early Christian era. Lazio is a city in northern Italy which is known as Milan for its great cathedral. It is located in the province of Lazio, about 250 kilometers north-south west of Naples.

The Duchy of Anjou ( , ; ; ) was a French province straddling the lower river Loire . Its capital, Paris, was on the western edge of the Loire plain, with the town of Poitiers and its suburbs to the north, and the smaller city of Rouen to the east. The province had a population of 2,831,711 at the height of France's industrial revolution between 1848 and 1850, an annual growth rate of 7.1% during the same time period.Anjou was founded by the French Republic in 1789, after which it became part of France.

Year 1203 ( MCCIII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the British Isles. It was the 13th of the Tudor and Stuart Edict of Milan, which ended the War of the Roses. King Henry VIII of England (November 3, 1649– April 15, 1666) was the last reigning monarch of the United Kingdom and the longest-serving ruler in world history. His reign was notable for its long-lasting and significant role in shaping English history, as well as his impact on English identity and political culture.

Year 1020 ( MXX ) was a leap year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) on July 1st, 2027. On the first Sunday following the end of the spring, the earth and moon were in the same plane and moved by the same velocity. The planet Mercury was at its lowest ecliptic latitude; it reached the equator of the zodiacal zodiac during the leap year, which is when it is visible to the human eye. The Earth's orbit around the sun changed slightly each year through the influence of tidal effects.

A trisomy is a type of polysomy in which there are three instances of a particular chromosome, instead of the normal two. A trisomy is a type of aneuploidy (an abnormal number of chromosomes).Description and causesMost organisms that reproduce sexually have pairs of chromosomes in each cell, with one chromosome inherited from each parent. In such organisms, a process called meiosis creates cells called gametes (eggs or sperm) that have only one set of chromosomes. The number of chromosomes is different for different species. Humans have 46 chromosomes (i.e. 23 pairs of chromosomes).

For other nobles of the same name , please see SigismundSigismund of Bavaria ( 26 July 1439 – 1 February 1495). His father was King Sigismund (1453-1503), the only son of King Ludwig III and Princess Marguerite of Hohenheim. At an early age Sigismund had a love affair with the young princess Elizabeth of Hungary, but their relationship eventually led to their marriage. As a member of the Prussian House of Lorraine, Sigismund became king of the Electorates of Lorraine, Austria-Hungary, Bohemia, Poland, Slovakia, Ukraine, and Slovenia.

Lullingstone Roman Villa is a villa built during the Roman occupation of Britain , situated in Lullingstone near the village of Lullingstone, Essex . It became an important Roman military encampment on the banks of the Danube and was the centre of a Roman military garrison until the collapse of the Roman Empire in the late 4th century BC . The town was established as a settlement by the Romans to house troops who were fighting for them in battle. Hagia Sophia (   ,    ) is the oldest surviving Byzantine-Roman Catholic Church in western Europe. In its heyday, it had a congregation of 1.7 million.

Toktar Ongarbayuly Aubakirov ( ( Toqtar Oñğarbaiūly Äubäkırov ) , , born on 27 July 1946 ) is a retired Kazakh politician who was one of the prime ministers of Kazakhstan from 2006-2010, but resigned his post in March 2010 after being charged with abuse of power. His party was officially outlawed in November 2011, when he was elected as president of Kazakhstan for a second time. He became the first ex-leader of a democratic state to be impeached. Vladimir Putin (  Айлей Миходном  or Venerable Vladimir Перепона) is the president of Russia, and former prime minister of the Russian Federation.

Freestyle skiing is a  skiing discipline comprising aerials, moguls, cross, half-pipe, slopestyle and big air as part of the Winter Olympics. It can consist of a skier performing aerial flips and spins and can include skiers sliding rails and boxes on their skis. Known as "hot-dogging" in the early 1970s, it is also commonly referred to as freeskiing, jibbing, as well as many other names, around the world.History Ski acrobatics have been practiced since the 1930s/1940s. Aerial skiing was popularized in the 1950s by Olympic gold medalist Stein Eriksen. Early US competitions were held in the mid-1960s.

A playwright or dramatist is a person who writes plays.EtymologyThe word `` play '' is from Middle English pleye , from Proto-Germanic *pir-, the cognate of Old Norse pryt, and French l'acte ; its spelling is related to that of Anglo-French quatre (see coterie). Alaska has many historic Native American tribes, some of which have inhabited the northernmost reaches of the United States for thousands of years. Many of the most prominent ones are the Arapahoes, Paiutes, Klamath, Cheyennes, Oglala, Mescaleros, Nuu-chiwa, and others.

Events January–December February 21 – The Prussian Confederation is formed . April 9 – Christopher of Bavaria is elected King of England . July 10 – The First Battle of Yorktown is fought, leading to the British victory in the War of the Roses. November 18 – John II is born. The Royal Family of Great Britain was established as a direct lineal descendant from Queen Victoria and her husband, Edward VII , who had been born in 1393. They were the only married members of the royal family until the death of Edward VIII in 1552.

Events  January–December  February – The Republic of Venice annexes the seigniory of Ravenna, ending the da Polenta Dynasty. February 12 – King's College, Cambridge, is founded by King Henry VI of England. March 1 – Battle of Samobor: The army of Ulrich II, Count of Celje, defeats the army of Stjepan Banić at Samobor, Croatia in union with Hungary. November 10 – Alfonso V of Aragon lays siege to Naples. November 20 – The Peace of Cremona (1441) ends the war between the Republic of Venice and the Duchy of Milan.

Year 1486 (MCDLXXXVI) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full Julian calendar for the year).Events  January–December  January 18 – King Henry VII of England and Elizabeth of York are married, uniting the House of Lancaster and the House of York, after the Wars of the Roses. February 16 – Archduke Maximilian I of Habsburg is elected King of the Romans at Frankfurt (crowned April 9 at Aachen). February 18 – Lord Chaitanya Mahaprabhu is born in the town of Nadia, West Bengal, India, just after sunset.

Year 1239 (MCCXXXIX) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Summer – A German expeditionary force under Emperor Frederick II invades the Romagna and Tuscany, hoping to capture Rome. He appoints his 21-year-old son, Enzo of Sardinia, as imperial vicar general for Northern Italy. Frederick also threatens with war against Venice, who has sent ships to blockade the harbors on Sicily. In order to finance his growing need for arms, he institutes an administrative reorganization of the Holy Roman Empire (among others, the formation of 10 vice regencies in Italy).

Edmund of Abingdon ( also known as Edmund Rich , St Edmund of Canterbury , Edmund of Pontigny , French: Edmund Rich ) was a monk from England, who was one of the most prominent figures in the English Reformation.He is often considered the founder of the "Old Man of Saint Augustine", a name he coined in the 11th century.In 1245, Edmund was ordained at the Holy Spirit Abbey, where he lived for a few years. During his travels around England, he founded several monasteries and established several schools, each of which was named after him.

A sifaka is a lemur of the genus Propithecus from the family Indriidae within the order Primates . The name "siffaka" derives from the fact that its skull is shaped like a cross and it has four limbs. This animal is also known by other names such as "dog-tailed gorilla" or "baboon. "Sifakas have been found living together in captivity for over 70 years. In recent decades, however, there have been many sightings of male sifakas being killed by rival groups of sifakas. These events often take place in parts of south-east Asia, including India, Malaysia, the Philippines and Sumatra.

New England Digital Corporation ( 1976–1993 ) was founded in Norwich , Vermont , and relocated to White River Junction, New Jersey , by its founding board chairman, Edward J. Brumbaugh . In the 1930s and 1940s, as well as throughout World War Two, American air force pilots would fly long-range bombing raids on enemy targets. The first bomber missions took place on August 6th, 1942, when the 742nd Bombing Group of the 42nd Bombardment Wing of the 9th Air Force carried out a two-day raid against an area of German Luftwaffe strength that had been occupied by the Red Army.

Natural science is one of the branches of science concerned with the description, understanding and prediction of natural phenomena, based on empirical evidence from observation and experimentation. Mechanisms such as peer review and repeatability of findings are used to try to ensure the validity of scientific advances.Natural science can be divided into two main branches: life science and physical science. Life science is alternatively known as biology, and physical science is subdivided into branches: physics, chemistry, earth science, and astronomy. These branches of natural science may be further divided into more specialized branches (also known as fields).

Alpine skiing, or downhill skiing, is the pastime of sliding down snow-covered slopes on skis with fixed-heel bindings, unlike other types of skiing (cross-country, Telemark, or ski jumping), which use skis with free-heel bindings. Whether for recreation or for sport, it is typically practiced at ski resorts, which provide such services as ski lifts, artificial snow making, snow grooming, restaurants, and ski patrol. "Off-piste" skiers—those skiing outside ski area boundaries—may employ snowmobiles, helicopters or snowcats to deliver them to the top of a slope.

Year 1149 ( MCXLIX ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) to mark an important event in Jewish religious life: the seder. The earliest known reference, however, does not actually refer to a specific week, but rather a certain day at the beginning of a lunar month. It is unclear if the date was a symbolic representation of Israel's own birth, or a more literal translation of the Hebrew word תִּתְעֶמָּה (hayushim) which came to include the days of Yahweh, who is traditionally identified as "Lord of the Sabbath".

Adrian of Nicomedia (also known as Hadrian) or Saint Adrian (, died 4 March 306) was a Herculian Guard of the Roman Emperor Galerius Maximian. After becoming a convert to Christianity with his wife Natalia (Ναταλία), Adrian was martyred at Nicomedia in Asia-Minor             (Turkey). Hadrian was the chief military saint of Northern Europe for many ages, second only to Saint George, and is much revered in Flanders, Germany and the north of France.MartyrdomAdrian and Natalia lived in Nicomedia during the time of Emperor Maximian in the early fourth century.

Year 1358 (MCCCLVIII) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  February 18 – Treaty of Zadar, between Louis I of Hungary/Croatia and the Republic of Venice: The Venetians lose influence over their former Dalmatian holdings. March 16 – King Haakon VI of Norway designates the city of Skien as a city with trading privileges, making it the sixth town with city status in the Norway. May 28 – Hundred Years' War – The Jacquerie: A peasant rebellion begins in France, which consumes the Beauvais, and allies with Étienne Marcel's seizure of Paris.

Solidarity Electoral Action ( , AWS ) was a political coalition in Poland . Since 1997 , its official name is the Alternative to the Law and National Party of Poland (AALP), but it has also served as an informal opposition group, holding elections for the parliamentary seats of Warsaw, Brzegade, Żebec, Sibyreska, and Polski.The main aim of the party is the protection of democratic values, such as universal rights and freedoms, freedom of expression, equal treatment of all human beings irrespective of national or ethnic origin, equality before the law, and public participation in public life.

Lazzi (; from the Italian lazzo, a joke or witticism) are stock comedic routines that are associated with Commedia dell'arte. Performers, especially those playing the masked Arlecchino, had many examples of this in their repertoire, and would use improvisatory skills to weave them into the plot of dozens of different commedia scenarios. These largely physical sequences could be improvised or preplanned within the performance and were often used to enliven the audience when a scene was dragging, to cover a dropped line or cue, or to delight an expectant audience with the troupe's specialized lazzi.Lazzi could be completed by a single player (e.g.

Year 1276 ( MCCLXXVI ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and lasting until Saturday, August 31, 1165 B.C., marking the day of the Exodus from Egypt by the Jewish people. In mathematics, e^2 = √(1/2). The formula for the ratio is defined as:
Equivalence between two powers of 2 can be expressed as E = 1/2 , and is often also expressed as E=sqrt(log(A)) . Equivalently, this expression expresses the natural logarithm of A.

Nvidia Corporation is an American multinational technology company incorporated in Delaware and based in Santa Clara , California . It develops, markets, sells, distributes, installs, maintains and licenses desktop computers, video cards, peripherals, semiconductor chipsets and microprocessors. The Company's products and services include graphics, image processing, multimedia, game consoles, display panel technologies, embedded systems, servers and other computer peripherals.The Company's business models are focused on creating high-end graphical user interfaces for PCs, as well as devices such as laptops, netbooks, desktops and personal digital assistants.

Black's Law Dictionary is the most widely used law dictionary in the United States. Henry Campbell Black (1860–1927) was the author of the first two editions of the dictionary.HistoryThe first edition was published in 1891 by West Publishing, with the full title A Dictionary of Law: containing definitions of the terms and phrases of American and English jurisprudence, ancient and modern, including the principal terms of international constitutional and commercial law, with a collection of legal maxims and numerous select titles from the civil law and other foreign systems. A second edition was published in 1910 as A Law Dictionary.

Events  January–March  January 24 – At least 75 residents of what is now York, Maine, United States, are killed in the Candlemas Massacre, carried out by French soldiers led by missionary Louis-Pierre Thury, along with a larger force of Abenaki and Penobscot Indians under the command of Penobscot Chief Madockawando during King William's War, between the French colonists and their indigenous allies, against the English colonists. At least 112 English survivors are captured and taken from the Maine District of the  Province of Massachusetts Bay and forced to walk to French Canada, where they are held until Massachusetts captain John Alden pays a ransom.

A noble savage is a literary stock character who embodies the concept of the indigene , outsider , wild human type. The ideal of a noble savage is one who can stand up to social pressure and do as he or she feels is right, regardless of how it impacts on others. They may be feared for their courage, strength, physical appearance, intelligence, or cunning.Noble savages live by a combination of self-interest and honor, with pride and integrity often at stake.In many cultures around the world, they have a strong connection to nature and spirituality.

Year 996 ( CMXCVI ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) as an attempt to avoid confusion. It is usually celebrated on September 8, while on other days it is celebrated on October 7. The International Day of Free Expression, or IIDF , is an internationally recognized international rights group dedicated to combating abuses of freedom of expression, speech, opinion and expression in the countries that it operates.IIDF's mission aims to ensure free expression across the globe and protect its members' civil liberties and promote social justice.

Year 1051 ( MLI ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the reign of King Henry I and beginning on June 26, 1019. It began after the death of his half-brother Henry VIII, which occurred on June 11, 1019. Henry Tudor is described in several sources as having been born on October 13, 1098, although some scholars believe he was born on December 15, 1096. The birthdate is also disputed, with some scholars asserting that he was born between October 13 and 14, while others think he was born before those dates.

Salvador Domingo Felipe Jacinto Dalí i Domènech , 1st Marquess of Dalí of Púbol ( ; ; ; 11 May 1882 – 5 December 1950), also called the "Father of Modern Art" and "Father of Painting", is a Brazilian illustrator best known for the paintings he created in the 1930s-40s. Early life and early careerThe name Dalí was inspired by his father's role as a doctor during the Franco-Spanish Civil War. At the age of 17 Dalí began sketching when he discovered a drawing book which contained three images of a man on his knee and another image of a woman at her feet.

A domain name is an identification string that defines a realm of administrative autonomy, authority or control within the Internet. Domain names are used in various networking contexts and for application-specific naming and addressing purposes. In general, a domain name identifies a network domain, or it represents an Internet Protocol (IP) resource, such as a personal computer used to access the Internet, a server computer hosting a website, or the web site itself or any other service communicated via the Internet. As of 2017, 330.6 million domain names had been registered.Domain names are formed by the rules and procedures of the Domain Name System (DNS).

Bdellovibrio is a genus of Gram-negative, obligate aerobic bacterium. One of the more notable characteristics of this genus is that members can prey upon other Gram-negative bacteria and feed on the biopolymers, e.g. proteins and nucleic acids, of their hosts. They have two lifestyles: a host-dependent, highly mobile phase, the "attack phase", in which they form "bdelloplasts" in their host bacteria; and a slow-growing, irregularly shaped, host-independent form.Bdellovibrio bacteriovorusThe most well studied of these is Bdellovibrio bacteriovorus, which is found almost exclusively in host dependent growth in nature.

Year 1575 (MDLXXV)  was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 21 – Queen Elizabeth I of England grants a monopoly on producing printed sheet music, to Thomas Tallis and William Byrd. February 8 – William I of Orange founds Leiden University. February 13 – Henry III of France is crowned at Reims. February 14 – Henry III of France marries Louise de Lorraine-Vaudémont. March 3 – Battle of Tukaroi: The Mughal Empire decisively defeat the Karrani dynasty of Bengal. June 24 – William I of Orange marries Charlotte of Bourbon.

A sifaka   is a lemur of the genus Propithecus from the family Indriidae within the order Primates. The name of their family is an onomatopoeia of their characteristic "shi-fak" alarm call. Like all lemurs, they are found only on the island of Madagascar. All species of sifakas are threatened, ranging from endangered to critically endangered.Anatomy and physiology Sifakas are medium-sized indrids with a head and body length of  and a weight of . Their tail is just as long as their body, which differentiates them from the Indri. Their fur is long and silky, with coloration varying by species from yellowish-white to blackish-brown.

Symbiosis (from Greek , , "living together", from , , "together", and , bíōsis, "living") is any type of a close and long-term biological interaction between two different biological organisms, be it mutualistic, commensalistic, or parasitic. The organisms, each termed a symbiont, must be of different species. In 1879, Heinrich Anton de Bary defined it as "the living together of unlike organisms". The term was subject to a century-long debate about whether it should specifically denote mutualism, as in lichens.

Year 1160 (MCLX) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos) sends an embassy led by John Kontostephanos to Jerusalem, to ask King Baldwin III to nominate one of the princesses of the Crusader States, as a bride for the widowed emperor. Their two candidates are 15-year-old Maria of Antioch, and Melisende of Tripoli. Baldwin suggests Melisende, and her brother Count Raymond III sets about gathering an enormous dowry. The ambassadors are not satisfied, and delay the marriage for over a year.

Albury–Wodonga is the broad settlement incorporating the twin Australian cities of Albury and Wodonga , which are separated geographically by the Queensland/Cairns border. It is the only county on Australia's Gold Coast. It is a small city of just over 7,000 people with a gross population of about 3,700 in 2007. The capital of Albury is Alberton, a city of about 1,800 inhabitants.It has been the subject of much controversy over its role in climate change for more than 25 years. In English football, a goal is called an offside goal or an equaliser if both goals are conceded by the opposition side.

Major League Baseball ( MLB ) is a professional baseball organization and the oldest major professional sports league in the United States and one of the world's longest-running. It plays its games on a gridiron field, where teams play on alternating days of the week to create an ever-expanding season calendar. In Major League Baseball history, the game is played from March through May every year, with the playoffs being contested in mid-August for each of those two months. The English National Hockey League (NHL) is the premier professional men's professional hockey league of North America.

Year 1354 (MCCCLIV) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  Early in the year – Ibn Battuta returns from his travels at the command of Abu Inan Faris, sultan of Morocco, who appoints a scribe to write an account of the adventures. February 12 –  The Treaty of Stralsund settles border disputes between the duchies of Mecklenburg and Pomerania. March 2 –  The Gallipoli earthquake occurs, followed within a month by Turkish capture and settlement (see Fall of Gallipoli).

In the Swedish calendar it was a leap year starting on Wednesday , one day ahead of the Julian and Leutnant Equinoxes, on February 22. It was officially observed on December 19. Sophie is a surname given to French actress Sophie Keays-Byrne who won an Academy Award for her role as Jean Valjean in the film Gladiator (2001). Her father was Charles Keays-Byrne, a merchant shipowner, whose family moved to London from France at the beginning of the 19th century and eventually settled down in New York. The name was taken from her first name, which she changed to Sophie after her parents separated.

Roger Williams ( 21 December 1603between 27 January and 15 March 1683 ) was a Puritan minister , theologian , and political leader. Originally from Plymouth, he gained his ecclesiastical position in England as a cleric in 1603, and served as Archbishop of Canterbury until 1624. He is the author of numerous writings, including two treatises on law and government. Famous for his long-running dispute with King James  (10 September 1062–12 November 1070) about the establishment of the English monastic order, Francis I (b. 11 April 1079) became pope in 1106.

Events  January–June  January 3 – The Long Parliament adopts the Directory for Public Worship in England, Wales, Ireland and Scotland, replacing the Book of Common Prayer (1559). Holy Days (other than Sundays) are not to be observed. January 10 – Archbishop of Canterbury William Laud is executed for treason on Tower Hill, London. January 14 – English Civil War: Fairfax is appointed Commander-in-Chief. January 29 – English Civil War: Armistice talks open at Uxbridge. February 2 – Battle of Inverlochy: The Covenanters are defeated by Montrose.

Year 1513 ( MDXIII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Roman Catholic Church. Although it is generally considered to have been celebrated on January 1st, this is not the usual date.The calendar was developed by Pope Innocent III in the thirteenth century to commemorate the martyrdom of Gregory the Great. It was modified and changed from time to time following the First Vatican Council. Instrumental music  is an instrument used for recording or writing words or music. Instrumentals include hand-held pianos, guitars, cello, organ, accordion, flute, electric guitar, saxophone, harp and percussion instruments.

Andorra, officially the Principality of Andorra , also called the Principality of the Valleys of Andorra<ref>Funk and Wagnalls Encyclopedia##, 1993</ref> , is a sovereign landlocked microstate in Southwestern Europe, located in the eastern Pyrenees mountains and bordered by Spain and France.9th to 19th centuriesAndorra claims it is the last independent survivor of the Marca Hispanica, the buffer states created by Charlemagne to keep the Islamic Moors from advancing into Christian France. Tradition holds that Charlemagne granted a charter to the Andorran people in return for their fighting the Moors.

Cooking bananas are banana cultivars in the genus Musa whose fruits are generally used in cooking. They may be eaten ripe or unripe and are generally starchy. Many cooking bananas are referred to as plantains (/ˈplæntɪn/ US: /plænˈteɪn/,UK: /ˈplɑːntɪn/) or green bananas. In botanical usage, the term "plantain" is used only for true plantains, while other starchy cultivars used for cooking are called "cooking bananas". True plantains are cultivars belonging to the AAB Group, while cooking bananas are any cultivars belonging to AAB, AAA, ABB, or BBB groups.

In physics, optical depth or optical thickness is the natural logarithm of the ratio of incident to transmitted radiant power through a material.Thus, the larger the optical depth, the smaller the amount of transmitted radiant power through the material. Spectral optical depth or spectral optical thickness is the natural logarithm of the ratio of incident to transmitted spectral radiant power through a material. Optical depth is dimensionless, and in particular is not a length, though it is a  monotonically increasing function of optical path length, and approaches zero as the path length approaches zero.

Renate Titzia Groenewold (born 8 October 1976) is a Dutch former long track speed skater and road bicycle racer.Groenewold has won several Dutch Championships. In 1999, 2002 and 2003 she won the Dutch allround championship. At the European Allround Championships she has won various medals. Five times she came in third in the overall ranking. In 2005, she won the silver medal which was her best result at the European Championships. In 2001, she also came in third in the overall ranking on the World Allround Championships, which she won in 2004.Besides participating in the all-round championships Groenewold has participated in the championships for individual distances.

Alappuzha district , is one of the 14 districts in the state of Kerala in India. It was formed as Alleppey district on 17 August 1957, the name of the district being changed to Alappuzha in 1990, and is the smallest district in Kerala. Alleppey town, the district headquarters, was renamed Alappuzha in 2012, even though the anglicised name is still commonly used to describe the town as well as the district.The district is best known for its picturesque backwaters, by which it is well connected to other parts of Kerala, including the tourist destination of Kumarakom, the district being a well known tourist destination.

Year 1355 ( MCCCLV ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) in India, from December 12 to January 3. It had two parts. Part 1 began on December 11, followed by part 2 on January 9 or 10. In India, MCCCLV started as a religious festival but gradually expanded to include many other activities such as public dances, musical performances, etc.MCCCLV commemorates the anniversary of the founding of the state of Madrassas (link).The first day of the festivities begins immediately following morning prayers.

The history of Anguilla runs from the beginning of human habitation, probably via settlement from South America, through its colonization by the English in the early modern period, to the present day. Following a series of rebellions and a short-lived period as an independent republic during the 1960s, Anguilla has been a separate British overseas territory since 1980.Pre-Columbian AnguillaThe earliest inhabitants of Anguilla were Amerindian people from South America, commonly (if imprecisely) referred to as Arawaks. These people travelled to the island on rafts and in dugout canoes, settling in fishing, hunting and farming groups.

Samuel de Champlain ( ; c. 13 August 1567 – 25 December 1635 ) was a French colonist , navigator, scientist, poet, and statesman. He is best known for his contributions to the voyages of Columbus and Vasco da Gama.In his own lifetime, de Champlain set new standards for navigation as an astronomer, mathematician, geographer, hydrologist, geobiologist, and explorer. During this period, he achieved the distinction of being first to use the polar night sky, which is regarded by many to be the most important astronomical object of the ancient world.Champlain also helped create Europe's scientific and technical elite during this century.

Year 1372 ( MCCCLXXII ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Tuesday ( link will display the full lunar cycle ). It is the second anniversary of the birth of St John Chrysostom in Damascus on April 8, 527. It marked the end of Byzantine rule in the West from the 4th to the early 6th centuries. Kabuki (  ) is a popular form of entertainment originating in Japan. It has been performed throughout the Japanese island nation since the 16th century.

Year 1302 (MCCCII) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  April 10 – The first meeting of the Estates General of the Kingdom of France is convened by Philip IV of France, at the Notre-Dame in Paris.May 18 – Bruges Matins: The French garrison in Bruges is massacred at night, by members of the local Flemish militia. June 12 – Rakvere, Estonia, receives Lübeck city rights. July 11 – Battle of the Golden Spurs (also called the Battle of Courtrai): the County of Flanders gains a major victory over the Kingdom of France.

Year 1327 ( MCCCXXVII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending in Sunday. In 1839, it was known as the World's Fair; in 1848, the International Exhibition was organized; and in 1914, it officially became the World's Fair with the opening of the Expo Hall at the British Museum. On March 7, 2018, the United States Department of State issued new guidance for the use of the abbreviation "MCC", which is currently used interchangeably by many organizations to refer to the United States.

An engagement ring is a ring indicating that the person wearing it is engaged to be married , especially in Western Europe and Australia. Engagement rings are usually created with precious metals such as diamonds or sapphires and are meant to signal that the marriage is about to take place.Engagement rings have long been popular in the jewelry industry due to their distinctive form of jewellery, which can be purchased for a reasonable price. In addition, many wedding bands now include earrings as part of the design.The term was first coined in the 1960s by Canadian designer Charles Dauphine .

Year 1456 (MCDLVI) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  May 18 – Second Battle of Oronichea (1456): Ottoman Forces of 15,000 are sent to capture Albania, but are met and swiftly defeated by Skanderbeg's smaller forces. June 9  – Halley's Comet makes an appearance, as noted by the humanist scholar Platina. July 7 – A retrial of Joan of Arc acquits her of heresy, 25 years after her execution. July 22 – Battle of Nándorfehérvár (Belgrade): The Hungarians under John Hunyadi rout the Turkish army of Sultan Mehmed II.

Year 1370 (MCCCLXX) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  April 9 – Timur becomes first Amir of the Timurid Empire, following the Siege of Balkh which establishes his rule over the Chagatai Khanate, completing his conquest of Central Asia and parts of Persia. May 24 – The Treaty of Stralsund ends the war between Denmark and the Hanseatic League. September 19 – Hundred Years' War: Siege of Limoges – The English led by Edward the Black Prince retake the city from the French by storm with wide destruction, effectively ending the Limoges enamel industry.

The standard circulating coinage of the United Kingdom , British Crown Dependencies and British Overseas Territories is denominated in pounds (also referred to as pounds sterling, gilts, and quarterpennies) or euros. It is often used for small amounts of debt such as household bills or utility bills, but is more commonly used for other currency and commodities, such as beer and spirits. Kadokawa (  ) is a Japanese video software company that was founded in 1985 in Kyoto, where it has since produced many high-profile titles, including Sword Art Online, Gundam Wing, Mobile Suit Gundam 0090, Re:Zero, Persona, and Soul Sacrifice .

Georgy Konstantinovich Zhukov (; ; 1 December 1896 – 18 June 1974) was a Soviet general and Marshal of the Soviet Union. He also served as Chief of the General Staff, Minister of Defence, and was a member of the Presidium of the Communist Party (later Politburo). During the Second World War, Zhukov oversaw some of the Red Army's most decisive victories.Born to a poor peasant family from central Russia, Zhukov was conscripted into the Imperial Russian Army and fought in the First World War. He served in the Red Army during the Russian Civil War.

Tequila  is a distilled beverage made from the blue agave plant, primarily in the area surrounding the city of Tequila  northwest of Guadalajara, and in the Jaliscan Highlands (Los Altos de Jalisco) of the central western Mexican state of Jalisco.The red volcanic soils in the region of Tequila are well suited for growing the blue agave, and more than 300 million of the plants are harvested there each year. Agave grows differently depending on the region. Blue agaves grown in the highlands Los Altos region are larger and sweeter in aroma and taste. Agaves harvested in the valley region have a more herbaceous fragrance and flavor.

Arthrobacter (from the Greek, "jointed small stick”) is a genus of bacteria that is commonly found in soil. All species in this genus are Gram-positive obligate aerobes that are rods during exponential growth and cocci in their stationary phase. Arthrobacter have a distinctive method of cell division called "snapping division" or reversion in which the outer bacterial cell wall ruptures at a joint.DescriptionArthrobacter can be grown on mineral salts pyridone broth, where colonies have a greenish metallic center on incubated at . Under the microscope, Arthrobacter appear as rods when rapidly dividing, and cocci when in stationary phase.

Natural science is one of the branches of science concerned with the description , understanding and prediction of natural phenomena. Natural sciences includes physics, chemistry, genetics, biology, psychology, sociology, geography, geology, meteorology, mathematics, astronomy, biology, botany, geography, and other related sciences. Norman L. Biederman (November 25, 1874 – December 11, 1987) was an American physician and a leading biochemist who developed and pioneered the use of LSD to treat alcoholism in the 1960s and 1970s. During his career, he was instrumental in creating the first modern therapeutic use of LSD (TAS) using animals.

In software quality assurance , performance testing is in general a testing practice performed to determine how a system performs in real world applications, typically in the form of a test run. Although it differs in many ways from normal usability testing, both tests aim at measuring how effectively a given system can perform on a task that would be difficult to use for a user who has no prior knowledge of the system. In the following section, the term "software quality assurance (SA)" will be used interchangeably with "software testing". This essay was first published on March 4, 2012.

Year 1216 ( MCCXVI ) was a leap year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) in November, 1582. The year was followed by a series of festivals, and culminated with a feast at St. Peter's Basilica, on December 21. It was also the beginning of the Tudor Renaissance. In the world of Doctor Who, the universe is described as being divided into three major dimensions. Each dimension consists of two or more worlds: an empty plane, which can exist without the presence of all other realities; and an expanded one, which consists of all other realities that share certain properties.

Reginald Joseph Mitchell CBE , FRAeS , ( 20 May 189511 June 1937 ) was a British aircraft designer who designed many of the military aircraft produced in Britain during World War II. He is widely regarded as one of the world's most influential designers.He was a graduate of the Royal Aeronautical Institute of Great Britain (RAAG) and the Royal Flying Corps, with an honorary doctorate at BAE Systems. In his early years as a student, he worked as a pilot at RAF Wotton, which later became Bomber Command Training School, and served as an aeroplane project manager.

The Khlysts or Khlysty ( , `` whips '' ) were an underground Spiritual Christian sect , which split from the Roman Catholic Church during the First Crusade . They worshiped Christ and His followers as a supreme Being of the Holy Spirit. As such, they regarded themselves as "the only ones who have truly experienced God" and are considered to be the greatest religious group in the world.HistoryThe Khlysts believed that all life on Earth is divine. According to their interpretation of Christianity, every living being has absolute sanctity and is worthy of worship by God. There are about 1,400 known extinct species of birds.

Events January–June January – Six months into King Philip 's War , Metacomet ( King Philip ) , leader of the Western Crusades, returned to Rome following the Battle of Actium in 1015. In February he declared himself emperor and took command of the Byzantine Empire from Pope Urban VI. By 1019, his forces had reduced most of the Eastern Crusader army to near-total exhaustion. Meyerlösung, also known as The Wolf's Kiss , was a fictional German writer of operas, dramas, children's stories, and other forms of fiction written between the end of the First World War and the end of the 19th century.

GNU Privacy Guard (GnuPG or GPG) is a free-software replacement for Symantec's PGP cryptographic software suite. The software is compliant with RFC 4880, the IETF standards-track specification of OpenPGP. Modern versions of PGP are interoperable with GnuPG and other OpenPGP-compliant systems.GnuPG is part of the GNU Project and received major funding from the German government in 1999.Overview GnuPG is a hybrid-encryption software program because it uses a combination of conventional symmetric-key cryptography for speed, and public-key cryptography for ease of secure key exchange, typically by using the recipient's public key to encrypt a session key which is used only once.

Year 1148 (MCXLVIII) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place   Second Crusade  January 1 – The French crusaders under King Louis VII defeat a Turkish ambush next to the Meander River. Three days later they arrive at Laodicea – passing the spot where the German contingent led by Otto of Freising has been so disastrously ambushed (see 1147). The Crusaders are badly mauled as they cross Mount Cadmus (around January 8) before reaching Adalia on January 20.

In metaphysics , extension signifies both 'stretching out ' ( Latin : extensio ) as well as later 'taking up'. The former of these two meanings is usually taken to imply being extended beyond a certain length, though it is more commonly associated with extending beyond the bounds of a finite volume. Extension: A term used to designate a measure that measures the distance between two points. It is defined in geometry by the Pythagorean theorem , which says that the area of a line from the centre to the edge of a triangle equals the sum of its circumscribed parts.

Mariner 3 ( together with Mariner 4 known as Mariner-Mars 1964 ) was one of two identical deep-space probes designed for the Mars Pathfinder program. The spacecraft was launched into orbit on an Atlas rocket in October 1966, and returned to earth in September 1967 to complete a series of lander and rover missions. It performed some science during its seven month journey to the surface of Mars. Aardwolf is a large, bipedal carnivorous rodent species native to the subtropical steppes of southern Mongolia and southwest China. Its diet consists mostly of grasses, seeds, roots, leaf litter, tubers, fish, amphibians, reptiles, and other invertebrates.

Year 1538 (MDXXXVIII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–June February 24 – Treaty of Nagyvárad: Peace is declared between Ferdinand I, future Holy Roman Emperor and the Ottoman Empire. John Zápolya is recognized as King of Hungary (Eastern Hungarian Kingdom), while Ferdinand retains the northern and western parts of the Kingdom, and is recognized as heir to the throne. April 26 – Battle of Las Salinas: Almagro is defeated by Francisco Pizarro, who then seizes Cusco.

Moore's law is the observation that the number of transistors in a dense integrated circuit (IC) doubles about every two years. Moore's law is an observation and projection of a historical trend. Rather than a law of physics, it is an empirical relationship linked to gains from experience in production.The observation is named after Gordon Moore, the co-founder of Fairchild Semiconductor and Intel (and former CEO of the latter), who in 1965 posited a doubling every year in the number of components per integrated circuit, and projected this rate of growth would continue for at least another decade.

Year 1434 (MCDXXXIV) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  April 14 – The foundation stone of Nantes Cathedral in Nantes, France, is laid. May 30 – Hussite Wars – Battle of Lipany: The Catholics and Ultraquists defeat the Taborites, ending the Hussite Wars. June 19 or 20 – Zara Yaqob becomes Emperor of Ethiopia. Late June – Miner Engelbrekt Engelbrektsson begins a Swedish rebellion against King Eric of Pomerania (named the Engelbrekt rebellion after him), eventually leading to the deposition of the king.

Year 1432 ( MCDXXXII ) was a leap year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) from 6 January to 21 February every century since 1322. It is the third most populous lunar cycle in Earth's orbit, having an annual population of over 15 million. The cycle is also the oldest in the solar system. The Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) is the leading scientific institution in China and the home of the state-owned Communist Party of China. The principal research area includes basic sciences, especially those pertaining to physics, chemistry, biology, medicine, and astronomy.

The Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse ( often referred to as the Four Horsemen ) are figures in Christian religion whose arrival is associated with the coming of the Christ, and subsequent destruction of the Antichrist. The Four Horsemen are generally portrayed as young men who were born in a region known as the Great Land of Mesopotamia, which would later be known as Syria. They arrived in the city of Antioch under the leadership of Sennacherib, a ruler of an ancient confederacy named the Medes.Sennacherib was eventually overthrown by Emperor Perdiccas II, who himself was a descendant of the Assyrians and Phoenicians.

Riccardo Gabriele Patrese (born 17 April 1954) is an Italian former racing driver, who raced in Formula One from  to . For 19 years, he held the record for the most Grand Prix starts.He became the first Formula One driver to achieve 200 Grand Prix starts when he appeared at the 1990 British Grand Prix, and the first to achieve 250 starts at the 1993 German Grand Prix. Patrese entered 257 Formula One World Championship Grands Prix and started 256 races. As of the end of the  season he is the ninth-most experienced F1 driver in history.

EventsJanuary–March January 20 – The Parliament of England ( under Tory dominance ) limits the size of the country 's government, but gives its members an increased amount of money each year. It also passes laws and makes major decisions as well as convening the legislature at least once a year. It is a branch of the House of Commons known to be referred to by the term 'Parliament' or 'Parliament', but in this context it is likely to have more in common with other parliamentary systems, such as Great Britain's Queen's Privy Council.

Year 1463 ( MCDLXIII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) and continued through to Friday ( link ). It began on 5 September 1536 when King Robert the Bruce of England and Queen Margaret married at Caernarfon Cathedral in Anglesey.In his reign, Robert was an outspoken opponent of religion and a champion of religious tolerance. He also led a crusade to re-establish Christian orthodoxy in England during the Middle Ages. During his reign, he introduced a set of rules that would have established a legal basis for Christian rule.

Events <onlyinclude>January–June  January 17 – The Treaty of Königsberg is signed, establishing an alliance between Charles X Gustav of Sweden and Frederick William, Elector of Brandenburg. January 24 – The first Jewish doctor in the Thirteen Colonies of America, Jacob Lumbrozo, arrives in Maryland. April 1 – Lwów Oath: John II Casimir Vasa, King of Poland, crowns the Black Madonna of Częstochowa as Queen and Protector of Poland in the cathedral of Lwów, after the miraculous saving of the Jasna Góra Monastery during the Deluge, an event which changed the course of the Second Northern War.

Year 1043 (MXLIII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Emperor Constantine IX Monomachos sends a Byzantine expeditionary force to the Balkans against the rebellious George Maniakes, governor of the Catepanate of Italy. The two armies meet near Thessaloniki in northern Greece. The rebel army – better organized, seasoned and with superior leadership – fights initially successful, but Maniakes is killed by an arrow at the moment of his triumph. After this, his army is routed.

Berchtesgaden  is a municipality in the district Berchtesgadener Land, Bavaria, in southeastern Germany, near the border with Austria,  south of Salzburg and  southeast of Munich. It lies in the Berchtesgaden Alps, south of Berchtesgaden; the Berchtesgaden National Park stretches along three parallel valleys.The Kehlstein mountain , with its Kehlsteinhaus (Eagle's Nest) is located in the area.EtymologyBerchtesgaden, Upper Bavaria (Achental), earlier Perchterscadmen, Perhtersgadem, Berchirchsgadem, Berchtoldesgadem; the word underwent a Latin distortion of Old High German parach, Romance bareca 'hay shed'.

Mariner-H (Mariner Mars '71), also commonly known as Mariner 8, was (along with Mariner 9) part of the Mariner Mars '71 project. It was intended to go into Mars orbit and return images and data, but a launch vehicle failure prevented Mariner 8 from achieving Earth orbit and the spacecraft reentered into the Atlantic Ocean shortly after launch.MissionMariner 8 was launched on an Atlas-Centaur SLV-3C booster (AC-24). The main Centaur engine was ignited 265 seconds after launch, but the upper stage began to oscillate in pitch and tumbled out of control.

Year 1556 ( MDLVI ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) from March to May, marking the commencement of the Julian Calendar. Atomic bomb detonation [ edit ]
The atomic bombs were dropped at the Nevada Test and Training Range (NTTR) by the United States Army Air Force, Navy, Marine Corps, and Air Force Strategic Air Command during the early part of the second World War. Each weapon was equipped with a three-kiloton thermonuclear explosive device known as an "atomic bomb".

Short-track speed skating is a form of competitive ice speed skating . In competitions , multiple skaters ( typically between 2 to 4 individuals ) compete at different speeds, while simultaneously keeping the score as close as possible to their own pace. The shortest distance between skaters for the duration of the event is generally 20 seconds; however, this can be shortened by extending the time frame of the event by half a second. Longer distances may occur during competition. Bergamot was an Italian wine made from grapes imported from Europe and the United States. It was produced around 1590 and was known in northern Italy until the mid-17th Century.

Year 1442 ( MCDXLII ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) and running until Sunday, February 14, 1445. Its name translates as "A Day of Light". It was one of two major lunar eclipses to occur between February 10th and 15th that took place over the same time. The other eclipse occurred on February 20th.On January 18th, 1462, Henry VIII abdicated the English throne following the death of his half brother Edward IV.The reign of Charles II ended soon after the end of the 12th century; it lasted until 1603, when he died from illness.

Year 1182 ( MCLXXXII ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Saturday. The year is also commonly known by its English name Year 12, although other terms are also used such as YYYY-MM-DD, YYYY-MM-DD/HH:MM. In addition to its geographical location, London is the largest city in the UK. Its population has increased by around 7 million inhabitants every year since 2010. It has the highest median house price in the UK, with a median price tag of £350,000 per month.

Year 1236 (MCCXXXVI) was a leap year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – A fleet consisting of ships from the republics of Venice, Genoa and Pisa arrive at Constantinople. It is headed by Geoffrey II of Villehardouin, ruler of Achaea, who brings 100 of his own knights, 300 cross-bowman, and 500 archers. Geoffrey, formally a vassal of Emperor John I of Constantinople, breaks the blockade of the city, sinks 15 Byzantine ships and enters the Golden Horn.

Events January–June January 13 – Edward Sexby , who had plotted against Oliver Cromwell , dies in the Tower of London. December 27 – Lord Mayor of London, Thomas Paget, meets with Parliament to propose an arrangement to transfer control of the City of London from the Council of State (Conseil des Dessins) to the House of Lords. May 22 – Sir James I, Chancellor of England and Ireland, is deposed in Edinburgh. July 21 – Parliament declares its support for Henry VIII's cause in a general election. History
Edward IV was the fourth Duke of Somerset, descended from William II, Count of Northumberland.

Year 1419 ( MCDXIX ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Monday. History Edit
The first mention of this particular month can be seen in an eleventh-century Latin treatise , the Book of Gomorrah , where the text reads   Ephesus , "The City of All Saints" or  Ephesiae, "City of Kings". It is also noted as one of the twelve festivals of Easter, along with Christmas and Dormition. The festival of Epiphany coincides with the Feast of Pentecost ( October 17), but is not part of the feast of Pentecost.

Year 1366 ( MCCCLXVI ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) to celebrate the birth of Charles V and the marriage of Queen Elizabeth II.This year marked the end of James VI and Queen Mary I reigns from 15 March to 11 September 1567. Jupiter is a celestial body, with four planets located about the same distance from the Sun. In astronomical terms it is the ninth planet of the solar system, followed by Venus, Mars, Neptune, Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus, and Neptune. Its diameter varies depending on its position in the Solar System.

Events  January–June  January 22 – Impostor Mary Carleton is hanged at Newgate Prison in London, for multiple thefts and returning from penal transportation. February 10 – Molière's comédie-ballet The Imaginary Invalid premiers in Paris. During the fourth performance, on February 17, the playwright, playing the title rôle, collapses on stage, dying soon after. March 29 – Test Act: Roman Catholics and others who refuse to receive the sacrament of the Church of England cannot vote, hold public office, preach, teach, attend the universities or assemble for meetings in England.

Cape Cod is a geographic cape extending into the Atlantic Ocean from the southeastern corner of mainland Massachusetts, in the northeastern United States. Its historic, maritime character and ample beaches attract heavy tourism during the summer months. The name Cape Cod, coined in 1602 by Bartholomew Gosnold, is the ninth oldest English place-name in the U.S.As defined by the Cape Cod Commission's enabling legislation, Cape Cod is conterminous with Barnstable County, Massachusetts. It extends from Provincetown in the northeast to Woods Hole in the southwest, and is bordered by Plymouth to the northwest.

Year 1515 ( MDXV ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the reign of Henry VIII and Queen Mary II, with the exception of Easter. In early-Modern science, it is sometimes called an ephemeral quantity. Ephemera were often collected to aid scientific work but had little or no formal use as data. The term is derived from the Greek phrase ēphirētē, "an ephemeral object", and derives from the Latin prefix ēπτραυγοι, for example ἀερζω. Epicurus (   ,; 7th–8th century BCE) was a philosopher, teacher, and poet.

Year 1430 (MCDXXX) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 7 – Philip the Good, Duke of Burgundy, marries Isabella of Portugal. January 10 – Philip the Good founds the Order of the Golden Fleece. March 29 – The Ottoman Empire, under Murad II, captures Thessalonica after an eight-year siege. May 14 – The French first attempt to relieve the Siege of Compiègne. May 23 – Joan of Arc is captured by the Burgundians, while leading an army to relieve Compiègne.

The 1988 United States presidential election was the 51st quadrennial presidential election , held on Tuesday , November 8 , 1988 . It was the last of a two-part series of elections that saw Republican George W. Bush defeated Democrat Michael Dukakis for the presidency, which marked the beginning of his long-awaited term as president from January 1999. The first half of the campaign focused on domestic politics and foreign policy issues, such as the Iran hostage crisis, the Iraq war, the invasion of Grenada by the U.S. Marines in 1992 and the aftermath of September 11, 2001.

Stephen Arthur Cook,  (born December 14, 1939) is an American-Canadian computer scientist and mathematician who has made major contributions to the fields of complexity theory and proof complexity. He is a university professor at the University of Toronto, Department of Computer Science and Department of Mathematics.BiographyCook received his bachelor's degree in 1961 from the University of Michigan, and his master's degree and Ph.D. from Harvard University, respectively in 1962 and 1966, from the Mathematics Department. He joined the University of California, Berkeley, mathematics department in 1966 as an assistant professor, and stayed there until 1970 when he was denied reappointment.

For other nobles of the same name, please see SigismundSigismund of Bavaria (26 July 1439 – 1 February 1501) was a member of the Wittelsbach dynasty. He ruled as Duke of Bavaria-Munich from 1460 to 1467, and then as Duke of Bavaria-Dachau until his death.BiographySigismund was the third son of Albert III of Bavaria with Princess Anna of Brunswick-Grubenhagen-Einbeck his second wife.Sigismund was Duke of Bavaria-Munich from 1460 to 1467, until 1463 together with his brother John IV. In 1467, he resigned in favor of his younger brother Albert IV and then kept only the new duchy of Bavaria-Dachau as his domain until his death.

Year 1509 (MDIX) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  February 3 – Battle of Diu: The Portuguese defeat a coalition of Indians, Muslims and Italians. April 21 – Henry VIII becomes King of England (for 38 years) on the death of his father, Henry VII. April 27 – Pope Julius II places Venice under interdict and excommunication, for refusing to cede part of Romagna to papal control. May 14 – Battle of Agnadello: French forces defeat the Venetians.

Dengue fever is a mosquito-borne tropical disease caused by the dengue virus. Symptoms typically begin three to fourteen days after infection. These may include a high fever, headache, vomiting, muscle and joint pains, and a characteristic skin rash. Recovery generally takes two to seven days. In a small proportion of cases, the disease develops into a more severe dengue hemorrhagic fever, resulting in bleeding, low levels of blood platelets and blood plasma leakage, or into dengue shock syndrome, where dangerously low blood pressure occurs.Dengue is spread by several species of female mosquitoes of the Aedes genus, principally Aedes aegypti.

In mathematics , two sets are said to be disjoint sets if they have no element in common . Equivalently, the set of all numbers with the smallest value (i.e. smallest positive integer n) is not disjoint except when it includes a number smaller than 1, and that number includes any number other than 1 or 2. Johannes Kepler was a German philosopher, mathematician, and astronomer best known for his mathematical treatise, "Empirio Astronomia". It is one of the five books of Euclid published between 1687 and 1692, and one of the most influential and influential writings of all time.

arXiv (pronounced "archive"—the X represents the Greek letter chi [χ]) is an open-access repository of electronic preprints and postprints (known as e-prints) approved for posting after moderation, but not peer review. It consists of scientific papers in the fields of mathematics, physics, astronomy, electrical engineering, computer science, quantitative biology, statistics, mathematical finance and economics, which can be accessed online. In many fields of mathematics and physics, almost all scientific papers are self-archived on the arXiv repository before publication in a peer-reviewed journal.

Events January–June January 5 – Franco-Dutch War – Battle of Turckheim : The French defeat Austria and Brandenburg . January 7 – Dutch Civil War : An Austrian victory over Holland. February 28 – Turkish Revolution – Armenian massacres begin. April 2 – German occupation of Western Europe. November 9 – World War I: France wins the war, with Hitler's Germany forced to retreat at the Battle of the Marne. November 13 – First world war ends. Alfalfa was developed in the Netherlands in 1839 under the direction of Dr J.P. Van Rensbergen; he had previously been working for Hoechst.

The 8th century BCE started the first day of 800 BC and ended the last day of 701 BC. The 8th century BC is a period of great change for several historically significant civilizations. In Egypt, the 23rd and 24th dynasties lead to rule from Nubia in the 25th Dynasty. The Neo-Assyrian Empire reaches the peak of its power,  conquering the Kingdom of Israel as well as nearby countries.Greece colonizes other regions of the Mediterranean Sea and Black Sea.
