Rome is founded in 753 BC, and the Etruscan civilization expands in Italy.

As of March 1 (O.S. February 19), where then Julian calendar acknowledged a leap day and the Gregorian calendar did not, the Julian calendar fell one day further behind, bringing the difference to 11 days until February 28 (O.S. February 17), 1800.In Sweden, the year started in the Julian calendar and remained so until February 28. Then, by skipping the leap day, the Swedish calendar was introduced, letting February 28 be followed by March 1, giving the entire year the same pattern as a common year starting on Monday.

The picometre (international spelling as used by the International Bureau of Weights and Measures; SI symbol: pm) or picometer (American spelling) is a unit of length in the metric system, equal to , or one trillionth  of a metre, which is the SI base unit of length.The picometre is one thousandth of a nanometre ( nm), one millionth of a micrometre (also known as a micron), one billionth of a millimetre, and one trillionth of a metre. The symbol μμ was once used for it.

Adrian of Nicomedia ( also known as Hadrian ) or Saint Adrian ( , died 4 March 306 ) was an African bishop of the Byzantine Empire. A contemporary of Cyril of Alexandria and his successor, Athanasius I, he was regarded as the founder of what became known as the Council of Nicaea, where he was elected Bishop of Antioch. Abdallah ibn Muhammad al-Zuhri  ( سامنز أدر) was a Syrian Arab ruler and general in the Second Caliphate of Islam who fought for the establishment of the Abbasid caliphate in the 7th century AD.

Year 1490 (MCDXC) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 4 – Anne of Brittany announces that all those who ally themselves with the king of France will be considered guilty of the crime of Lèse-majesté. March 13 – Charles II becomes Duke of Savoy at age 1; his mother Blanche of Montferrato is regent. March or April – 1490 Ch'ing-yang event, a presumed meteor shower or air burst over Qingyang in Ming dynasty China, said to have caused casualties.

Blum Blum Shub (B.B.S.) is a pseudorandom number generator proposed in 1986 by Lenore Blum, Manuel Blum and Michael Shub that is derived from Michael O. Rabin's one-way function.Blum Blum Shub takes the form,where M = pq is the product of two large primes p and q. Albert III  (9 November 141411 March 1486) was Elector of Brandenburg from 1471 until his death, the third from the House of Hohenzollern. A member of the Order of the Swan, he received the cognomen Achilles  because of his knightly qualities and virtues. He also ruled in the Franconian principalities of Ansbach from 1440 and Kulmbach from 1464 (as Albrecht I).BiographyEarly lifeAlbert was born at the Brandenburg residence of Tangermünde as the third son of the Nuremberg burgrave Frederick I and his wife, the Wittelsbach princess Elisabeth of Bavaria-Landshut.

Year 1558 (MDLVIII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar, the 1558th year of the Common Era (CE) and Anno Domini (AD) designations, the 558th year of the 2nd millennium, the 58th year of the 16th century, and the 9th year of the 1550s decade.Events  January–June  January 7 – French troops, led by Francis, Duke of Guise, take Calais, the last continental possession of the Kingdom of England. January 9 – Geneva becomes independent from the Canton of Bern.

Frederick Barbarossa (1122 – 10 June 1190), also known as Frederick I , was the Holy Roman Emperor from 1155 until his death 35 years later. He was elected King of Germany at Frankfurt on 4 March 1152 and crowned in Aachen on 9 March 1152. He was crowned King of Italy on 24 April 1155 in Pavia and emperor by Pope Adrian IV on 18 June 1155 in Rome. Two years later, the term  ("holy") first appeared in a document in connection with his empire. He was later formally crowned King of Burgundy, at Arles on 30 June 1178.

Jon Howard Appleton ( January 4 , 1939 – January 30 , 2022 ) was an American composer , an accomplished pianist and a music theorist. He is regarded as the most influential of contemporary composers, having written numerous pieces for such musical genres as jazz, rock and pop, folk, gospel and R&B, and he became a major cultural icon when he was awarded the Grammy Award in 2002 for Best Original Score for his score to Shakespeare's Richard III. The son of two English teachers from a German Jewish family, Howard began his musical career at the age of ten.

Year 1373 (MCCCLXXIII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 24 – The Treaty of Santarém is signed between Ferdinand I of Portugal and Henry II of Castile, ending the second war between the two countries. April 28 – Hundred Years' War: The French re-capture most of Brittany from the English, but are unable to take Brest. May 13 – English anchoress Dame Julian of Norwich receives the sixteen Revelations of Divine Love. June 16 – The Anglo-Portuguese Treaty is signed in London, and is the oldest active treaty in the world.

The Mattachine Society , founded in 1950 , was an early national gay rights organization in the United States , with members from many areas of the population. It advocated for the full employment and social acceptance of gays and lesbians as members of the public, a policy that continues to this day. The founding committee was made up of four openly gay men, who met together on the second floor of New York City's Stonewall Inn . The group became one of the most prominent and visible gay rights groups in the country.

Epicureanism is a system of philosophy founded around 307 BC based upon the teachings of the ancient Greek philosopher Epicurus. It teaches that existence exists as a physical reality outside the human mind and has a rational explanation, in contrast to the view held by other philosophers who hold that existence is non-rational. The Epicureans deny that there are any ultimate principles that can account for our existence, however they believe that reason should give us more answers than we can put up with on our own.The term itself has been used to describe various philosophical philosophies since the time of the Enlightenment, though its precise meaning was unknown prior to that.

Year 1310 (MCCCX) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December  January –  Forces of the Kingdom of Castile retreat from the Siege of Algeciras, after enduring severe losses, and secure a peace treaty. March – Muhammed III, former Sultan of the Emirate of Granada, is blinded and found dead in a pool, after an attempted coup to retake his throne from his brother Nasr. May 11 – In France, 54 members of the Knights Templar are burned at the stake for heresy.Date unknown  Abu al-Fida becomes governor of Hama.

Winter sports or winter activities are competitive sports or non-competitive recreational activities which are played on snow or ice . Some of these sports include: skating (in the winter, including skiing and snowboarding); snowboarding (all year round); mountain biking; ski touring; snowmobiling; air sport; cross-country skiing; snowmobile racing. Sports in Canada are typically governed by an association called the National Sport Association of Canada (NASAC) or the Canadian Winter Sports Association (CWSA), which is made up primarily of athletes who have participated in these types of sports.

Year 1029 ( MXXIX ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the early Byzantine Republic. It was one of the first three major Christian festivals, as it commemorated the birth of Saint Peter and marked the start of his second reign. The festival was observed from January to April. According to the Latin calendar, MXXIX is the ninth of its kind, ending at 12 December 2015. There are no other known ical calendars that begin with MXXIX.The Greek calendar begins with the  month  , which ends with the ֹ.

The Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse (often referred to as the Four Horsemen) are figures in Christian religion, first appearing in the Old Testament's prophetic Book of Zechariah and in the Book of Ezekiel, where they are named as punishments from God, and later in the New Testament's final book, Revelation, an apocalypse written by John of Patmos.Revelation 6 tells of a book or scroll in God's right hand that is sealed with seven seals. The Lamb of God/Lion of Judah opens the first four of the seven seals, which summons four beings that ride out on white, red, black, and pale horses.

In software quality assurance, performance testing is in general a testing practice performed to determine how a system performs in terms of responsiveness and stability under a particular workload. It can also serve to investigate, measure, validate or verify other quality attributes of the system, such as scalability, reliability and resource usage.Performance testing, a subset of performance engineering, is a computer science practice which strives to build performance standards into the implementation, design and architecture of a system.Testing typesLoad testing Load testing is the simplest form of performance testing. A load test is usually conducted to understand the behavior of the system under a specific expected load.

Adnams is a regional brewery founded in 1872 in Southwold, Suffolk, England, by George and Ernest Adnams. It produces cask ale and pasteurised bottled beers. Escherichia coli , also known as E. coli , is a Gram-negative, facultative anaerobic, rod-shaped, coliform bacterium of the genus Escherichia that is commonly found in the lower intestine of warm-blooded organisms. Most E. coli strains are harmless, but some serotypes (EPEC, ETEC etc.) can cause serious food poisoning in their hosts, and are occasionally responsible for food contamination incidents that prompt product recalls. The harmless strains are part of the normal microbiota of the gut, and can benefit their hosts by producing vitamin K2, and preventing colonisation of the intestine with pathogenic bacteria, having a mutualistic relationship.

The Witan, literally "wise men", was the king's council in Anglo-Saxon England from before the seventh century until the 11th century. Its primary function was to advise the king on subjects such as promulgation of laws, judicial judgments, approval of charters transferring land, settlement of disputes, election of archbishops and bishops and other matters of major national importance. Hide-and-seek is a popular children 's game in which at least two players ( usually at least three ) conceal themselves and hide in plain sight under objects or surfaces. In art history, literature and cultural studies, Orientalism is the imitation or depiction of aspects in the Eastern world. A trisomy is a type of polysomy in which there are three instances of a particular chromosome , instead of the usual two. The term is derived from the fact that it's often difficult to determine if an X-linked trisomy is due to environmental factors or genetic factors. A Roman villa was typically a farmhouse or country house built in the Roman Republic and the Roman Empire , usually with its own garden. A semi-automatic rifle is an autoloading rifle that fires one round each pull of the trigger. A noble savage is a literary stock character who embodies the concept of the indigene, outsider, wild human, an "other" who has not been "corrupted" by civilization, and therefore symbolizes humanity's innate goodness. The original design, in the Byzantine Revival and Romanesque Revival styles, began construction in 1892.

Algebraic topology is a branch of mathematics that uses tools from abstract algebra to study topological spaces . The basic idea is to define a space such that all the fields are connected by an arrow. These fields include the elements of the set and each other, and are called "fields" of the space.Topology (in its full sense) is a branch of algebra. It is concerned with the study of the natural order of sets. It is also used in other areas where algebra is concerned, such as geometry and probability theory, and it is the main subject of courses in many undergraduate departments.

Bdellovibrio is a genus of Gram-negative , obligate aerobic bacterium . One of the more notable characteristics of this genus is that it belongs to the Brachiopoda subfamily. Year 1033 ( MXXXIII ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) in Western Europe. In its early stages, it was sometimes used as an annual holiday of choice among Europeans and Roman emperors, though it may not have been formally observed for over one hundred years. Many countries had their own calendars, but most of those were later supplanted by Gregorian calendars. A list of the main calendars can be found at this link. Larousse de Bouillon (  , ; 9 July 1804 – 13 April 1870) was a French mathematician and poet, best known for his book Mémorologie .

Jacques René Chirac ( , , ; 29 November 193226 September 2019 ) was a French politician who served as president of France from 1975 to 1980. He represented the Parti Républicain until his resignation in 1970.Rémy Cazeneuve ( , ; 14 December 1874 – 19 January 1900), nicknamed "The Doctor", was a French doctor of medicine who lived in Geneva, Switzerland and died in 1880 after a short illness. He was best known for his work with the young Marie Curie, which led to the development of modern medicine.

Jon Howard Appleton (January 4, 1939 – January 30, 2022) was an American composer, an educator and a pioneer in electro-acoustic music. His earliest compositions in the medium, e.g. "Chef d'Oeuvre" and "Newark Airport Rock" (1967) attracted attention because they established a new tradition some have called programmatic electronic music. In 1970, he won Guggenheim, Fulbright and American-Scandinavian Foundation fellowships. When he was twenty-eight years old, he joined the faculty of Dartmouth College where he established one of the first electronic music studios in the United States.

Abolitionism, or the abolitionist movement, was the movement to end slavery. In Western Europe and the Americas, abolitionism was a historic movement that sought to end the Atlantic slave trade and liberate the enslaved people.The British abolitionist movement started in the late 18th century when English and American Quakers began to question the morality of slavery. James Oglethorpe was among the first to articulate the Enlightenment case against slavery, banning it in the Province of Georgia on humanitarian grounds, and arguing against it in Parliament, and eventually encouraging his friends Granville Sharp and Hannah More to vigorously pursue the cause.

An oak is a tree or shrub in the genus Quercus (; Latin "oak tree") of the beech family, Fagaceae. There are approximately 500 extant species of oaks. The common name "oak" also appears in the names of species in related genera, notably Lithocarpus (stone oaks), as well as in those of unrelated species such as Grevillea robusta (silky oaks) and the Casuarinaceae (she-oaks). The genus Quercus is native to the Northern Hemisphere, and includes deciduous and evergreen species extending from cool temperate to tropical latitudes in the Americas, Asia, Europe, and North Africa.

Events  March 18 – Jacques de Molay, the 23rd and last Grand Master of the Knights Templar, is burned at the stake in Paris, France. April 4 – Exeter College, Oxford is founded in England by Walter de Stapledon, Bishop of Exeter. June 24 – Battle of Bannockburn: Scottish forces led by Robert the Bruce defeat Edward II of England, regaining Scotland's independence. August 31 – King Haakon V of Norway moves his capital from Bergen to Oslo, where he builds Akershus Fortress, from which Norway is ruled for the next 500 years.

1581 ( MDLXXXI ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Roman Republic. It is a secular holiday, celebrated by the citizens of Rome to mark the birthdays of several prominent Romans. It commemorates the death of Emperor Marcus Licinius Marcellus Augustus and other important Roman figures. It has been known since ancient times as a pagan celebration; however, in practice it changed to a Christian one during the first centuries of Christianity. The Imperial House of Habsburg was an absolute monarchy that held sway over Germany until 1801, at which time its rule was dissolved by the Bavarian-Prussian War.

Stephen Arthur Cook , ( born December 14 , 1939 ) is an American-Canadian computer scientist and mathematician who has become known as one of the leading pioneers of the field of computer programming. Born to a working-class family in Winnipeg, he was raised in a close-knit Jewish-German Catholic family. As a young man, he studied at McGill University's School of Computer Science. He then joined IBM where he became one of two members of IBM's supercomputer division before being recruited by Intel Corporation to head a research team that developed the architecture for the personal computer (PC).

Events  January–June  January–March – Archangelsk is founded as New Kholmogory in northern Russia, by Ivan the Terrible. January 11 – Sir Walter Mildmay is given a royal licence to found Emmanuel College, Cambridge. March 18 (N.S. March 28) – Ivan the Terrible, ruler of Russia since 1533, dies; he is succeeded as Tsar by his son, Feodor. May 17 – The conflict between Toyotomi Hideyoshi and Tokugawa Ieyasu culminates in the Battle of Nagakute. June 1 – With the death of the Duc d'Anjou, the Huguenot Henry of Navarre becomes heir-presumptive to the throne of France.

Events January–March January 24 – At least 75 residents of what is now York , Maine , United States , were killed in a fire that broke out in a coal mine. The explosion destroyed an industrial plant, killing 44 people and injuring more than 700. A second incident, later claimed to have been perpetrated by another group of workers, also left 46 people dead and injured almost 400. Although the causes of the fire cannot be traced, investigators conclude it began when a pile of loose coal on the roof of a gas station exploded, sending flames flying through the building.

Year 1201 (MCCI) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  July 31 – John Komnenos the Fat, a Byzantine aristocrat, attempts to usurp the imperial throne; he is proclaimed emperor and crowned by Patriarch John X Kamateros, at Constantinople. Meanwhile, Emperor Alexios III Angelos, who resides in the Palace of Blachernae, dispatches a small force under Alexios Palaiologos, Alexios' son-in-law, who is regarded as his heir-apparent. With support of the Varangian Guard, John is overthrown and decapitated by the end of the day.

Year 1047 (MXLVII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  September 25–28 – Rebel general Leo Tornikios (a nephew of Emperor Constantine IX) proclaims himself emperor at Adrianople, and besieges Constantinople. Byzantine troops personally led by Constantine repel him, and re-occupy the walls. Tornikios is forced to withdraw, while his followers start to abandon him. Finally, he is captured at a church in Boulgarophygon (modern Turkey), and is publicly blinded.

The sousaphone is a brass instrument in the same family as the more widely known tuba . Created around 1893, it has long been used as a portable musical instrument but has since been largely superseded by its more modern cousin the trombone for its versatility. Sousaphones are made from wood with steel strings. Suspicious Behavior ( スペシャル ファービジュア , Ōscaru Nā Biyū ): A type of "behavior" that may or may not violate a human's personal boundaries. In this manner, a person may become suspicious of their actions and decide to act upon them, regardless of whether these actions would be morally correct or not.

Year 1161 ( MCLXI ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending at sundown each day from 11 October 2012 until 31 January 2014. The year would consist of seven Saturdays between 11 October 2012 and 1 January 2014 (including the Easter holiday in that period) and four Sundays between 29 October 2012 and 3 January 2014. There was one Sunday per lunar month. Lunar calendar is a series of days, weeks, months and solstices arranged in a circle around a central fixed sun which marks the equinox of the vernal equinoctial reference system.

Year 1513 (MDXIII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  March 9 – Pope Leo X (layman Giovanni di Lorenzo de' Medici) succeeds Pope Julius II, as the 217th pope, despite a strong challenge by Hungarian cardinal Tamás Bakócz. March 27 – Juan Ponce de León becomes the first European definitely known to sight Florida, mistaking it for another island. April 2 – Juan Ponce de León and his expedition become the first Europeans known to visit Florida, landing somewhere on the east coast.

Events  January–June  January 8 – The Jesuit educational plan, known as the Ratio Studiorum, is issued. March 12 – Robert Devereux, 2nd Earl of Essex, is appointed Lord Lieutenant of Ireland, by Queen Elizabeth I of England. April 23 – The Earl of Essex arrives in Dublin at the head of 16,000 troops, the largest army ever seen in Ireland. May 16 – The Kalmar Bloodbath takes place in Kalmar, Sweden. May 29 – Essex takes Cahir Castle, supposedly the strongest in Ireland, after a short siege. June 20 – The Synod of Diamper is convened.

Events January–June January 14 – Portuguese Restoration War – Battle of the Lines of Elvas : The Portuguese beat the Romans at Ostia , and recaptured Constantinople in November. January 31st is an Easter Sunday celebrated throughout the Orthodox Church, though this is only one part of a liturgical year. It occurs when Christians celebrate Pentecost on the first full moon after Easter. It takes place on Friday before the Nativity of Jesus, although there are still several churches commemorating the Savior's birth on such a day. It is believed that it begins at 10:30 AM and continues until 11:40 AM.

Wellfleet is a town in Barnstable County , Massachusetts , United States , and is located halfway between the ``Long Bay'' and the ``Binghamton'' metropolitan regions of Boston. It is approximately 3,000 km northeast of the city of Boston and 1,100 km southwest of New York City. The town's population is approximately 30,000, while its gross metropolitan area is estimated at 22,600 square kilometers. History History [ edit ]
The town was established in 1805 by the Wampanoag tribe to protect their hunting grounds and trade routes along the Narragansett Gulf.

Photomontage is the process and the result of making a composite photograph by cutting, gluing, rearranging and overlapping two or more photographs into a new image. Sometimes the resulting composite image is photographed so that the final image may appear as a seamless physical print. A similar method, although one that does not use film, is realized today through image-editing software. This latter technique is referred to by professionals as "compositing", and in casual usage is often called "photoshopping" (from the name of the popular software system).

Prince Igor is an opera in four acts with a prologue , written and composed by Alexander Borodin . The piece was performed in Russia in the 19th Century and received wide acclaim from both the public and Russian critics.The first few lines are as follows:"A boy's heart beats through his fingers. In his dreams it sings to him, says he: 'I will live; I will die. 'In his dream this same boy walks along the street with his brother. When he falls into a ditch he shouts: 'Come on, go ahead of me!'

Year 1165 ( MCLXV ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the reign of Pope Gregory IX. It was held at the end of Lent, from 30 September to 3 October. During this month, Christians were invited to visit St. Mark's Square and to celebrate the Resurrection of Jesus.The year was also celebrated as the feast of Saint John Paul II, who was canonized on 22 January, 2001.According to the Latin calendar, MCLXV falls on 24 March and coincides with the Feast of Corpus Christi in the West Indies.

Microware was a US corporation based in Clive , Iowa that produced the OS-9 real-time operating system.Microware Systems Corporation existed from 1977 until its dissolution in 1998, when Microware's name was changed and acquired by Sierra Microsystems.Microware software was designed primarily for the IBM Model M personal computer (1970–1984) and was marketed in the US and other developed markets worldwide.During the 1990s, Microware products began to be targeted at the low-market segment of the Mac market. The Canadian Space Agency (CSA), is the federal agency for space development in Canada, charged with promoting Canada's national security interests within the country.

Ross Powers (born February 10, 1979) is an American world champion halfpipe snowboarder from South Londonderry, Vermont, director of the snowboarding program at the Stratton Mountain School in Stratton, Vermont and a philanthropist.CareerThough he originally rode at Stratton Mountain, Vermont, his home mountain is now Okemo, Vermont. Powers helps with the design of the Superpipe and also helped design the RossCross Family Terrain Park. Powers also runs a snowboard camp through Okemo. He led the U.S. sweep in the 2002 Winter Olympics men's halfpipe competition, one day after his 23rd birthday.

Margaret (, ; March or April 1283 – September 1290), known as the Maid of Norway, was the queen-designate of Scotland from 1286 until her death. As she was never inaugurated, her status as monarch is uncertain and has been debated by historians.Margaret was the daughter of King Eric II of Norway and Margaret of Scotland. By the end of the reign of her maternal grandfather, King Alexander III of Scotland, she was his only surviving descendant and recognized heir presumptive. Alexander III died in 1286, his posthumous child was stillborn, and Margaret inherited the crown.

The transport in Azerbaijan involves air traffic, waterways and railroads. All transportation services in Azerbaijan except for oil and gas pipelines are regulated by the Ministry of Transportation of Azerbaijan Republic. For Soviet transportation, see Transport in the Soviet Union.RailwaysThere are  of rail tracks out of which only  are in common carrier service and  are industrial lines. Total:  (2013)Country comparison to the world: 59Broad gauge:  gaugeRailway links with adjacent countriesTimelineMetro System Currently, the only metro system in Azerbaijan is the Baku Metro, located in Baku, the country's capital.New plans to open metro systems in the most populated and developed cities of Azerbaijan were unveiled.

Year 1233 (MCCXXXIII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  War of the Lombards: Lombard forces at Kyrenia surrender to John of Beirut, after a 10-month siege. The defenders, with their personal belongings, are allowed to retire to Tyre. Prisoners captured, are exchanged for those held by Richard Filangieri, commander of the Lombards, at Tyre. Cyprus is wholly restored under the rule of the 16-year-old King Henry I (the Fat). His vassals are rewarded, and loans that they have made are repaid.

Year 1145 (MCXLV) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Levant  Spring – Seljuk forces led by Imad al-Din Zengi capture Saruj, the second great Crusader fortress east of the Euphrates. They advance to Birejik and besiege the city, but the garrison puts up a stiff resistance. Meanwhile, Queen-Regent Melisende of Jerusalem joins forces with Joscelin II, count of Edessa and approaches the city. Zengi raises the siege after hearing rumours of trouble in Mosul. He rushes back with his army to take control.

Prince Igor  is an opera in four acts with a prologue, written and composed by Alexander Borodin. The composer adapted the libretto from the Ancient Russian epic The Lay of Igor's Host, which recounts the campaign of Rus' prince Igor Svyatoslavich against the invading Cuman ("Polovtsian") tribes in 1185. He also incorporated material drawn from two medieval Kievan chronicles. The opera was left unfinished upon the composer's death in 1887 and was edited and completed by Nikolai Rimsky-Korsakov and Alexander Glazunov. It was first performed in St. Petersburg, Russia, in 1890.

Photomontage is the process and the result of making a composite photograph by cutting , gluing , rearranging and overlapping parts of an original image.Composites make up the largest form of digital imaging on film, and they are among the world's most valuable assets. It is widely seen as a technological leap forward in terms of technical accuracy, cost and versatility, while it has been hailed by many as the future of photography.Compositions are generally taken at one or more cameras that can be connected with each other through high speed optical fibre cables.

Vanity Fair is an English novel by William Makepeace Thackeray, which follows the lives of Becky Sharp and Amelia Sedley amid their friends and families during and after the Napoleonic Wars. It was first published as a 19-volume monthly serial from 1847 to 1848, carrying the subtitle Pen and Pencil Sketches of English Society, which reflects both its satirisation of early 19th-century British society and the many illustrations drawn by Thackeray to accompany the text. It was published as a single volume in 1848 with the subtitle A Novel without a Hero, reflecting Thackeray's interest in deconstructing his era's conventions regarding literary heroism.

Aloysius Lilius (c. 1510 – 1576), also variously referred to as Luigi Lilio, Luigi Giglio, was an Italian doctor, astronomer, philosopher and chronologist, and also the "primary author" who provided the proposal that (after modifications) became the basis of the Gregorian Calendar reform of 1582.The crater Lilius on the Moon is named after him, as is the asteroid 2346 Lilio. In computer science, the Lilian date is the number of days since the adoption of the Gregorian calendar on 15 October 1582.Life and workNot much is known about the early life of Lilius/Lilio/Giglio.

Year 1377 ( MCCCLXXVII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) from September 29, 1357 to August 3, 1378 in the Netherlands. It was considered the beginning of the Hundred Years' War because it marked the death of the Dutch King Richard I and the end of the reign of Henry VIII of England. Eddie Hall was born around 1517 into an English noble family. In 1708 his mother died when Eddie was twelve months pregnant with his brother Edward, who later became Earl of Somerset.

Year 1132 (MCXXXII) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Levant  Summer – Imad al-Din Zengi, Seljuk governor (atabeg) of Aleppo and Mosul, marches on Baghdad (the capital of the Abbasid Caliphate) to add it to his dominions. He is defeated by the forces of Caliph Al-Mustarshid near Tikrit (modern Iraq). Zengi flees and escapes with help of Tikrit's governor Najm ad-Din Ayyub (the father of Saladin) who conveys him across the River Tigris.

Year 1219 ( MCCXIX ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Monday ( link will not display dates from 1869 to 1900 ). This year began on July 4, 1874, and finished on March 31, 1897. In English, "monumental" is defined as "the sum or sum of an area or series of parts, in order of greater importance than all its parts, and containing more or less elevation". The meaning of this expression has varied widely throughout the years.

Year 1378 (MCCCLXXVIII) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January – Charles IV, Holy Roman Emperor, visits his nephew Charles V of France in Paris, to celebrate publicly the friendship between their two nations. January 13 – Balša II succeeds his brother, Durađ I, as ruler of Lower Zeta (modern-day Montenegro). March – In England, John Wycliffe tries to promote his ideas for Catholic reform by laying his theses before Parliament, and making them public in a tract.

John Bunyan (; baptised 30 November 162831 August 1688) was an English writer and Puritan preacher best remembered as the author of the Christian allegory The Pilgrim's Progress, which also became an influential literary model. In addition to The Pilgrim's Progress, Bunyan wrote nearly sixty titles, many of them expanded sermons.Bunyan came from the village of Elstow, near Bedford. He had some schooling and at the age of sixteen joined the Parliamentary Army during the first stage of the English Civil War. After three years in the  army he returned to Elstow and took up the trade of tinker, which he had learned from his father.

The Roman conquest of Britain was a process that consisted of the conquest of territory located on the island of Britain from the Goths, a people with whom the Huns were at war in the 7th/8th century. The British Empire then included all the areas occupied by the Huns (from the western shore of Lake Erech to the north west corner of the River Thames). Bartolomeo Bonaparte is a former Emperor of Spain and King of Naples. A member of the House of Martel, Bonaparte's great-grandfather was the Duke of Lorraine.

A business plan is a formal written document containing the goals of a business , the methods for attaining those goals and how these are to be met, including cost savings.The process of writing a business plan typically begins with an outline, which identifies objectives that must be addressed by the company during the following six-year period. If the goal is achieved, the plan will then describe the steps (such as hiring, purchasing, improving technology or operations) to complete the goal.Business plans are usually designed to be self-explanatory, even when they contain numerous subplots that provide additional context and explanation.

Year 1270 (MCCLXX) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar, the 1270th year of the Common Era (CE) and Anno Domini (AD) designations, the 270th year of the 2nd millennium, the 70th year of the 13th century, and the 1st year of the 1270s decade.Events  Africa  The Eighth Crusade Before August – King Louis IX of France launches the Eighth Crusade, in an attempt to recapture the Crusader States from the Mamluk sultan Baibars; the opening engagement is a siege of Tunis.

In the Swedish calendar it was a leap year starting on Wednesday, one day ahead of the Julian and ten days behind the Gregorian calendar.Events  January–June  January 1 – Charles XII of Sweden invades Russia, by crossing the frozen Vistula River with 40,000 men. January 12 – Shahu I becomes the fifth Chhatrapati of the Maratha Empire in the Indian subcontinent. February 26 – HMS Falmouth, a 50-gun fourth-rate ship of the line built at Woolwich Dockyard for the Royal Navy, is launched. March 11 – Queen Anne withholds Royal Assent from the Scottish Militia Bill, the last time a British monarch vetoes legislation.

Year 1024 (MXXIV) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Emperor Basil II prepares a Byzantine expedition to invade Sicily. Governor Ahmed al-Akhal appeals to the Zirids of Ifriqiya for help. They dispatch a fleet, but these are caught up in a storm and destroyed near Pantelleria. Battle of Lemnos:  Kievan Viking raiders (800 men) sail through the straits at Abydos to the Aegean Sea. From there they make for the island of Lemnos, but are defeated by a Byzantine fleet of the Cibyrrhaeot Theme.

Year 1391 ( MCCCXCI ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display full calendar ) of the Roman Catholic calendar.It was the sixth and last year of the Western Empire in the Western Christian Church, after A.D. 1087, when the Apostolic Lateran Council (AD 1077) decreed the canonisation of Pope Innocent I. He was succeeded by Benedict IX, whose reign is usually commemorated as the Fourth Ecumenical Council. Heinlein (  ,  ) was an American physicist, best known for his work on quantum mechanics. He was elected president of Yale University from 1966 to 1968.

Year 1250 ( MCCL ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending Sunday, December 21 , in the Carolingian Empire. It is widely regarded as the oldest civil calendar in antiquity.This year had three phases: the "old-year", the "pregnant" and the "nun". The new-year cycle lasted from January 1st to August 31st. Each year began with the celebration of the Feast of St. John the Baptist, and ends with a major feast known as the Liturgy of the Annunciation.

Year 1210 (MCCX) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  May – The Second Parliament of Ravennika, convened by Emperor Henry of Flanders, is held in the town of Ravennika in Central Greece, in order to resolve the differences between the princes of Frankish Greece, and the Roman Catholic clergy of their domains. The assembled nobles and prelates conclude a concordat, which recognizes the independence and immunity of all Church property in Frankish Greece from any feudal duties.

Year 1023 (MXXIII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  The Judge-Governor of Seville in Al-Andalus (modern Spain) takes advantage of the disintegration of the Caliphate of Córdoba and seizes power as Abbad I, founding the Abbadid dynasty. December – Abbad I declares the Taifa of Seville independent from Córdoban rule. Abd ar-Rahman V is proclaimed Caliph at Córdoba. Asia  April – An epidemic in Kyoto (Japan) is so severe that there are corpses in the streets; disease spreads throughout the country.

Year 1295 ( MCCXCV ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Monday. It was followed by Easter Sunday, called in English "the Easter of St. Mark". On 20 June 2015, President Xi Jinping of China celebrated his birthday as the fourth head of state to reach that milestone.Xi was born on 28 July 1924 in the city of Dalian, Zhejiang province, but spent most of his childhood there before immigrating to Szechuan Province with his mother in 1937. He had five brothers and four sisters.

Events June 16 – The deposed and imprisoned Mary , Queen of Scots , recognizes Philip II of Spain as the legitimate sovereign of Holy Rome. January 28–March 30, 1709–The British Parliament approves a Bill establishing the "Free Trade Union of England and Wales" in its first session . October 19–December 18, 1796–The Treaty of Havana between France and the United States of America states that the American Revolutionary War was an "invasion of Cuba". April 4–April 5, 1825–On the Fourth of July, a group of Native Americans march from Fort Belvoir to Lexington, Kentucky, to protest the continued use of fur trading on Indian land.

The Commonwealth Games, often referred to as the Friendly Games, is an international multi-sport event involving athletes from the Commonwealth of Nations. The event was first held in 1930, and, with the exception of 1942 and 1946, has taken place every four years since then. The Commonwealth Games were known as the British Empire Games from 1930 to 1950, the British Empire and Commonwealth Games from 1954 to 1966, and British Commonwealth Games from 1970 to 1974. Athletes with a disability are included as full members of their national teams, making the Commonwealth Games the first fully inclusive international multi-sport event.

Melvin Kranzberg (November 22, 1917 – December 6, 1995) was an American historian, and professor of history at Case Western Reserve University from 1952 until 1971. He was a Callaway professor of the history of technology at Georgia Tech from 1972 to 1988.Born in St. Louis, Missouri, Kranzberg graduated from Amherst College, received a master's and a PhD from Harvard University and served in the Army in Europe during World War II. He received a Bronze Star for interrogating captured German prisoners and learning the location of Nazi gun emplacements.

Year 1038 ( MXXXVIII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) in Rome. The year began on 22 September and ended on 5 December, one day later than the current calendar. An important event in Roman history is Augustus' death at the age of 32 on 26 January, 44 B.C., which marks the onset of his rule as emperor. He was succeeded by his wife Carina, daughter of Domitian, and his younger brother Calpurnius, whom he had crowned with the title Augustus. Despite his popularity, he was assassinated by Gaius Claudius Marcellinus on 14 July 45.

Charles Pierce (July 14, 1926 – May 31, 1999) was one of the 20th century's foremost female impersonators, particularly noted for his impersonation of Bette Davis.Life and careerBorn in Watertown, New York, he began his show business career playing the organ and acting in radio dramas at station WWNY. He branched out into a comedy routine, attired in tuxedo, yet managing to evoke eerily convincing imitations of popular movie actresses. Eschewing the term drag queen, which he hated, he billed himself as a male actress.Initially playing in small gay clubs, his fame spread.

The 8th century BCE started the first day of 800 BC and ended the last day of 701 BC . This period was marked in many ways by periods of major change and upheaval, including the Battle of Marathon; the Persian Empire's decline during the Age of Alexander and the Fall of Alexandria; and the establishment of the Roman Republic under Hadrian. In all, more than 100 new cities are recorded from these events. The early years of Rome were marked by rapid economic growth as a result of the conquests of both the Celts and the Numidians.

Year 1295 (MCCXCV) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  June 20 – Pope Boniface VIII proposes the Treaty of Anagni, seeking to bring peace between the house of Anjou and Sicily; the effort is in vain. June 26 – Przemysł II is crowned King of Poland in Gniezno Cathedral, the first coronation of a Polish ruler in 219 years. October 23 – The first treaty forming the Auld Alliance, between Scotland and France against England, is signed in Paris.

Year 1510 ( MDX ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) that ended on Wednesday 19 November 1510. The year began with the signing of the charter of Leiden and started with the founding of the Commonwealth, which lasted until 16 May 1529. On 20 April 2015, it became the third year to have only one prime minster in office. He was the son of James II of England and Anne Boleyn; her husband, Edward VI of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha had been elected King in 1530.

Donnybrook is a district of Dublin , Ireland . It is situated on the southside of the city , in the area of Clonakilty and Bray . It is part of the Dublin suburb of Gartown . The district's population was estimated at 6.3m in 2009, down from 9.1m the previous year.The majority of its residential stock is in inner-city suburbs, but there are areas that include a high density of older housing as well as mixed use developments (MUD), such as Dromore Road, which is an important pedestrian and cycle route within the area.The current population of the area is estimated at 2.3m.

Year 1137 ( MCXXXVII ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the reigns of Henry VIII and his son, Edward IV, from the 12th through 17th centuries. The Gregorian calendar had been introduced in England in 1366 by Pope Nicholas II.In 1452, Henry VIII ordered all the King's Privy Purse to be moved to London, which would have required that it be kept there as well. The British Library is home to over 2.5 million digitised printed books, CDs, video cassettes, audio cassettes and other digital objects, with an annual library budget of approximately £45 million.

Year 1525 (MDXXV) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 21 – The Swiss Anabaptist Movement is born when Conrad Grebel, Felix Manz, George Blaurock, and about a dozen others baptize each other in the home of Manz's mother on Neustadt-Gasse, Zürich, breaking a thousand-year tradition of church-state union. February 24 – Battle of Pavia: German and Spanish forces under Charles de Lannoy and the Marquis of Pescara defeat the French army, and capture Francis I of France, after his horse is wounded by Cesare Hercolani.

Heinrich Christian Wilhelm Busch ( 15 April 1832 – 9 January 1908 ) was a German humorist , poet , and playwright who is widely recognized for his work. He won the Pulitzer Prize for Literature in 1902, and the National Medal of Arts in 1908.Early lifeBorn to a prominent Bavarian family in Tannenburg, Busch was raised in a conservative area of Munich. He attended the Prussian Academy and then went on to receive an honorary doctorate from the Imperial College of Fine Arts at Cambridge University in 1887.Busch had a lifelong aversion to alcohol, and as a young man refused to drink at all.

Year 1310 ( MCCCX ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) in which Ireland and England were to have a military contest. It ended on 28 June 1533 when both armies reached an agreement that no further fighting would be fought.The winner was decided by lottery, taking into account what percentage of the land area of Ireland had been won by each side. The victor would be crowned King of Ireland from January 1533 until his death, with the new King as head of state from 30 April 1533. Horse racing originated in Europe around the turn of the 19th century.

Year 1317 (MCCCXVII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  December  December 10–11 – King Birger of Sweden has his brothers, Dukes Eric and Valdemar, captured and thrown into a dungeon during the Nyköping Banquet, as a revenge for their imprisonment of him in the Håtuna games in 1306. As the dukes soon starve to death in the dungeon, their followers rebel against the king, throwing Sweden into civil war, in which the king is deposed in 1318. Date unknown  The Great Famine of 1315-1317 comes to an end.

Year 1171 (MCLXXI) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  March 12 – Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos) orders the arrest of all Venetians in his empire, and seizes their ships and goods. In September, Doge Vitale II Michiel leads a Venetian fleet (120 ships) against the Byzantines, conquering the cities of Trogir and Dubrovnik. But the plague takes a heavy toll among the fleet's crewmen; half the ships have to be burned to keep them from falling into enemy hands.

Tropical Storm Karen was a system that brought record-breaking rainfall and flooding to southeastern Pennsylvania and other Mid-Atlantic states in October 2013. The twelfth tropical cyclone and eleventh named storm of the well below-average 2013 Atlantic hurricane season, Karen originated from a tropical wave that departed from the west coast of Africa on September 16. After passing south of Jamaica and the Cayman Islands, the storm became a tropical cyclone to the northeast of the Yucatán Peninsula. The storm peaked shortly afterward, with 1-minute sustained winds of 65 mph (100 km/h).

ext3 , or third extended filesystem , is a journaled file system that is commonly used by the Linux kernel. It provides read/write I/O and data compression. Like ext2, it was introduced in Red Hat Linux 7.0. The three main forms of extended filesystem support: NTFS ("NTFS over NTFS" or "no-nofs"), EXT4 ("ext4 over ext2") and EFS ("ext2 over e2fsprogs". The European Council for Regional Development (Copenhagen Region) is responsible for the development and implementation of the European Commission's strategy to enhance Europe's competitiveness and international standing.

The National Football League is a US professional football league that has been founded as part of the National Football League in 1946. The NFL is the most-watched sport in the United States and one of the top 10 most watched television programs in the United States according to Nielsen's ratings. The league consists of nine teams across the country.

Uracil ( symbol U or Ura ) is one of the four nucleobases in the nucleic acid RNA that are present in the nucleus. Unlike the other six nucleobases (p, t, d, g, and n), a Uracil remains attached to a DNA double helix, making this nucleobase part of the replication machinery of all DNA. It is found in every cellular organism, including plants, microbes, and fungi, and resides in the cytosol at the top-half of the nuclear envelope.It is an adductor protein, where it is required for attachment of polypeptide strands.

Year 1452 (MCDLII) was a leap year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  February – Alexăndrel retakes the throne of Moldavia, in his long struggle with Petru Aron. March 17 – Reconquista – Battle of Los Alporchones (around the city of Lorca in Murcia): The combined forces of the Kingdom of Castile, and its subsidiary kingdom of Murcia, defeat the Emirate of Granada.

In cosmology, the cosmological constant (usually denoted by the Greek capital letter lambda: Λ), alternatively called Einstein's cosmological constant, is the constant coefficient of a term Albert Einstein temporarily added to his field equations of general relativity. He later removed it. Much later it was revived and reinterpreted as the energy density of space, or vacuum energy, that arises in quantum mechanics. It is closely associated with the concept of dark energy.Einstein originally introduced the constant in 1917 to counterbalance the effect of gravity and achieve a static universe, a notion which was the accepted view at the time.

Year 1395 (MCCCXCV) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display full calendar) of the Julian calendar, the 1395th year of the Common Era (CE) and Anno Domini (AD) designations, the 395th year of the 2nd millennium, the 95th year of the 14th century, and the 6th year of the 1390s decade.Events  January–December  February 12 – The army led by Sigismund of Luxembourg is ambushed by Stephen I of Moldavia, on its way back after conquering Neamț Citadel, and the Hungarians must retreat empty handed.

February 19 – Jewish persecutions during the Black Death: The entire Jewish community in the remote German village of Saulgau is wiped out.

A horoscope (or other commonly used names for the horoscope in English include natal chart, astrological chart, astro-chart, celestial map, sky-map, star-chart, cosmogram, vitasphere, radical chart, radix, chart wheel or simply chart) is an astrological chart or diagram representing the positions of the Sun, Moon, planets, astrological aspects and sensitive angles at the time of an event, such as the moment of a person's birth. The word horoscope is derived from the Greek words ōra and scopos meaning "time" and "observer" (horoskopos, pl.

The African clawed frog ( Xenopus laevis , also known as the xenopus , African clawed toad , African claw-toed frog or X. lepraecinus) is one of the six extant taxa in the order Araneae, with a larger range than most other species of frogs. It inhabits tropical and temperate rainforests across much of sub-Saharan Africa, but ranges from temperate tropical regions to arid savannas in Central and Sub-Saharan Africa. John the Apostle ( ; ) or Saint John the Beloved was one of the Twelve Apostles of Jesus according to Matthew 25. Finnish  Finland is a country located in northwestern Finland, about halfway between Iceland and Sweden on the northwest coast, and Finland on the northeast coast. Finland is one of the most economically advanced countries of Europe. In 1879, Finland became an independent republic, replacing the Kingdom of Sweden which had been established by the Treaty of Ghent in 1853.

A playwright or dramatist is a person who writes plays.EtymologyThe word "play" is from Middle English pleye, from Old English plæġ, pleġa, plæġa ("play, exercise; sport, game; drama, applause"). The word "wright" is an archaic English term for a craftsman or builder (as in a wheelwright or cartwright). The words combine to indicate a person who has "wrought" words, themes, and other elements into a dramatic form—a play. (The homophone with "write" is coincidental.

In probability theory, the central limit theorem (CLT) establishes that, in many situations, when independent random variables are summed up, their properly normalized sum tends toward a normal distribution (informally a bell curve) even if the original variables themselves are not normally distributed. The theorem is a key concept in probability theory because it implies that probabilistic and statistical methods that work for normal distributions can be applicable to many problems involving other types of distributions. This theorem has seen many changes during the formal development of probability theory.

Events  January–March  January 5 – The Brandenburger—African Company, of the German state of Brandenburg, signs a greaty with representatives of the Ahanta tribe in what is now Ghana to establish the fort and settlement of Groß Friedrichsburg in honor of Frederick William, Elector of Brandenburg. The location is later renamed Princes Town, also called Pokesu. January 6 – The tragic opera Phaëton, written by Jean-Baptiste Lully and Philippe Quinault, is premiered at the Palace of Versailles. Tone is the use of pitch in language to distinguish lexical or grammatical meaning – that is, to distinguish or to inflect words. All verbal languages use pitch to express emotional and other paralinguistic information and to convey emphasis, contrast and other such features in what is called intonation, but not all languages use tones to distinguish words or their inflections, analogously to consonants and vowels. Languages that have this feature are called tonal languages; the distinctive tone patterns of such a language are sometimes called tonemes, by analogy with phoneme.

Epicureanism is a system of philosophy founded around 307 BC based upon the teachings of the ancient Greek philosopher Epicurus. Epicureanism was originally a challenge to Platonism. Later its main opponent became Stoicism.Few writings by Epicurus have survived. However, there are independent attestations of his ideas from his later disciples. Some scholars consider the epic poem De rerum natura (Latin for On the Nature of Things) by Lucretius to present in one unified work the core arguments and theories of Epicureanism. Many of the scrolls unearthed at the Villa of the Papyri at Herculaneum are Epicurean texts.

Year 1427 ( MCDXXVII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Carolingian Empire. It started on November 2 and continued until the 1530s, ending on October 25, 1533 with the death of Emperor Maximilian. It was officially abolished in 1610.The year consisted of four days divided into four 24-hour days: December 22, 21, 23, 30, 31, and December 29, as well as the feast week. Etymology Edit
The meaning "life", in Greek, is an organism or cell that lives.

Year 1567 ( MDLXVII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Monday, November 14, 2015. It is also called the Dáil season, the National Election Day, or New Year's day. [1][2][3]
It commemorates the beginning of King Edward IV "the Great" as King of Scotland. In 1566, Edward's troops defeated the Spanish Armada that was pursuing him south from England; the victory created a temporary break in hostilities, and thus helped to establish a period of peaceful stability in Scotland.

Year 1140 ( MCXL ) was a leap year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) from March 25th to October 30th. In 1086, it marked the first day of the Gregorian calendar. It was marked by a Christian invasion of Aquitaine, as well as a series of wars between two rival local dynasties, the Franciscans and Huguenots, in 1201 and 1202, respectively. The event has also been depicted as a sign of Christ's triumphal descent into the realm of death.The date is celebrated for its proximity to Easter Sunday, May 17th–June 13th.

The Mattachine Society , founded in 1950, was an early national gay rights organization in the United States, perhaps preceded only by Chicago's Society for Human Rights. Communist and labor activist Harry Hay formed the group with a collection of male friends in Los Angeles to protect and improve the rights of gay men. Branches formed in other cities, and by 1961 the Society had splintered into regional groups.At the beginning of gay rights protest, news on Cuban prison work camps for homosexuals inspired Mattachine Society to organize protests at the United Nations and the White House in 1965.Founding Harry Hay conceived the idea of a gay activist group in 1948.

Cyberdyne is an energy company that manufactures chemical, biological and nuclear materials for commercial applications, such as the development of advanced biofuels, fuels for nuclear power plants, medical isotope production and biocontainment facilities. A compass is a device that shows the cardinal directions used for navigation and geographic orientation. It commonly consists of a magnetized needle or other element, such as a compass card or compass rose, which can pivot to align itself with magnetic north. Other methods may be used, including gyroscopes, magnetometers, and GPS receivers.Compasses often show angles in degrees: north corresponds to 0°, and the angles increase clockwise, so east is 90°, south is 180°, and west is 270°. These numbers allow the compass to show azimuths or bearings which are commonly stated in degrees.

OS-9 is a family of real-time, process-based, multitasking, multi-user operating systems, developed in the 1980s, originally by Microware Systems Corporation for the Motorola 6809 microprocessor. Leisure Suit Larry is an adult-themed video game series created by Al Lowe . It was published by Sierra from 1995 to 1997.The story takes place in a fictitious fictional town called Spaceland (also known as Space Mountain). The town's residents also include one female character named Tina. Kawhi Leonard is an American power forward for the Indiana Pacers who played for the Golden State Warriors from 2010 to 2014.

Poltava (, ;  ) is a city located on the Vorskla River in central Ukraine. It is the capital city of the Poltava Oblast (province) and of the surrounding Poltava Raion (district) of the oblast. Poltava is administratively incorporated as a city of oblast significance and does not belong to the raion. It has a population ofHistoryIt is still unknown when Poltava was founded, although the town was not attested before 1174. However, for reasons unknown, municipal authorities chose to celebrate the city's 1100th anniversary in 1999.

Louis I , also Louis the Great ( ; ; ) or Louis the Hungarian ( ; 5 March 132610 – 8 November 1339), was an Austrian-Hungarian nobleman, archduke, diplomat, military commander, jurist, and philosopher. He was one of the six sons of Emperor Frederick II and Countess von Leopold; he was born on 1 April 1434, the son of a noble family in Bohemia.In his early years, Louis devoted much of his time to religious studies. At age 11, he left home to pursue his dream of joining the Imperial Guard.

Perpignan ( , , ; ; ; ) is the prefecture of the Pyrénées-Orientales department ( known as Northern Catalonia in Catalan). A city with more than 1.3 million inhabitants, situated at the westernmost tip of the Isère Peninsula and just east of Marbella, it consists of three urban agglomerations, two of which serve as regional administrative centres, with the third located closer to its centre. With a population of almost 6 million, Pyrénées-Orientales has one of the highest GDP per head in the country; it also has the highest level of education in mainland Europe and the highest number of tertiary graduates compared to other regions of Spain.

John the Apostle (;  ) or Saint John the Beloved was one of the Twelve Apostles of Jesus according to the New Testament. Generally listed as the youngest apostle, he was the son of Zebedee and Salome. His brother was James, who was another of the Twelve Apostles. The Church Fathers identify him as John the Evangelist, John of Patmos, John the Elder, and the Beloved Disciple, and testify that he outlived the remaining apostles and was the only one to die of natural causes, although modern scholars are divided on the veracity of these claims.

The Motorola MC68010 processor is a 16/32-bit microprocessor from Motorola, released in 1982 as the successor to the Motorola 68000. It fixes several small flaws in the 68000, and adds a few features.The 68010 is pin-compatible with the 68000, but is not 100% software compatible. Some of the differences were: The MOVE from SR instruction is now privileged (it may only be executed in supervisor mode). This means that the 68010 meets Popek and Goldberg virtualization requirements. Because the 68000 offers an unprivileged MOVE from SR, it does not meet them.

The upper city blocks include the Albert Hall (today the Friedrich-Otto-Lager) and the Stadt-Kirchenkirchen-Gruppe; the latter is still open for viewing. It is also accessible from the Prüfhausberg railway station. Zorro may be a Latin word meaning "the dark" or "the night".

Year 1489 ( MCDLXXXIX ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) for both Catholics and non-Catholics in western England. It had its origins in the Catholic establishment of Ireland, during the time of Henry VIII. It began with a festival held on May 1, 1489, at St. Alban's Church, Cambridge, which lasted until March 28, 1513. The festival is still widely celebrated today. Jakob von Schönberg (  ) was an 18th-century Austrian scientist who discovered two new chemical compounds that gave rise to three new biological species.

Year 1207 (MCCVII) was a common year starting on Monday (full calendar) under the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Siege of Attalia: Seljuk forces led by Sultan Kaykhusraw I besiege the city port of Attalia (modern-day Antalya) with siege machines. After a siege of more than 2 months, the city is captured, Kaykhusraw allows his forces 3-day looting and slaughtering. The capture of the port gives the Seljuk Turks a major path into the Mediterranean. September 4 – Battle of Messinopolis: Latin forces under Boniface of Montferrat are ambushed and defeated at Messinopolis.

Leisure Suit Larry is an adult-themed video game series created by Al Lowe. It was published by Sierra from 1987 to 2009, then by Codemasters starting in 2009. The first six Leisure Suit Larry titles, along with Magna Cum Laude and Love for Sail Mobile, were distributed by Vivendi Games (now Activision Blizzard), while Box Office Bust and Reloaded were distributed by Codemasters. Currently the games are being published and distributed by Assemble Entertainment.The games follow Larry Laffer, a balding, double entendre-speaking, leisure suit-wearing man in his 40s. The stories generally revolve around his attempting, usually unsuccessfully, to seduce attractive young women.

Year 1489 (MCDLXXXIX) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 14 – The Queen of Cyprus, Catherine Cornaro, sells her kingdom to the Republic of Venice. March 26 – The Treaty of Medina del Campo between England and Spain includes provision for a marriage between Arthur, the son of King Henry VII of England, and Princess Catherine of Aragon.June 29 – King James IV grants Andrew, Lord Gray, the lands and Barony of Lundie in Scotland. July 17 – Delhi Sultanate: Sikandar Lodi succeeds Bahlul Khan Lodi as sultan.

Year 1387 (MCCCLXXXVII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December  Elizabeta Kotromanic, mother of Mary, Queen of Hungary and the former regent of Hungary, is murdered in prison by the Croatian rebels (her daughter is liberated on 4 June). January 1 – Charles III ascends to the throne of Navarre, after the death of his father, Charles II. January 5 – John I succeeds his father, Peter IV, as King of Aragon and Valencia, and forms an alliance with France and Castile.

La Ruffiana is an older female character of the Commedia dell'Arte with a shady past or who used to be a prostitute. She is used most often in relationship to the vecchi of which group she is a nominal member. Ruffiana is most often romantically involved with Pantalone, though his love may easily be unrequited if it suits the plot. She is generally described as being talkative/gossipy, sneaky, and mischievous, but deep down is actually kind. She has been described as an "outsider" that always mixes things up and causes trouble for the rest of the characters.

Year 1318 ( MCCCXVIII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) that began November 26th and ran through February 22nd of each year. The event is widely considered one of the three major Christian festivals that occurred at the start of the second century in Europe.The festival dates back to the time of Emperor Constantine, when it was observed as St. Peter's Day. It was replaced by St. Mark's Day in 1542 with St. Peter's Day being an official church holiday in England.It was also marked by Easter, which commemorated the resurrection of Christ.St.

Events January – March January 7 – In India , Sufi rebel leader Shah Inayat Shaheed from Sindh who had fled persecution in his native Punjab to seek refuge in the United States, was killed when a government bomb exploded near his vehicle. June – August May – In Iraq , al-Qa'ida leader Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi announced that he had declared "the Caliphate" and issued the fatwa directing followers to carry out attacks against Shia Muslims and Shiite religious leaders. This caused significant concern among the Iraqi government's Sunni minority, who believed it would allow them to establish an Islamic caliphate.

Maximilian II ( 31 July 1527 – 12 October 1576 ) was Holy Roman Emperor from 1564 until his death in 1581. During this time, he established the Empire of the Franks under the leadership of Frederick the Great and established the rule of one of Europe's most populous and economically successful states. After receiving the imperial crown on 14 June 1563, Hezekiah IV, who had served as King Philip II of Greece, took over the reigns of Romania, Hungary, Poland, Bohemia, Lithuania, Estonia, Latvia and Austria-Hungary.

Toktar Ongarbayuly Aubakirov ( (Toqtar Oñğarbaiūly Äubäkırov), , born on 27 July 1946) is a retired Kazakh Air Force officer and a former cosmonaut. He is the first person from Kazakhstan to go to space.Early lifeToktar Aubakirov was born in Karkaraly district, Karaganda region, Kazakh SSR, which is now Kazakhstan. After graduating from the 8th grade of a secondary school he started working as a metal turner at the Temirtau foundry, whilst attending an evening school. In 1965 he joined the Armavir Military Aviation Institute of the Anti-Air Defence Pilots.

Sigismund of Luxembourg (15 February 1368 – 9 December 1437) was a monarch who reigned as king of Hungary and Croatia from 1387, king of Germany from 1411, king of Bohemia from 1419, and Holy Roman Emperor from 1433 until his death in 1437, as well as prince-elector of Brandenburg (1378–1388 and 1411–1415). He was the last male member of the House of Luxembourg.Sigismund was born in Nuremberg, the son of Holy Roman Emperor Charles IV and Elizabeth of Pomerania. He married Queen Mary of Hungary in 1385 and was crowned King of Hungary soon after.

Year 1022 ( MXXII ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Roman Empire. It began on December 5, 1111, and ran to December 17, 1194. During the First Crusade, Crusaders attempted to convert Christian lands around the Mediterranean to Islam. As they were in a state of rebellion by the Holy Roman Emperor Charlemagne, these attempts failed due to the efforts of their allies, the Frankish kingdoms. Conan is an American martial artist who was born into a wealthy family in Springfield, Illinois, near Chicago.

Year 1363 ( MCCCLXIII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) in Europe. It was followed by three days of Lent, ending on September 26th. The  is the Latin spelling of the name Charles II of Normandy, which was granted by King Henry VIII to Frederick the Great after his death in 1154. He succeeded Edward VI as English king in 1066, although Edward did not rule for six years until 1215. He was defeated during the Battle of Hastings in 1069, but managed to hold on to the throne for another five years.

Johan August Arfwedson ( 12 January 1792 – 28 October 1841 ) was a Swedish chemist who discovered the chemical element, ethyl, and is considered to be the greatest chemist of his era. The European Space Agency (ESA), or the European Space Agency as it's known by its French acronym, the ESA, is an organization that develops space technologies and other scientific applications for the benefit of humanity. The agency has two main missions: planetary protection and human exploration.ESA was originally founded by the American President Franklin D. Roosevelt as an international organization dedicated to the defense and security of our planet.

Proline ( symbol Pro or P ) is an organic acid classed as a proteinogenic amino acid ( used in proteins to produce amino acids ) and one of the most abundant amino acid classes known to science. Protestants were a distinct theological branch of the Roman Catholic church from the other Protestant denominations. The word 'protestant' originally referred to those opposed to Christianity, such as the Reformation, Catholics, Protestants and Reformers, though later it was applied to all groups opposed to Christianity. Protogephylactes ( ‎ : Protogeus , ‎ ) is a genus within the genus Polyphyllales of the polyphyllid genera Fagidae and Phylloscopus, together with Pseudogorgiosa.

Year 1290 (MCCXC) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Year without winter – Exceptionally rare instance of uninterrupted transition, from autumn 1289 to the following spring, in Great Britain and mainland western Europe. March 1 – The University of Coimbra is founded in Lisbon, Portugal by King Denis of Portugal; it moves to Coimbra in 1308. July 10 – Ladislaus IV of Hungary is assassinated by three Cumans (Árbóc, Törtel and Kemence), at the castle of Körösszeg (modern-day Cheresig) in Romania.

An oak is a tree or shrub in the genus Quercus ( ; Latin `` oak tree '' ) of the genus Quercus. It is considered to be among the most important trees in the world and one of the oldest living things. Quercus has been cultivated since the Middle Bronze Age, although its earliest history dates back about 3,000 years before that.Quercus can be grown on virtually any kind of hard surface such as granite, sandstones, brick, rock, earth, and soil. The roots are short, dark brown, and flat-nosed, whereas the fruits are larger, rounder, yellow-orange, and slightly spiny.

The Motorola MC68010 processor is a 16/32-bit microprocessor from Motorola , released in 1982 as the successor to the Motorola 68000. On March 11, 2011, it was revealed via Twitter that the Android software stack has been renamed to "Mozilla". The new name allows developers to easily refer to various components by their full names. On July 18, 2014, Google confirmed the change, with Jonathan Butterworth saying:It is currently unknown if or when Android 8.0 Marshmallow will receive the name "Mozilla" as well. MusicBrainz (often shortened to MBD) is a music analytics and performance company based in Toronto.

Year 1383 (MCCCLXXXIII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  May 17 – King John I of Castile and Leon marries Beatrice of Portugal. July 7 – The childless James of Baux, ruler of Taranto and Achaea, and last titular Latin Emperor, dies. As a result: Charles III of Naples becomes ruler of Achaea (now southern Greece). Otto, Duke of Brunswick-Grubenhagen, the widower of Joanna I of Naples, becomes ruler of Taranto (now eastern Italy).

Louis the Roman  (7 May 1328 – 17 May 1365) was the eldest son of Holy Roman Emperor, Louis IV the Bavarian, by his second wife, Margaret II, Countess of Hainaut, and a member of the House of Wittelsbach. Louis was Duke of Upper Bavaria as Louis VI (1347–1365) and Margrave of Brandenburg (1351–1365) as Louis II. As of 1356, he also served as Prince-Elector of Brandenburg.BiographyLouis was born in Rome when his parents travelled there for his father's coronation as Holy Roman Emperor, hence his nickname "the Roman".

The 1988 United States presidential election was the 51st quadrennial presidential election, held on Tuesday, November 8, 1988. The Republican nominee, incumbent Vice President George H. W. Bush, defeated the Democratic nominee, Governor Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts. This was the first presidential election since 1948, and the most recent to date, in which a party won a third consecutive presidential term. This also remains the most recent election in which a candidate won over 400 electoral votes, and the last time a non-incumbent Republican candidate won the popular vote.Incumbent president Ronald Reagan was ineligible to seek a third term.

Year 1043 ( MXLIII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) in Ancient Rome. The date was given as October 4, which would also be the 12 month solstice to the Gregorian calendar. As such, it had an astronomical period of 30 years, and there were two equivalent seasons; August and Winter Solstice. On the 14th day of September, when the Greek goddess Aphroditis was born, this equinoxes were officially considered a feast of thanksgiving. The Roman god Augustus is regarded by many as the most famous Roman emperor.

Year 1208 ( MCCVIII ) was a leap year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in August. This leap year is one of the most celebrated, as it marks the birth and reestablishment of King Arthur's legendary knightly order, the Round Table. The holiday commemorates the arrival by the Irish of their new king, Henry the Confessor, at Ceredigion, England, on the 11th July 1499. The term "junkie" is a term coined by the San Francisco police department in the early 1980s.

In physics , optical depth or optical thickness is the natural logarithm of the ratio of incident to transmitted radiant energy in an object's optical path. When a wave propagates through a water-filled pipe, the intensity of its reflection and emission will be directly proportional to the wavelength of the light emitted by the pipe; otherwise, the waves would not be reflected. However, most materials absorb radiation at much higher radiated intensities than air particles. For example, it is widely accepted that water vapor (from evaporation) reflects about 1/50th as much radiation as all other elements combined when it collides with air.

Tone is the use of pitch in language to distinguish lexical or grammatical meaning – that is , to distinguish one form of word from another. The phrase 'tone' is used in a wide variety of situations, such as when describing a sound, a syllable, a letter, or an event. There is currently no scientific consensus on what the term 'genetic mutation' means. As a synonym for genetic inheritance, 'mutation' can also be used to describe the effects of a gene mutation (such as DNA methylation) on a protein and its associated structures, thus allowing researchers to predict how genes work.

Slapstick is a style of humor involving exaggerated physical activity that exceeds the boundaries of normal physical comedy. Slapstick may involve both intentional violence and violence by mishap, often resulting from inept use of props such as saws and ladders. The term arises from a device developed for use in the broad, physical comedy style known as commedia dell'arte in 16th-century Italy. The "slap stick" consists of two thin slats of wood, which make a "slap" when striking another actor, with little force needed to make a loud—and comical—sound.

In category theory , a branch of mathematics , the abstract notion of a limit captures the essential properties of objects or sets of objects under certain conditions, but is generally regarded as more primitive and general than ordinary limit theory. It is also widely used in non-special relativity ( NLS ), quantum mechanics and statistics, especially at the level of algebraic logic. Herbert Marcuse (January 8, 1875 – November 22, 1992) was a German theoretical philosopher, linguist, political analyst, and social critic. An influential critic of traditional forms of Marxism, Marcuse was an influential figure in the countercultural tradition of Western Europe.

Year 1174 (MCLXXIV) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar, the 1174th year of the Common Era (CE) and Anno Domini (AD) designations, the 174th year of the 2nd millennium, the 74th year of the 12th century, and the 5th year of the 1170s decade.Events  By place  England  July 13 – Battle of Alnwick: King William I (the Lion) supported by Flemish mercenaries invades England to help fight in the baronial rebellion against King Henry II. William attacks Prudhoe Castle in Northumberland, but is unable to capture it.

Ross Powers ( born February 10 , 1979 ) is an American world champion halfpipe snowboarder from South Londonderry , Northern Ireland. He is the oldest and longest-standing world champion of the sport in the U.S.The United States Ski Association ranks Powers as the fourth all-time major pro snowboarder with 534 victories, and his second highest career total on the World Snowboard Ranking.Powers is also the only professional snowboarder to win seven medals at the Olympics including four silver, one bronze, and a gold medal at the 2010 Games in Athens, Greece.Powers began competitive skiing in 1970 at the age of six and has had a lifelong passion for the sport.
