Year 1347 (MCCCXLVII) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar, and a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Proleptic Gregorian calendar.Events  January–December  January 26 – Charles University in Prague is founded by a bull issued by Pope Clement VI at the request of Charles I, King of Bohemia. February 2 – The Byzantine civil war of 1341–1347 between John VI Kantakouzenos and the regency for John V Palaiologos ends with Kantakouzenos entering Constantinople. April – The Knights Hospitaller defeat a Turkish fleet, and sink 100 ships off Imbros.

Year 1357 ( MCCCLVII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) in North America, the Americas, and South America. In the United Kingdom, it started on 12 February 1759 and continued through 21 November 1791. It was chosen as the "most important Christian feast" for the Anglican Church in England during the English Puritan Reformation. For centuries it was a popular holiday to commemorate the life of St Clement of Alexandria, the First Ecumenical Council of the Eastern Church.In 1492 Pope Leo X granted indulgences to Christians who had been under penance for an indefinite period of time.

Ski jumping is a winter sport in which competitors aim to achieve the farthest jump after sliding down on their skis from a specially designed curved ramp. Along with jump length, competitor's aerial style and other factors also affect the final score. Ski jumping was first contested in Norway in the late 19th century, and later spread through Europe and North America in the early 20th century. Along with cross-country skiing, it constitutes the traditional group of Nordic skiing disciplines.The ski jumping venue, commonly referred to as a hill, consists of the jumping ramp (in-run), take-off table, and a landing hill.

CBE may refer to : Travel CBE , IATA code for Greater Cumberland Regional Airport . CBE , ICAO code for Greater Cumberland Regional Airport is an air transport hub near Stirling, England. It serves as the main transshipment port of British Columbia and New Brunswick and is one of the largest airports in Canada.The terminal is a four-floor building that offers direct access to the airport via two elevated lifts on each floor. This allows passengers to be moved between terminals at a moment's notice. The liftways are connected by tunnels, which are open 24 hours per day.

Events January–March January 7 – the Republic of Genoa forbids the unauthorized printing of newspapers and all handwriten newssheets . Genoa, a small Mediterranean port city on the Adriatic coast (modern-day Serbia), lies at the center of the Aegean Sea between Italy and Turkey, and is known for its numerous cultural attractions. A UNESCO world Heritage Site since 1866, its history dates to Roman times.The town was founded in the 10th century by Marco Polo as his personal fortress. Today it is surrounded by archaeological sites, including the site of the last major Roman fort, Palmyra , which was rebuilt around 442 AD.

Algebraic topology is a branch of mathematics that uses tools from abstract algebra to study topological spaces. The basic goal is to find algebraic invariants that classify topological spaces up to homeomorphism, though usually most classify up to homotopy equivalence.Although algebraic topology primarily uses algebra to study topological problems, using topology to solve algebraic problems is sometimes also possible. Algebraic topology, for example, allows for a convenient proof that any subgroup of a free group is again a free group.Main branches of algebraic topologyBelow are some of the main areas studied in algebraic topology:Homotopy groupsIn mathematics, homotopy groups are used in algebraic topology to classify topological spaces.

Year 1303 ( MCCCIII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Saturday. It was officially celebrated around the world on November 30th with fireworks, music, public worship and celebration, and a feast of the Holy Trinity at Christ's Epiphany . The International Space Station ( ISSPACE ) is a United States government space station built by NASA to conduct research and experiments on the International Space Station as part of its Expedition 51 mission in 1999.It consists of four functional segments which are located in Earth orbit aboard a Russian Soyuz spacecraft.

Year 1474 (MCDLXXIV) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events <onlyinclude>January–December  February – The Treaty of Utrecht puts an end to the Anglo-Hanseatic War. March 19 – The Senate of the Republic of Venice enacts the Venetian Patent Statute, one of the earliest patent systems in the world. New and inventive devices, once put into practice, have to be communicated to the Republic to obtain the right to prevent others from using them. This is considered the first modern patent system.

EventsJanuary–March January 1 – Prince Muhammad Akbar , son of the Mughal Emperor Aurangzeb , initiates a civil war in which thousands die. Theatre
Hercules  ( Greek: ἐγελος ἐνδυπτρος) is a Greek epic poem written about Thebans, a subgroup of the ancient Near Eastern kingdom of Crete. It was first composed by Hippolytus sometime around 480 BCE, and later became known as the Macrobius or Macrobian Oratorios. The earliest extant copies are held at the British Museum in London.Hercules is widely regarded to be the most important drama ever written, not only for its cultural achievements but for its impact on literature and art.

Year 1432 (MCDXXXII) was a leap year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 1 – Iliaș succeeds his father as Prince of Moldavia. Spring – An Albanian revolt, led by Gjergj Arianit Komneni, breaks out against the Ottoman Empire, and spreads through most of Albania. April – At the end of the Hook and Cod wars, Jacqueline, Countess of Hainaut and Countess of Holland and Zeeland, is forced by Philip the Good, Duke of Burgundy, to abdicate all her estates in his favour, ending Hainaut and Holland as independent counties.

Year 1181 (MCLXXXI) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  King Philip II (Augustus) annuls all loans made by Jews to Christians, and takes a percentage for himself. A year later, he confiscates all Jewish property and expels the Jews from Paris. Philip II begins a war against Philip of Alsace, count of Flanders, over the Vermandois. He claims the territory for his wife Isabella of Hainault as her dowry. Philip is unwilling to give it up.

Year 1527 (MDXXVII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June January 1 – Croatian nobles elect Ferdinand I of Austria as King of Croatia in the Parliament on Cetin. January 5 – Felix Manz, co-founder of the Swiss Anabaptists, is drowned in the Limmat in Zürich by the Zürich Reformed state church. March 17 – Battle of Khanwa: Babur defeats Rajput ruler Rana Sanga. This and two other major Moghul victories lead to their domination of northern India. Dhaulpur fort is taken by Babur.

The 7th millennium BC spanned the years 7000 BC to 6001 BC ( c. 9 ka to c. 8 ka ), while the first recorded use of the Hebrew language is known from the early 3rd millennium B.C. There are only a few remaining surviving written records of this era in the region, but these were used as the basis for historical and archeological studies throughout the millennia by the scholars involved. The Jewish people had arrived on the western coast of Israel around 1200 BC and migrated into the Delta area, forming the dominant ethnic group there, with the Negev bordering the Dead Sea at present.

Year 1047 ( MXLVII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the years from 1031 to 1051.The year began on June 30th and ended on Saturday, November 25th at 12:01 AM UTC. This was known as the day "The Day of the Little Lion". Nominal number is generally considered to correspond with the numeral 8 in the Julian decimal system, but that may not always be correct for numerical systems such as the English or the Roman system where the initial letter can also be an infinite sequence of digits or even a single digit.

Acetic acid bacteria ( AAB ) are a group of Gram-negative bacteria which oxidize sugars or ethanol and produce acetic acid, an alkaline hydrocarbon which can be used as a fuel.Acetic acid is produced by aerobic bacteria when they use the energy from the burning of glucose and alcohol to create enzymes capable of metabolizing these sugars into acetyl-CoA. It is used as a source of energy for organisms such as humans but it has no nutritional value due to the low rate of metabolism. Atomic bomb testing began in April 1946 as part of United States Strategic Bombing Survey  , an armament study that assessed the threat to the United States from nonnuclear weapons.

Year 1379 ( MCCCLXXIX ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending Sunday. The Roman Catholic church officially recognized it as the Year of Mercy, commemorating its victory over the Carthaginians at Cannae in April 441 CE.The year began on December 31, when St Augustine declared that there would be a universal celebration of the life and miracles of Christ. It continued for two years to March 30, then ended on May 15, 614.During the first decade of the century, the Julian calendar had been used throughout Latin America and parts of Central and Eastern Asia.

Year 1366 (MCCCLXVI) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  March 13 – Henry II deposes his half-brother, Pedro of Castile, to become King of Castile. October 12 – Frederick III of Sicily forbids decorations on synagogues. October 26 – Comet 55P/Tempel–Tuttle passes  from Earth.Date unknown  Thomas Fraser obtains lands in Aberdeenshire, upon which he starts the building of a towerhouse, that will later be known as Muchalls Castle. Muhammed V builds the Granada Hospital in Granada (in present-day Spain).

Year 1406 ( MCDVI ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) that marked the beginning of the Great Reformulation, an era of transition from the feudal system of Roman Catholicism to the new democratic state system established by the Carolingian emperor Charles V in the 11th Century. In the first few years of the Renaissance, as part of the efforts to strengthen the church's prestige within Europe, several reforms took place which included the establishment of monasteries and theological seminaries. In 1320, the Pope decreed the separation of laymen from monks and women from men in the order of the laity.

The Laboratory for Atmospheric and Space Physics ( LASP ) is a research organization at the University of Colorado Boulder, funded by federal grants that are administered jointly by the National Science Foundation ( NSF ) in partnership with the Department of Energy. Its primary mission is to support the exploration, study, and development of the physics and astronomy of the atmosphere and land surfaces around the globe.LASP's core research activities concern the physical processes governing the formation of clouds, dust storms, hurricanes, typhoons, tropical cyclones, droughts, and more.

Three bobsleigh events were competed at the 2002 Winter Olympics, at Utah Olympic Park. The competition took place between February 16 and February 23, 2002.For the first time since 1932, Olympic bobsleigh added a new event, with the first ever women's competition, won by Jill Bakken and  Vonetta Flowers of the United States.The competitions comprised four heats. Teams raced in the first and third heats in the order of the draw. The second heat was raced in order of ranking after the first heat, and the fourth heat is raced in order of the ranking after the first three heats.

Year 1530 (MDXXX) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar, the 1530th year of the Common Era (CE) and Anno Domini (AD) designations, the 530th year of the 2nd millennium, the 30th year of the 16th century, and the 1st year of the 1530s decade.Events  January–June  February 14 – Tangaxuan II, last cazonci of the Tarascan State, is executed by conquistador Nuño de Guzmán, ending the Tarascan State's independence from Spain. February 24 – Charles V is crowned emperor in Bologna, by Pope Clement VII.

Lead azide is an inorganic compound . More so than other azides , is explosive . It is used in explosives (such as fissile materials and thermogenic substances) to produce high pressure. Atomic energy, the energy of one atom, is the maximum amount that can be produced by a reaction between two atoms when all three atomic states are at their minimum. It is called the nuclear energy limit or the "enormous energy limit". Academy Athletic Association ( AA ), the organization that governs National Football League (NFL) teams nationwide, is the governing body for the NFL.

Mariner 10 was an American robotic space probe launched by NASA on 3 November 1973 , to fly by the Moon and explore its surface. Named after US space engineer Robert C. "Bob" Hansen, the mission consisted of four main components – a two-person robot called the Viking lander (later dubbed the Skylab) to collect samples and sample return to Earth, and a rover that would perform a series of complex scientific experiments to answer some of the biggest questions about the Moon. Hepatitis A (also known as hepatitis A virus), is an infectious infection caused by a virus infecting the liver and pancreas.

The hobby of collecting includes seeking, locating, acquiring, organizing, cataloging, displaying, storing, and maintaining items that are of interest to an individual collector. Collections differ in a wide variety of respects, most obviously in the nature and scope of the objects contained, but also in purpose, presentation, and so forth. The range of possible subjects for a collection is practically unlimited, and collectors have realised a vast number of these possibilities in practice, although some are much more popular than others.In collections of manufactured items, the objects may be antique or simply collectable.

Year 990 (CMXC) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Al-Mansur, de facto ruler of Al-Andalus, conquers the Castle of Montemor-o-Velho (modern Portugal), expanding the Umayyad Caliphate of Córdoba. The city of Lund, Sweden is founded, during the reign of the Danish king Sweyn Forkbeard (approximate date). Africa  The Ghana Empire takes the Berber town of Aoudaghost (modern Mauritania) as the West African nation makes further gains. Construction of the Al-Hakim Mosque by orders of the Fatimid vizier Gawar Al-Siqilli begins in Cairo (modern Egypt).

Events  January–June  January 1 Colonel George Monck (with his regiment) crosses from Scotland to England at the village of Coldstream, and begins his advance towards London in support of the English Restoration. Samuel Pepys begins his diary. February 3 – George Monck and his regiment arrive in London. February 13 – Charles XI becomes king of Sweden at the age of five, upon the death of his father, Charles X Gustavus. February 27 – John Thurloe is reinstated as England's Secretary of State, having been deprived of his offices late in the previous year. March 16 – The Long Parliament disbands.

Vapor pressure (or vapour pressure in English-speaking counties other than the US; see spelling differences) or equilibrium vapor pressure is defined as the pressure exerted by a vapor in thermodynamic equilibrium with its condensed phases (solid or liquid) at a given temperature in a closed system. The equilibrium vapor pressure is an indication of a liquid's evaporation rate. It relates to the tendency of particles to escape from the liquid (or a solid). A substance with a high vapor pressure at normal temperatures is often referred to as volatile. The pressure exhibited by vapor present above a liquid surface is known as vapor pressure.

The standard circulating coinage of the United Kingdom, British Crown Dependencies and British Overseas Territories is denominated in pounds sterling (symbol "£"), and ranges in value from one penny to two pounds. Since decimalisation, on 15 February 1971, the pound has been divided into 100 (new) pence. Before decimalisation, twelve pence made a shilling, and twenty shillings made a pound. British coins are minted by the Royal Mint in Llantrisant, Wales. The Royal Mint also commissions the coins' designs.In addition to the circulating coinage, the UK also mints commemorative decimal coins (crowns) in the denomination of five pounds.

Year 998 ( CMXCVIII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) that is considered the birthyear of Alexander the Great and the first year of Emperor Claudius I (link will display the full calendar). On January 1st, 1797, Napoleon II received his first commission. It was to become an officer in the Russian army. On July 5th, he succeeded in setting up a permanent headquarters at St. Petersburg for the administration of Russia, which had previously been part of France. On October 13th, 1808, Napoleon declared himself emperor, becoming the last reigning emperor of the world.

Year 1186 (MCLXXXVI) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January 27 – Constance of Sicily marries Henry (the future Henry VI, Holy Roman Emperor). John the Chanter becomes Bishop of Exeter. The Byzantine Empire recognizes the independence of Bulgaria and Serbia. Joscius becomes Archbishop of Tyre. Jayavarman VII, the king of Cambodia, founds the temple of Ta Prohm. After the death of the child-king Baldwin V, his mother succeeds him as Sibylla of Jerusalem, and appoints her disfavoured husband Guy de Lusignan king consort.

Year 1412 (MCDXII) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) on the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 16 – The Medici Family are  made official bankers of the Papacy. January 25 – Ernest, Duke of Austria, marries Cymburgis of Masovia. July 24 – Behnam Hadloyo becomes Syriac Orthodox Patriarch of Mardin. October 5 – Emperor Go-Komatsu abdicates, and Emperor Shoko accedes to the throne of Japan. October 28 – Eric of Pomerania becomes sole ruler of the Kalmar Union (Sweden, Denmark and Norway), upon the death of Queen Margaret.

Botulinum toxin ( BoNT ) is a neurotoxic protein produced by the bacterium Clostridium botulinum and related species . It is widely distributed worldwide. In the US, it is most often associated with enteric infections but may be found in other forms such as diarrhea and pneumonia. The toxin binds to proteins that are important in digestion, leading to tissue damage and disease. Infections can be fatal, especially if prolonged. BoNT toxins cause mild inflammation, which makes breathing difficult or death more likely. Bromine ( Bromide ) is an aliphatic derivative of hydrochloric acid which has multiple functions.

Eric Arthur Heiden (born June 14, 1958) is an American physician and a former long track speed skater, road cyclist and track cyclist. He won an unprecedented five individual gold medals, and set four Olympic records and one world record at the 1980 Winter Olympic Games. Heiden was the most successful athlete at those Olympic Games, single-handedly winning more gold medals than all nations except for the Soviet Union (10) and East Germany (9). He is the most successful Winter Olympian from a single edition of any Winter Olympics. He delivered the Athlete's Oath at those same 1980 Games.

Optical rotation , also known as polarization rotation or circular birefringence , is the rotation of the orientation of the sun relative to the celestial equator. Polarization means that the plane of the solar disk (or "solar frame") always faces toward the celestial equator; it is a term used by mathematicians, and cosmologists, to refer to the apparent direction of an object facing its own axis. The European Space Agency ("ESA") is a multi-stakeholder space organisation within the European Union dedicated to establishing and maintaining European space technologies for the benefit of humanity and society worldwide.

Events January–June January 7 – The Westminster Assembly begins debating the biblical proof texts , to support the new Confession . January 9 – John Damascene is ordained as the fifth abbé of Canterbury Cathedral, where he is also canonised as a saint (later canonised as a saint by Pope St. Leo I and Saint John IV ). January 11 – On the evening of January 11, 1748, Jean Baptiste de Saint-Clair, the Marquise de Saguenay, the Archbishop of Paris, and many other prominent members of society and government attend a mass in favor of marriage reform.

Year 1342 ( MCCCXLII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Christian era in medieval Europe. It began on 7 December, 1443 and ended on 15 February, 1547, when it marked the beginning of the Long Council of Florence, which is commonly referred to as the "Great Council of Lyons". The Medieval Calendar is an official calendar adopted in 1452 by the Roman Empire, the Principate of Castile, and the Holy Roman Empire. It marks the year 1342 from 11 November until 2 January.

Events January–March January 11 – 1693 Sicily earthquake : Mount Etna erupts , causing a devastating earthquake that affects parts of Italy, Greece, Turkey, and northwestern Africa. Etymology  The word  is from the Old English  (originally) meaning "to break or to destroy" or "to shake off or away." The Old English  had its origin in Germanic languages; it was later replaced by  in English. The Latin  came into common speech in the second half of the sixteenth century, after the Reformation in the 14th century, when ecclesiastical authorities began using it to refer to things they disapproved of, including heresy.

Year 1337 (MCCCXXXVII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 16 – Edward, the Black Prince establishes the Duchy of Cornwall, becoming the first English Duke. May 24 – Philip VI of France confiscates Gascony from English control. August – English forces relieve Stirling Castle, ending Edward III of England's last campaign in Scotland. October – Hundred Years' War: Edward III of England formally rejects Philip VI's claim to the French throne, initiating hostilities between France and England.

In metaphysics, extension signifies both 'stretching out' (Latin: extensio) as well as later 'taking up space', and most recently, spreading one's internal mental cognition into the external world.The history of thinking about extension can be traced back at least to Archytas' spear analogy for the infinity of space. How far can one's hand or spear stretch out until it reaches the edge of reality? “If I arrived at the outermost edge of the heaven, could I extend my hand or staff into what is outside or not?

Year 1051 (MLI) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Spring – William of Normandy consolidates his power in Normandy. He fights over the control of Maine (after the death of Count Hugh IV), and lays siege to the fortresses of Alençon and Domfront (Western France). May 19 – King Henry I of France marries Anne of Kiev at the cathedral of Reims. William of Normandy marries Matilda of Flanders, daughter of Count Baldwin V, which Henry sees as a threat to his throne.

The governor of Montana is the head of government of Montana and the commander-in-chief of the state's military forces. The governor has a duty to enforce state laws, the power to either approve or veto bills passed by the Montana State Legislature, to convene the legislature at any time, and to grant pardons and reprieves.The current Montana Constitution, ratified in 1972, calls for a 4-year term for the governor, commencing on the first Monday in January following an election. The governor is term-limited to 8 years in any 16-year period. The constitution provides for the election of a lieutenant governor for the same term as the governor.

Dari ( , , ) , or Dari Persian , is a political term used for the various dialects of the Persian language, which are widely spoken and understood across Iran. It is used to describe the ethnic and cultural origin of those speaking Iranian. The International Confederation of Red Cross ( ), also known by its Latin abbreviation IVRC, was founded on October 14, 1951 in Brussels, Belgium, as an intergovernmental organization with a mission to provide aid to refugees and displaced persons in the United Nations World Heritage Site in Lesbos.

Robert von Ranke Graves (24 July 1895 – 7 December 1985) was a British poet, historical novelist and critic. His father was Alfred Perceval Graves, a celebrated Irish poet and figure in the Gaelic revival; they were both Celticists and students of Irish mythology. Graves produced more than 140 works in his lifetime. His poems, his translations and innovative analysis of the Greek myths, his memoir of his early life—including his role in World War I—Good-Bye to All That, and his speculative study of poetic inspiration The White Goddess have never been out of print.

Observations show that the expansion of the universe is accelerating, such that the velocity at which a distant galaxy recedes from the observer is continuously increasing with time.The accelerated expansion was discovered during 1998, by two independent projects, the Supernova Cosmology Project and the High-Z Supernova Search Team, which both used distant type Ia supernovae to measure the acceleration. The idea was that as type Ia supernovae have almost the same intrinsic brightness (a standard candle), and since objects that are further away appear dimmer, we can use the observed brightness of these supernovae to measure the distance to them.

Year 1378 ( MCCCLXXVIII ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) in Europe. It was an international holiday celebrated by various nations, primarily England, France, Germany, Italy, Denmark, Russia, Spain, Poland, Sweden, Norway, Portugal, Ireland, Finland and the United States of America.It is considered to be one of the best known holidays among Christians. The festival dates back to at least AD 1485 when St. Michael of Córdoba's feast was celebrated during this year.

Events < onlyinclude > January–June January 17 – The Treaty of Königsberg is signed , establishing an alliance between Charles V of Austria and Denmark. March–April April 18 – Emperor Franz Ferdinand is killed in a plane crash outside Sarajevo. May–June June 24 – French forces occupy the Dutch city of Rotterdam, but do not take over the city itself until August.August 26 – King Philip II of Spain marries Anne of Austria. History [ edit ]
The Middle Ages (also called the Early Middle Ages or Middle Ages) started with the death of Constantine I.

Arthrobacter ( from the Greek , `` jointed small stick ” ) is a genus of bacteria that is commonly found living in freshwater aquatic environments. There are around 30,000 species, and some are known to have been domesticated and used in food production over the past 70 million years.The genus Thaumaturgus belongs to a diverse group of bacteria known collectively as thaumaturgs, which can be divided into two distinct phyla, namely Archaea and Phylum Bacteria. This classification was proposed in the early 1960s, and many different groups continue to apply their principles to archaean organisms. The taxonomy of phylum-bound ichthyosporidium was established in 1975 by the Ichićevoćić family.

Panettone (, ;  ) is an Italian type of sweet bread originally from Milan, usually prepared and enjoyed for Christmas and New Year in Western, Southern, and Southeastern Europe as well as in South America, Eritrea, Australia, the United States and Canada.It has a cupola shape, which extends from a cylindrical base and is usually about 12–15 cm high for a panettone weighing 1 kg. Other bases may be used, such as an octagon, or a frustum with a star section shape more common to pandoro. It is made during a long process that involves curing the dough, which is acidic, similar to sourdough.

Events January–March January 8 – Carolean Death March begins : A catastrophic retreat by a largely-Finnish Swedish-Carolean army under the leadership of King Karl III of Sweden. The collapse of his army and the occupation of Finland by the Ottomans lead to the Treaty of Fontana, which ended the Finns' status as a republic in 1803. November 19 – November 21 October 23 – General Henry "Hank" Mackinaw is ambushed on his way home from a fishing trip on Lake Michigan while hunting for a walleye. He survives and is later buried in the St. Clair County Cemetery, just north of Kalamazoo.

Year 1344 (MCCCXLIV) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 26 – Reconquista: The Siege of Algeciras (1342–44), one of the first European military engagements where gunpowder is used, ends with the Muslim city of Algeciras surrendering and being incorporated into the Kingdom of Castile. April 17 – Constantine II, King of Armenia, is killed in an uprising and succeeded by a distant cousin, Constantine III. April 23 – The St. George's Night Uprising: The Livonian Order hangs Vesse, the rebel Estonian Elder of Saaremaa Island.

Élie Ducommun ( 19 February 1833 , Geneva – 7 December 1906 , Bern ) was a Swiss peace activist, diplomat, politician and philosopher. His writings have often been used as a basis for criticism of the war on foreign soil, especially the Great War in which he served. In his early years at Geneva, when Ducommun was only eighteen years old, he was one of few young people attending school there. Eliza Mather ( 29 April 1862 – 27 October 1925 ) was an Australian poet, playwright, essayist and editor.

Year 1208 (MCCVIII) was a leap year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events By place  Asia  April 15 – A fire breaks out in the Song Chinese capital city of Hangzhou, raging for four days and nights, destroying 58,097 houses over an area of more than , killing 59 people, and an unrecorded number of other people, who are trampled while attempting to flee. The government provides temporary lodging for 5,345 people, in nearby Buddhist and Taoist monasteries. The collective victims of the disaster are given 160,000 strings of cash, along with 400 tons of rice.

Events  January–June  March – The Synod of Jerusalem brings together bishops and representatives from the whole of Eastern Orthodox Christendom, to discuss Orthodox dogma against the challenge of Protestantism. March 15 – Charles II of England issues the Royal Declaration of Indulgence, suspending execution of Penal Laws against Protestant nonconformists and Roman Catholics in his realms; this will be withdrawn the following year under pressure from the Parliament of England. March 17 – Third Anglo-Dutch War: The Kingdom of England declares war on the Dutch Republic. April 8 – France declares war on the Dutch Republic, invading the country on April 29.

Year 1271 (MCCLXXI) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  July 2 – Kings Otakar II of Bohemia and Stephen V of Hungary sign the first Peace of Pressburg, settling territorial claims, following the failed invasion of Hungary by Otakar II. September 1 – Pope Gregory X succeeds Pope Clement IV as the 184th pope, as the compromise candidate between French and Italian cardinals, ending a three-year conclave, the longest ever. The County of Toulouse is returned to the crown of France.

The Caucasus , or Caucasia , is a region between the Black Sea and the Caspian Sea , mainly occupied by the Russian-administered portion of the former USSR. The term Caucasus can be used to designate any area in the region with a population of more than 500,000.HistoryThe Caucasus was one of the most populous regions of central Asia after its incorporation into the Soviet Union. By the late nineteenth century, it had become the third-largest country in Central Asia (after Russia and Uzbekistan) and one of the major trading hubs of the vast Eurasian steppes, which extended from Turkmenistan in the southwest to Kazakhstan in the southeast.

Palermo ( , ;  , locally also  or ; , from ; older ) is a city in southern Italy, the capital of both the autonomous region of Sicily and the Metropolitan City of Palermo, the city's surrounding metropolitan province. The city is noted for its history, culture, architecture and gastronomy, playing an important role throughout much of its existence; it is over 2,700 years old. Palermo is in the northwest of the island of Sicily, by the Gulf of Palermo in the Tyrrhenian Sea.The city was founded in 734 BC by the Phoenicians as  ("flower").

Events  January–March  January 10 – England and the Dutch Republic sign a mutual defense treaty in order to fight against France. January 27 – The first fire engine company (in what will become the United States) goes into service. February 18 – The first part of English nonconformist preacher John Bunyan's Christian allegory, The Pilgrim's Progress, is published in London. March 6 – King Charles II of England opens his third Parliament. March 21 – Thomas Shadwell's comedy, A True Widow, is given its first performance, debuting at The Duke's Theatre and staged by the Duke's Company.

Year 1379 (MCCCLXXIX) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December  May 29 – John I succeeds his father, Henry II, as King of Castile and King of León. June 30 – New College, Oxford, is founded in England by William of Wykeham, Bishop of Winchester. July 1 – Forces of the Republic of Venice and Ottoman Turks, having invaded Constantinople, restore John V Palaiologos as Byzantine co-emperor. Andronikos IV Palaiologos is allowed to remain as co-emperor, but is confined to the city of Silivri for the remainder of his life.

The Hubble Space Telescope ( often referred to as HST or Hubble ) is a space telescope that was launched aboard the shuttle Discovery in December 2001. Its purpose was to observe distant galaxies and other interstellar objects, which would help astronomers figure out how galaxies interact with each other. Since its inception, it has seen nearly 100 billion galaxies, making it the largest visible universe observatory ever designed. The telescope is now located at Mauna Kea in Hawaii. Highlands of the Andes Mountains range from southern Spain all the way down to northern Argentina.

Hawaii Five-O is an American police procedural drama series produced by CBS Productions and created by Leonard Freeman . Set in Hawaii, the show follows the exploits of the Kāhiheleke tribe as they try to protect their homeland from a foreign threat.The series first premiered on January 31st, 1995, and ran for 14 seasons from 1995 to 1999. During that time it averaged more than 1.5 million viewers with a total episode count of 3,093. It was also the most-watched comedy series in the history of syndicated television. The series has spawned several spinoffs, both feature films, theatrical shorts, miniseries, web shorts, and live-action adaptations.

Year 1239 ( MCCXXXIX ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) for the Roman Catholic Church as well as the Lutheran Church of Christ. The church held the first mass, Easter Vigil, on March 7, 1307 and celebrated Masses three times each week for the next thirty years, ending with the Feast of the Annunciation , which marks the date that Mary was declared to have been "the Son of God" by Pope Urban II in 1342. Fashion  is the art of transforming one's clothes into other clothing to fit the appearance and/or style of a particular person or place.

Year 1567 (MDLXVII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–June  January – A Spanish force under the command of Captain Juan Pardo establishes Fort San Juan, in the Native American settlement of Joara. The fort is the first European settlement in present-day North Carolina. January 20 – Battle of Rio de Janeiro: Portuguese forces under the command of Estácio de Sá definitively drive the French out of Rio de Janeiro. January 23 – After 45 years' reign, the Jiajing Emperor dies in the Forbidden City of China.

Year 1541 (MDXLI) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  February 12 – Pedro de Valdivia founds Santiago del Nuevo Extremo, which will become the capital of Chile. April 7 – Francis Xavier leaves Lisbon, on a mission to the Portuguese East Indies. April 24 – Battle of Sahart: Gelawdewos is defeated by the forces of Imam Ahmad ibn Ibrahim al-Ghazi. May 8 – Spanish explorer Hernando de Soto reaches the Mississippi River, naming it the Rio de Espiritu Santo ("River of the Holy Spirit").

A killer is someone or something that kills, such as a murderer or a serial killer. Killer or The Killer may also refer to:Arts, entertainment, and mediaFictional characters Killer (Home and Away), a character from Home and Away Killer Kane, the villain of the 1939 Buck Rogers film serial Ghostface (Scream), aka "The Killer" - the murderer in the Scream movie seriesFilms The Killer (1921 film), an American western film directed by and starring Jack Conway (filmmaker) The Killer (1953 film), a Turkish adventure film Killer!

Year 1435 ( MCDXXXV ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) for the period between Sunday and Friday. It is known in many medieval communities as the day of resurrection. The festival took place on December 14, 1536, when bishops gathered together at the church of St John Chrysostom to commemorate the resurrection of Christ.The feast began with mass at 6 p.m. Masses were typically held on Christmas Day, or on Easter Sunday. At the end of Lent, the bishop gave a reading from the liturgy before the usual mass.

Year 1361 (MCCCLXI) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 17 – An-Nasir Hasan, Mamluk Sultan of Egypt, is killed by one of his own mamluks, Yalbugha al-Umari, who, with the senior Mamluk emirs, has al-Mansur Muhammad installed as the new sultan. April 13 – The University of Pavia is founded, on the Italian Peninsula. July 27 – Battle of Visby: King Valdemar IV of Denmark conquers the city of Visby by defeating his peasant army. This allows Lübeck to become the new leading city of the Hanseatic League.

Year 1443 ( MCDXLIII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending Monday ( link will display the day) in the Gregorian calendar system. It was used by most of North America from the 19th century to about 1885. An event is an activity or process that results in a change in the social status of others. Social status may increase after an event, such as winning an election, getting an academic degree, or being appointed to leadership positions at a company or institution.

Frederick II of Brandenburg ( 19 November 1413 – 10 February 1471 ) , nicknamed `` the Iron '' (after his armor), was German Emperor from 1427 to 1484.He ruled over the Empire for twelve years between 1426 and 1444, ending his reign in 1456. He is often regarded as the father of modern German political thought. He was also the founder and leader of the Prussian state, the Holy Roman Empire . During his reign he established a form of Christian constitutional monarchy that lasted nearly until his own death on 11 January 1464.

Anne Boleyn (;  1501 – 19 May 1536) was Queen of England from 1533 to 1536, as the second wife of King Henry VIII. The circumstances of her marriage and of her execution by beheading for treason and other charges made her a key figure in the political and religious upheaval that marked the start of the English Reformation. Anne was the daughter of Thomas Boleyn, 1st Earl of Wiltshire, and his wife, Lady Elizabeth Howard, and was educated in the Netherlands and France, largely as a maid of honour to Queen Claude of France.

Greyhound racing is an organized, competitive sport in which greyhounds are raced around a track. There are two forms of greyhound racing, track racing (normally around an oval track) and coursing, the latter is now banned in most countries. Track racing uses an artificial lure (usually a form of windsock) that travels ahead of the greyhounds on a rail until the greyhounds cross the finish line. As with horse racing, greyhound races often allow the public to bet on the outcome.In many countries greyhound racing is purely amateur and solely for enjoyment.

Robert Sanderson Mulliken ( June 7 , 1896 – October 31 , 1986 ) was an American physicist and chemist. He invented the electro-hydrogen gas theory of condensation and his work is still considered by many to be one of the major contributions to thermodynamics.He was a member of the American Philosophical Association until its dissolution in 1947, when he became president of the American Institute of Physics.Sanderson developed the theories of condensed matter and atomic theory in the late 19th century. He proposed that particles of the same kind can condense into different states, while other atoms can separate from each other without splitting.

Wenceslaus IV ( also Wenceslas ; ; , nicknamed `` the Idle '' ; 26 February 136116 August 1419 ) was a Hungarian king who reigned from 1426 until his death in 1484. In his reign, Hungary continued its rule over most of Western Europe as the first fully developed democratic republic. He was regarded as the founder of the modern liberal-conservative movement and is considered the founding father of European history. As head of the Roman Empire, he established many reforms, particularly on the economy and the state, including the so-called "Law of Twelve Tables."

The Duchy of Anjou (, ; ; ) was a French province straddling the lower river Loire. Its capital was Angers and it was roughly coextensive with the diocese of Angers. Anjou was bordered by Brittany to the west, Maine to the north, Touraine to the east and Poitou to the south. The adjectival form is Angevin, and inhabitants of Anjou are known as Angevins. In 1482, the duchy became part of the Kingdom of France, and from then remained a province of the Kingdom under the name of the Duchy of Anjou.

Reginald Joseph Mitchell CBE, FRAeS, (20 May 189511 June 1937) was a British aircraft designer who worked for the Southampton aviation company Supermarine from 1917 to 1936. He is best remembered for designing racing seaplanes such as the  Supermarine S.6B, and the Supermarine Spitfire.Born in Butt Lane, Staffordshire, Mitchell attended Hanley High School and afterwards worked as an apprentice at a locomotive engineering works, whilst also studying engineering and mathematics at night. In 1917 he joined Supermarine, where he was appointed Chief Engineer in 1920 and Technical Director in 1927.

The human leg , in the general word sense , is the entire lower limb of the human body , including the upper legs and other limbs. Humans have six main parts: the foot, ankle, knee, hip, ribcage, thorax, and back. In mathematics, the inverse square root of 2 is called the eigenvalue of a function , and it's also commonly referred to as eigenvectors.Eigenvector notation is based on Eigenfunctions, an algebraic notation that allows expressing eigenvalues of functions by expressions which are derivatives of another expression. It also allows for simplifying computations involving polynomials.Eigenvectors can be regarded as two-dimensional structures.

Year 1434 ( MCDXXXIV ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Saturday. It was also one of the three most important calendars used in Spain to calculate the average length of each day of the week by counting from the beginning of the next day until its close. The year started on the 25th day of April (the first day of March), as usual, and ended on the 6th of May. Its name comes not only from the date of its introduction, but also from the way that the days are divided into groups.

Year 1037 ( MXXXVII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the reign of Justinian and ending on August 21, AD 753.The calendar has been described as "perfect" by both ancient and modern researchers, though there are several problems that may impact its accuracy. First, it depends on the dates of leap years; this is especially true for those of Roman times. This can vary considerably from one calendar to another, with some being slightly off and some more accurate than others.

A Roman villa was typically a farmhouse or country house built in the Roman Republic and the Roman Empire, sometimes reaching extravagant proportions.Typology and distributionPliny the Elder (23–79 AD) distinguished two kinds of villas near Rome: the villa urbana, a country seat that could easily be reached from Rome (or another city) for a night or two; and the villa rustica, the farmhouse estate permanently occupied by the servants who generally had charge of the estate. The Roman Empire contained many kinds of villas, not all of them lavishly appointed with mosaic floors and frescoes.

Louis I, also Louis the Great (; ; ) or Louis the Hungarian (; 5 March 132610 September 1382), was King of Hungary and Croatia from 1342 and King of Poland from 1370. He was the first child of Charles I of Hungary and his wife, Elizabeth of Poland, to survive infancy. A 1338 treaty between his father and Casimir III of Poland, Louis's maternal uncle, confirmed Louis's right to inherit the Kingdom of Poland if his uncle died without a son. In exchange, Louis was obliged to assist his uncle to reoccupy the lands that Poland had lost in previous decades.

Events January–June January 8 – The Jesuit educational plan , known as the Ratio Studiorum , is issued . March 7 – Cardinal John Burke (later Archbishop of Rochester) becomes Archbishop of St. Louis, in what is now Saint Louis. September 14 – An Act of Parliament makes England the sole British protectorate in Ireland for the next sixty years.January 15 – Pope Leo X renounces all rights of the Holy Roman Emperor to the Spanish crown.April 1 – Pope Clement VII departs for Italy after a long illness; he died on June 29, 1482.

Events < onlyinclude > January–March January 5 – King Charles II of England gives the title Duke of St Albans to George IV of France on his deathbed in 1425. August 1 – A new charter is issued authorizing the king to grant certain privileges to William and Mary, the mother and eldest daughter of Henry VI of England. February 6 – William III of Brittany becomes king of England. (August 13–14) June 12 – William I of Normandy wins a victory in the Battle of Acton, defeating the French army led by Louis IX of Navarre at the Battle of Bois de Lorraine.

Vanity Fair is an English novel by William Makepeace Thackeray , which follows the lives of Becky Sharp and Amelia Wells, sisters from a wealthy Irish family who are exiled from Ireland after their parents are murdered. Ricardo Carvalho (March 15, 1931 – April 16, 2004) was an Argentine writer, painter, and artist. He is largely known for his surrealist-influenced aesthetic that he explored both within his own art and as a member of the Buenos Aires based Futuristas Art Club . Carvalho was best known for his contributions to painting, collage, and graphic fiction.

Year 1046 ( MXLVI ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Middle Roman Empire in northwestern Italy. The event began on April 22 at sunset and ran until October 26, with the final day celebrating the birth of Emperor Domitian.The first days of the Gregorian calendar begin on Tuesday, June 7th, and finish on Thursday, July 19, with the last day of the Gregorian cycle ending on November 21. Gerry Adams is an American actor and politician, who served as governor of New Mexico from 2007 to 2017.

Year 1186 ( MCLXXXVI ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) at 9:01 A.T. (UTC) and ending at 5:02 A.T. (UTC). It was one of two major astronomical festivals, the other being the Summer Solstice Equinox , which takes place annually on June 19th (or May 21st, according to the time zone). The New World has many languages spoken in its present day, with Spanish the world's most commonly spoken native language, and Portuguese the third-most widely spoken language in the Americas following English and French.

Year 1408 ( MCDVIII ) was a leap year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) and lasting from Monday 29 November to Sunday 7 December. It was recognized by the International Year Booking Conference (IWBC) as one of the ten most important events of this century.The celebration began with the announcement that the English translation of Tocqueville's 1845 book What is Property was being published, although it had been postponed for some time due to financial constraints. This was followed by two public reading sessions in London at the Royal College of Surgeons, both of which drew more than one thousand speakers.

Year 1160 ( MCLX ) was a leap year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Sunday. It is the longest leap year in North America and the only one for which the date varies from month to month within each year. Papal States (  :  ,  ;  : ) are the sovereign authority of the Catholic Church in the world. They form part of the papal constitution or constitution dei Popolo; as an institution, it consists of the four constituent territories of the Holy See: the Papal States of Italy, Austria, Germany, and Poland.

Norwich is a town in Windsor County , in the U.S. state of Vermont . The population was 3,612 at the 2010 Census. History [ edit ]
The city was settled by English settlers to the middle of the 18th century and later incorporated into Connecticut. The oldest buildings dating to the 1760's are a church, a public square, and two municipal buildings. [1][2][3]The area was formerly an iron-plated coal mine until its closure in the late 1800s. It became part of the National Historic Preservation Act of 1966.

Mariner-H ( Mariner Mars '71 ) , also commonly known as Mariner 8 , was ( along with Mariner 9 ) the first spacecraft to visit a near-Earth object ( NEO ), which had been detected by previous expeditions. On March 20, 1971, they sent back a radio transmission from the comet Chelyabinsk . The discovery was hailed at the time as a major step in the quest for extraterrestrial life, and an example of humanity's scientific progress towards discovering alien life.On July 1, 1972, the Mariner 10 probes returned data regarding the impact of comets on asteroids and comets.

The transport in Azerbaijan involves air traffic , waterways and railroads . All transportation services in Azerbaijan except for oil are operated through the national railways. Transportation in the Republic of Azerbaijan by sea and air is provided by the Azerbaijani Maritime Transport Company (AMTOC), with the majority of the ship traffic originating in the port of Tbilisi or on the Azeri Gulf, while most other transports take place at the port of Caspian Sea terminals in the Black Sea. There are also several inland ferries run by the Russian Trans-Siberian Railways operating between Tbilisi and the capital city of Astrakhan, as well as to the ports of Minsk and Kuznetsov.

Events January–June January 22 – Impostor Mary Carleton is hanged at Newgate Prison in London , for multiple thefts and other crimes. She is the only woman to be imprisoned on death row, though some of her accomplices were executed later. February 16 – After years of efforts to secure a trial in the case of James Bond film villain Dr. Watson, British Prime Minister William Gladstone makes a speech to Parliament urging his countrymen to "support the progress of justice." The Speech is widely seen as signalling that Britain does not regard its own crime-fighting work with suspicion.

Escherichia coli , also known as E. coli , is a Gram-negative , facultative anaerobic , rod-shaped , coliform bacterium native to soil, water, plants, and other microorganisms. In nature, E. coli are the smallest of the eukaryotic bifurcates of bacteria. Ethanol is a naturally occurring carbon-based chemical compound found in the petroleum refining industry, which consists primarily of methane and propane. It is frequently used as a flavor additive, but has been identified as a carcinogen; it may also be carcinogenic to humans under certain circumstances.In the United States, ethanol is sold as corn ethanol, corn starch, and soybean oil, among other names.

The Zwinger  is a palatial complex with gardens in Dresden, Germany. Designed by architect Matthäus Daniel Pöppelmann, it is one of the most important buildings of the Baroque period in Germany. Along with the Frauenkirche, the Zwinger is the most famous architectural monument of Dresden. The name "Zwinger" goes back to the name used in the Middle Ages for a fortress part between the outer and inner fortress walls, even though the Zwinger no longer had a function corresponding to the name at the start of construction.The Zwinger was built in 1709 as an orangery and garden as well as a representative festival area.

Year 1165 (MCLXV) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos) makes an alliance with Venice against Emperor Frederick I (Barbarossa), who takes an oath at the Diet of Würzburg to support Antipope Paschal III against Pope Alexander III. Andronikos Komnenos, a cousin of Manuel I, escapes from prison at Constantinople. After passing through many dangers, he reaches Kiev and seeks refuge at the court of Prince Yaroslav Osmomysl.

Andorra , officially the Principality of Andorra , also called the Principality of the Valleys of Andorra < ref > ( ) is a country of the Netherlands in the north of Western Europe. It is the second largest country in Western Europe after France and Luxembourg. Although it is recognized as a nonmember state, Austria-Hungary is a member of the EU and a permanent member of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe. Hungary is governed by the Parliament of Hungary with a President elected by national referendum; however, this does not affect the power and decision-making process of the government or its policies.

In mathematics , open sets are a generalization of open intervals in the real line . In a metric space—that is, one in which the values of all possible open sets are the same—there are several ways for the value of a metric space to change: The initial value of an open interval that has been determined will change (usually by addition or subtraction from its initial value); or It can be set to a known value. The National Geographic Society is the world's largest privately-owned nonprofit organization dedicated to public interest science and research.

Year 1559 ( MDLIX ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Monday ( link will display the month list ). It had a 12-hour day and twelve hour noon to midnight local time offset. There are currently no known official figures as to how many British soldiers died during World War I, however it is believed that between 10% and 40% of British soldiers died in action. This figure may be lower if the war were not fought in Great Britain.

Hide-and-seek is a popular children's game in which at least two players (usually at least three) conceal themselves in a set environment, to be found by one or more seekers. The game is played by one chosen player (designated as being "it") counting to a predetermined number with eyes closed while the other players hide. After reaching this number, the player who is "it" calls "Ready or not, here I come!" or "Coming, ready or not!" and then attempts to locate all concealed players.The game can end in one of several ways.

Robert von Ranke Graves ( 24 July 1895 – 7 December 1985 ) was a British poet , historical novelist , and politician best known as the author of more than 150 novels and hundreds of short stories throughout the English-speaking world during the 20th and 21st centuries.His books, such as The Adventures of Huckleberry Finn and The Wind in the Willows, were widely praised and won a number of awards and nominations for best novel and best short story.He was one of Britain's most prominent Victorian poets.Graves died on 8 December at the age of 95 after a long illness.

Charles XV also Carl ( Carl Ludvig Eugen ) ; Swedish : Karl XV and Norwegian : Karl IV (1823–91), Carl Ludwig von Waldauf ( 1825–1909), Carl Ludwig von Waldorf (1832–1909)
(born October 7, 1921; died January 27, 1992) is the author of more than a dozen novels, including several science fiction novels, which have appeared in more than twenty languages.Born into a Russian Jewish family in Vienna and raised as an orthodox Jewish child, his earliest books were written in the late 1920s when he had to stop school at age twelve.

The Fertile Crescent is a crescent-shaped region in the Middle East, spanning modern-day Iraq, Syria, Lebanon, Palestine, Israel, Jordan, and Northern Egypt, together with the northern region of Kuwait, southeastern region of Turkey and the western portion of Iran. Some authors also include Cyprus.The region is one of the cradles of civilization because it is one location where settled farming first emerged as people started the process of clearance and modification of natural vegetation to grow newly domesticated plants as crops. Early human civilizations such as Sumer in Mesopotamia flourished as a result.

Year 1046 (MXLVI) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Autumn – King Henry III (the Black) travels to Italy to secure the imposition of Guido da Velate, archbishop of Milan, and other similarly loyal candidates in other sees (like Ravenna, Verona and Modena). Vatha Pagan Revolt: King Peter Orseolo (the Venetian) is overthrown after a 2-year reign. Bishops Gerard of Csanád and Bystrík (or Bestricus) are stoned to death in Budapest (Hungary).

Anne Boleyn ( ; 1501 – 19 May 1536 ) was Queen of England from 1533 to 1536 , as her son Henry III succeeded her father as reigning King of England after his death. She was the wife and mother of Edward VI, eldest son of Edward IV, Duke of Gloucester. Tina Fey is a British stage actress who has acted in many roles over the last 20 years. She won three Tony Awards for Best Actress in 2003 for The Little Mermaid, then won four more in 2008 for The Fairly OddParents.

Year 1325 (MCCCXXV) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 7 – Afonso IV becomes King of Portugal. February – Muhammad bin Tughluq succeeds his father Ghiyath al-Din Tughluq, as Sultan of Delhi. July – War of the Bucket breaks out: Modena makes incursions into the territory of Bologna. November 15 – Battle of Zappolino: Modena defeats Bologna. Date unknown  The town of Bolu is conquered by the Ottoman Empire. Ibn Battuta begins his travels. Mansa Musa completes his pilgrimage to Mecca.

Year 1328 (MCCCXXVIII) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January 24 – Philippa of Hainault marries King Edward III of England a year after his coronation. The marriage produces ten children, the eldest of whom is Edward the Black Prince. May 1 – Treaty of Edinburgh–Northampton: England recognises Scotland as an independent nation, after the Wars of Scottish Independence. May 12 – Antipope Nicholas V is consecrated at St. Peter's Basilica in Rome by the bishop of Venice. May 26 – William of Ockham secretly leaves Avignon, under threat from Pope John XXII.

The term chat room , or chatroom ( and sometimes group chat ; abbreviated as GC ) , is primarily used for online discussion between members of a network of computers, typically on a private computer. The use of the term has also been used in some academic contexts, including to describe groups of students who share computing time and information; it is thus commonly associated with such networks.GC is a term that can be applied to virtually any form of online communication, but its primary uses are in the context of social networking sites and forums like Facebook and LinkedIn.

In geometry, two figures or objects are congruent if they have the same shape and size, or if one has the same shape and size as the mirror image of the other.More formally, two sets of  points are called congruent if, and only if, one can be transformed into the other by an isometry, i.e., a combination of rigid motions, namely a translation, a rotation, and a reflection. This means that either object can be repositioned and reflected (but not resized) so as to coincide precisely with the other object.

Stigmata ( , plural of , 'mark , spot , brand ' ) , in Christianity , are the appearance of something, or a person, in God's eyes. Geography  is a science of the geographical sciences, encompassing information theory, geology, hydrology, and atmospheric physics, as well as geological analysis and cartography.The field has broad roots in the Middle Ages, although it has often been influenced by many other disciplines.Geography in Western civilization is concerned primarily with mapping and geographic information systems. Most modern maps are based on trigonometric techniques, especially those developed at the turn of the 20th century.

Year 1151 ( MCLI ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Tuesday. It was one of only two exceptions to the fixed date calendar system that began in the 12th century, replacing it with a solar-powered lunar calendar which had no fixed date. The European Union ( EU ) is a member state of the European Economic Community (EEC) and the United Nations. The EU consists of 19 member states, including the remaining 13 countries of the former Soviet Union.

Year 1198 (MCXCVIII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place The volcano was formed around 4000 years ago and last erupted in 1198 during a phreatic eruption - a powerful steam eruption caused by groundwater interacting with magma. Europe  March 8 – Philip of Swabia, son of the late Emperor Frederick I, is elected "King of Germany" by his supporters at Mühlhausen in Thuringia. Archbishop Adolf of Cologne elects Otto of Brunswick, son of Henry the Lion, as Philip's rival.

J. Robert Oppenheimer ( ; April 22 , 1904 – February 18 , 1967 ) was an American theoretical physicist who served as the United States National Aeronautics and Space Administration Administrator from January 1, 1958 to January 1, 1963. Oppenheimer was the highest-ranking American in the U.S. Atomic Energy Commission at that time, having held various posts throughout the agency during the post-World War II space race. During his career, he developed many of the basic ideas that would lead to the modern nuclear power plant.A prolific writer and essayist for more than half a century, Oppenheimer was inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in 1999.

DeCSS is one of the first free computer programs capable of decrypting content on a commercially produced DVD video disc (CD, Blu-ray, digital HD or other file format). It was created by Ken Wharton in 1974 and is still in use.In 1997, the United States Department of Commerce named it an "Implementing Technical Assistance Award winner." The International Association for Computing Machinery (AIAMC), abbreviated IACM or IEEE Computer Machining Society, is a trade organization established by the American Society of Information Systems (ASEI) in 1982. The group's primary purpose is to promote cooperation in the area of computer science.

Year 1569 ( MDLXIX ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) which was celebrated by the English royal family from 17 November to 24 January. It marked the end of the reign of Edward I of England and the coronation of King John VI, who ascended to the throne on 1 February 1560. Bartlett , David  (; ; 9 February 1573 – 25 May 1599) was an English painter and sculptor. His career as a portraitist, known in his time as Bartlett, spanned more than a century.

Year 1350 (MCCCL) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 9 – Giovanni II Valente becomes Doge of Genoa. May 23 – A number of supporters of William V, Count of Holland, in his power struggle with his mother Margaret I, Countess of Holland, found the Cod League. August 29 – Battle of Les Espagnols sur Mer off Winchelsea: An English fleet personally commanded by King Edward III defeats a Castilian fleet. September 5 – Conservative noblemen in the County of Holland found the Hook League.

Jan Bos (born 29 March 1975) is a Dutch speedskater and sprint cyclist. In the late 1990s he was world champion in speed skating and he competed in the 1998 and 2002 Winter Olympics.Speed skaterIn 1998 Bos both became the world champion sprint and won the silver medal that year in the 1000 meter sprint during the Winter Olympics in Nagano. He won the silver medal on that same distance in Salt Lake City.He competed at the 2004 Summer Olympics in Athens in the team sprint track cycling event, together with his brother Theo Bos, who won the silver at the individual sprint, and Teun Mulder.

Ice hockey at the 2002 Winter Olympics was held at the E Center in West Valley City and Peaks Ice Arena in Provo, Utah. The men's and women's tournaments were won by Canada, who defeated the host United States in both finals.Medal summaryMedal tableMedalistsMen's tournamentQualifyingThe final standings at the end of the 1999 IIHF World Championship were used to determine the path to the Olympic tournament. The top six places were given direct entry to the first round, places seven and eight were given direct entry to the preliminary round, and all other participants were seeded in qualifying tournaments to fill the remaining six spots.

Year 1031 ( MXXXI ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Sunday of this week. The first three Sundays of each month were considered Saturdays for purposes of religious observance. In the vernacular of the Roman Empire, the term "day of the Lord" was also referred to as  Day of Repentance.The celebration began with the feast of Easter at midnight. The following days were known as Pascha or Yule in the Old Roman Empire: Aries, Scorpio, Libra, Sagittarius, Cancer, Leo, Capricorn, Virgo, Aquarius and Taurus.

Mariner 3 (together with Mariner 4 known as Mariner-Mars 1964) was one of two identical deep-space probes designed and built by the Jet Propulsion Laboratory (JPL) for NASA's Mariner-Mars 1964 project that were intended to conduct close-up (flyby) scientific observations of the planet Mars and transmit information on interplanetary space and the space surrounding Mars, televised images of the Martian surface and radio occultation data of spacecraft signals as affected by the Martian atmosphere back to Earth.Although the launch was initially successful, there was a separation issue and Mariner 3 stopped responding when its batteries ran out of power.

A conjugate acid, within the Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory, is a  chemical compound formed when an acid donates a proton (H+) to a base—in other words, it is a base with a hydrogen ion added to it, as in the reverse reaction it loses a hydrogen ion. On the other hand, a conjugate base is what is left over after an acid has donated a proton during a chemical reaction. Hence, a conjugate base is a species formed by the removal of a proton from an acid, as in the reverse reaction it is able to gain a hydrogen ion.

In the performing arts, a scenario (, ; from Italian: "that which is pinned to the scenery", ) is a synoptical collage of an event or series of actions and events. In the commedia dell'arte it was an outline of entrances, exits, and action describing the plot of a play, and was literally pinned to the back of the scenery. It is also known as canovaccio  or "that which is pinned to the canvas" of which the scenery was constructed.Surviving scenarios from the Renaissance contain little other than character names, brief descriptions of action, and references to specific lazzi with no further explanation.

Year 1419 (MCDXIX) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 19 – Hundred Years' War: Rouen surrenders to Henry V of England, which brings Normandy under the control of England. June 20 – The Ōei Invasion of Tsushima Island, Japan by Joseon Korea begins. July 30 – The first Defenestration of Prague occurs in Bohemia. August – Siege of Ceuta: The Portuguese successfully defend off the invading Moroccans who attempt to retake the city of Ceuta. September 10 – John the Fearless, Duke of Burgundy is assassinated by adherents of the Dauphin.

In the Swedish calendar it was a common year starting on Friday, one day ahead of the Julian and ten days behind the Gregorian calendar.Events  January–March  January 1 – Battle of St. John's: The French capture St. John's, the capital of the British colony of Newfoundland. January 6 – Western Europe's Great Frost of 1709, the coldest period in 500 years, begins during the night, lasting three months, with its effects felt for the entire year. In France, the Atlantic coast and Seine River freeze, crops fail, and 24,000 Parisians die.

A pine is any conifer tree or shrub in the genus Pinus  of the family Pinaceae. Pinus is the sole genus in the subfamily Pinoideae. The Plant List compiled by the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew and Missouri Botanical Garden accepts 126 species names of pines as current, together with 35 unresolved species and many more synonyms. The American Conifer Society (ACS) and the Royal Horticultural Society accept 121 species. Pine may also refer to the lumber derived from pine trees; pine is one of the more extensively used types of wood used as lumber.

Year 1548 ( MDXLVIII ) was a leap year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) from January 14th, 1548 until April 24th, 1548. It was held annually during the 12 months of June and July to mark the transition from winter solstice to summer equinox in the eastern hemisphere. In Greek mythology, Apollo is a god of the sky. Apollo was the first of the twelve Olympiads and one of the ten gods who ruled the Milky Way between 300 BC and 500 AD. He inspired the epic poem Theaetetus, which began with the famous phrase "Aphrodite born.

Operetta is a form of theatre and a genre of light opera. It includes spoken dialogue, songs, and dances. It is lighter than opera in terms of its music, orchestral size, length of the work, and at face value, subject matter. Apart from its shorter length, the operetta is usually of a light and amusing character. It sometimes also includes satirical commentaries. "Operetta" is the Italian diminutive of "opera" and was used originally to describe a shorter, perhaps less ambitious work than an opera. Operetta provides an alternative to operatic performances in an accessible form targeting a different audience.

Digital electronics  is a field of electronics involving the study of digital signals and the engineering of devices that use or produce them. This is in contrast to analog electronics and analog signals.Digital electronic circuits are usually made from large assemblies of logic gates, often packaged in integrated circuits. Complex devices may have simple electronic representations of Boolean logic functions.HistoryThe binary number system was refined by Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz (published in 1705) and he also established that by using the binary system, the principles of arithmetic and logic could be joined. Digital logic as we know it was the brain-child of George Boole in the mid 19th century.

The Stoned Guest is a `` half-act opera '' by Peter Schickele in the satirical persona of P. D. Q. Mott. It takes place in New York City, in the 1920s, in an era marked by political unrest, economic stagnation, crime and social strife. I was born in East Germany on August 9, 1953 to a family of Polish Jewish emigrants from Poland who were forced to flee following the collapse of communism. I attended elementary school in Berlin, studying mathematics and engineering. During my junior high school career, I joined the Soviet Red Army as a combat engineer.

Events  January–June  January–June – The Swiss Peasant War is fought. January 3 – By the Coonan Cross Oath, the Eastern Church in India cuts itself off from colonial Portuguese tutelage. February 2 – New Amsterdam (later renamed New York City) is incorporated. February 3 – Cardinal Mazarin returns to Paris from exile. March 14 – A Dutch fleet defeats the English in the Battle of Leghorn; the Dutch commander, Johan van Galen, later dies of his wounds. April 20 – Oliver Cromwell expels the Rump Parliament in England.

Year 1301 ( MCCCI ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) in Scotland beginning on the 1st of September. It was also commonly known as "Luther's birthday".It was held annually from 14 October to 17 March, with the first three days commemorating King Arthur and his victory over the Saxons. History [ edit ]
Arthur is an Anglo-English king from the Carolingian period who fought for the Holy Roman Empire after the fall of the House of Frankish Kings in the Wars of the Roses.

Mai Elisabeth Zetterling (; 24 May 1925 – 17 March 1994) was a Swedish actress, novelist and film director.Early lifeZetterling was born in Västerås, Sweden to a working class family. She started her career as an actress at the age of 17 at Dramaten, the Swedish national theatre, appearing in war-era films.CareerZetterling appeared in film and television productions spanning six decades from the 1940s to the 1990s. Her breakthrough came in the 1944 film Torment written by Ingmar Bergman, in which she played a controversial role as a tormented shopgirl.

The human leg, in the general word sense, is the entire lower limb of the human body, including the foot, thigh and even the hip or gluteal region. However, the definition in human anatomy refers only to the section of the lower limb extending from the knee to the ankle, also known as the crus or, especially in non-technical use, the shank. Legs are used for standing, and all forms of locomotion including recreational such as dancing, and constitute a significant portion of a person's mass.

Abolitionism , or the abolitionist movement , was the movement to end slavery . In Western Europe and the Americas, it included movements from France and Britain, as well as other regions such as Italy and the Netherlands, who sought to abolish slavery; in the United States, they were largely led by William Lloyd Garrison, leader of the American Underground Railroad, and many of his followers. Some abolitionists held that slavery existed in all non-human animals and humans.The abolitionist movement gained widespread acceptance through the efforts of its leading figures, including Harriet Beecher Stowe and Samuel L. Jackson.

Year 1511 (MDXI) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  March 26 - The 1511 Idrija earthquake occurs, with a maximum Mercalli intensity of X (Extreme). The epicenter is around the town of Idrija in present-day Slovenia, although some place it some 15-20 kilometers to the west, between Gemona and Pulfero in Friulian Slovenia. The earthquake affects a large territory between Carinthia, Friuli, present-day Slovenia and Croatia. April 9 St John's College, Cambridge, England, founded by Lady Margaret Beaufort, receives its charter.The Şahkulu Rebellion breaks out in Anatolia.

Year 1020 (MXX) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  Summer – Emperor Henry II conducts his third Italian military campaign. He makes plans to invade the south, but remains non-commital. June 15 – Byzantine troops under Catepan Basil Boioannes (supported by his ally Prince Pandulf IV) capture the fortress of Troia. The French city of Saint-Germain-en-Laye is founded by King Robert II (the Pious). King Canute the Great codifies the laws of England (approximate date).

Year 1474 ( MCDLXXIV ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) from August to April of each year. It was the fourth-longest consecutive leap year in the modern history of the calendar, trailing only the  years 1751, 1800, and 1802. John Locke's Theory of Human Rights The Lockean theory of human rights posits that every person is entitled to live a life free of discrimination based on race, color, sex, disability or religion, as well as to be protected from all forms of government interference in their private lives.

Year 998 (CMXCVIII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Spring – Otto III retakes Rome and restores power in the papal city. Crescentius II (the Younger) and his followers barricade themselves in Castel Sant'Angelo. Otto's former tutor John Philagathos (Antipope John XVI), who tries to escape into Campania, is pursued by German troops and captured. He is horribly mutilated – his ears, nose and tongue cut off and his eyes are gouged out. Crescentius surrenders at his stronghold and is beheaded.

Events  June 16 – The deposed and imprisoned Mary, Queen of Scots, recognizes Philip II of Spain as her heir. July 6 – The Treaty of Berwick is signed between Queen Elizabeth I of England and King James VI of Scotland. July 21 – English explorer Thomas Cavendish begins the first deliberately planned circumnavigation of the globe. September 20–21 – Execution of the Babington Plotters: The 14 men convicted of a plot (uncovered on July 17) to murder Queen Elizabeth and replace her with Mary, Queen of Scots, are hanged, drawn and quartered (the first seven being disembowelled before death) in St Giles Field, London.

Year 1533 ( MDXXXIII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending Sunday, 31 October.
