It was in commemoration of the birth of Edward III of France, who became king of England in 1466 at Westminster Abbey.On 1 April 1609, an Act of Parliament gave King James VI of Scotland absolute power to appoint his own successor. In May 1611, King Henry II of England appointed his second son, Robert Dudley, Earl of Northumberland (Dudley married his cousin Elizabeth of York in December 1620), as High Steward of the Realm.

The hobby of collecting includes seeking , locating , acquiring , organizing , cataloging , displaying , storing , and exchanging information relating to various topics within a group or individual's interest or professional history. Collectors tend to be focused on items that they believe belong to their particular interests, usually in the field of firearms, knives, or other tools used in hunting. The word "collect" can refer to any kind of collecting activity, such as the hobby itself or related fields (such as music).There is no universally accepted definition of what constitutes a "collection."

A finite difference is a mathematical expression of the form . If a finite difference is divided by , one gets a difference quotient. The approximation of derivatives by finite differences plays a central role in finite difference methods for the numerical solution of differential equations, especially boundary value problems.The difference operator, commonly denoted  is the operator that maps a function  to the function  defined byA difference equation is a functional equation that involves the finite difference operator in the same way as a differential equation involves derivatives. There are many similarities between difference equations and differential equations, specially in the solving methods.

Andrew Stuart `` Andy '' Fastow ( born December 22 , 1961 ) is a convicted felon and former financier who was convicted of conspiracy to commit bank fraud and other crimes during the 1990s.He was also charged by the United States Attorney Office for the Eastern District of Tennessee with conspiracy to commit securities fraud, mail fraud, money laundering and money laundering conspiracy.Early life and educationFastow began his banking career in 1971 when he was employed as an executive assistant at a New York bank. He later earned a bachelor's degree in sociology from Columbia University.

In mathematics, open sets are a generalization of  open intervals in the real line. In a metric space—that is, when a distance function is defined—open sets are the sets that, with every point , contain all points that are sufficiently near to  (that is, all points whose distance to  is less than some value depending on ).More generally, one defines open sets as the members of a given collection of subsets of a given set, a collection that has the property of containing every union of its members, every finite intersection of its members, the empty set, and the whole set itself.

Year 1343 ( MCCCXLIII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) when the Roman Catholic Calendar was established at the beginning of June every year. It was replaced by the Gregorian calendar from 1848 onwards. The date is shown below in English with an abbreviation for Latin "Calendar della Reale" (link will display the calendar abbreviations).It was one of only five centuries to have a long period without a new lunar month during this period, the others being 1492-95, 1533-35, and 1763-75.

The Fertile Crescent is a crescent-shaped region in the Middle East , spanning modern-day Iraq , Syria , Lebanon , and Jordan and extending northwestward into the Mediterranean Sea . It covers an area roughly twice the size of Great Britain and consists mainly of highland plateau and lowland desert. Francisco de Mello ( December 15, 1797 – January 13, 1918) was an Italian Renaissance artist, painter, writer, dramatist, and poet whose paintings are best known for depicting scenes from the life of Gionetto d'Ascena, or Leonardo da Vinci.Mello died at his home in Milan on November 1, 1918 after a short illness.

Major League Baseball (MLB) is a professional baseball organization and the oldest major professional sports league in the world. , a total of 30 teams play in Major League Baseball—15 teams in the National League (NL) and 15 in the American League (AL)—with 29 in the United States and 1 in Canada. The NL and AL were formed in 1876 and 1901, respectively. Beginning in 1903, the two leagues signed the National Agreement and cooperated but remained legally separate entities until 2000 when they merged into a single organization led by the Commissioner of Baseball.

The Witan , literally `` wise men '' , was the king 's council in Anglo-Saxon England from before the reign of the Old English kings Eadric, Harold and Alfred to the reign of Richard III (1167).Witan is the title of a man of considerable stature, with a reputation as one of the greatest rulers in England's history. A wælk is a unit of measurement used by scientists for measuring the weight of objects. One measure of a physical system is called an atomic unit (such as an electron or its mass).

Year 1342 (MCCCXLII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December  January 21–June 27 – An-Nasir Ahmad, Sultan of Egypt, rules prior to being deposed by his half-brother As-Salih Ismail. May 7 – Pope Clement VI succeeds Pope Benedict XII, as the 198th Pope. July 16 – Louis I becomes king of Hungary. July 18 – Battle of Zava: Mu'izz al-Din Husayn defeats the Sarbadars. July 22 – St. Mary Magdalene's flood is the worst such event on record for central Europe.

Sigismund ( 26 October 1427 – 4 March 1496 ) , a member of the House of Habsburg , was one of the four sons of Emperor Frederick III of Germany. He became Count of Trier and Baronet of Trier shortly after he was born, and held numerous political and financial posts throughout his lifetime. (born 19 May 1421 – 31 January 1495), better known as Henry VI (pronounced /herhˈeɪn/  ), was an English monarch who ruled from 1459 to 1499 during the Reign of George III. During the reign of George I, he spent the majority of his time leading England to victory in war with Spain.

Events  January–June  January 7 – The Westminster Assembly begins debating the biblical proof texts, to support the new Confession of Faith. January 16 – Citizens of Dublin declare their support for Rinuccini, and refuse to support the army of the Marquis of Ormond. March 14 – Thirty Years' War: Bavaria, Cologne, France and Sweden sign the Truce of Ulm. April 3 – In England, a letter from the Agitators of the New Model Army, protesting delay of pay, is read in the House of Commons. May 13 – The 1647 Santiago earthquake rattles Chile.

A Tesla coil is an electrical resonant transformer circuit designed by inventor Nikola Tesla in 1891. It is used to produce high-voltage, low-current, high frequency alternating-current electricity. Tesla experimented with a number of different configurations consisting of two, or sometimes three, coupled resonant electric circuits.Tesla used these circuits to conduct innovative experiments in electrical lighting, phosphorescence, X-ray generation, high frequency alternating current phenomena, electrotherapy, and the transmission of electrical energy without wires. Tesla coil circuits were used commercially in sparkgap radio transmitters for wireless telegraphy until the 1920s, and in medical equipment such as electrotherapy and violet ray devices.

Year 1502 ( MDII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the reign of King Frederick I and ending at sunrise on Tuesday, August 1714. The First World War began on 7 September 1918. It was the largest conflict in world history. Over one million men were killed, more than half the human race, and nearly half of all war fatalities were caused by aerial bombardments. During the war, some 15 million Allied soldiers and civilians died, while over 1.4 million German soldiers perished.

Year 1404 ( MCDIV ) was a leap year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Sunday, 25 February. It was considered an important religious date in Christian theology, particularly as it marks the end of the Roman Catholic Easter week. The year began on 2 April 1404, the fourth day of Leo XIII's papal pontificate, which also coincided with the anniversary of Pope Clement VIII's apostolic decrees. This article is a sub-category of History of the United States .For more information about the history of slavery see Slavery in the United States.

Year 1578 ( MDLXXVIII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Friday ( link ). It marks the end of the reign of Henry VIII, which saw the loss of the Protestant Reformation. His son, Henry III, was succeeded by his daughter, Edward I, who ruled until 1453, when their son, King Henry VII, died in battle near the Spanish Armada in North Africa.Edward I was succeeded by his two sons, Edward III and Edward IV. Edward VI remained the only English king to live to adulthood after his death in 1455.

Events  January–June  January – Six months into King Philip's War, Metacomet (King Philip), leader of the Algonquian tribe known as the Wampanoag, travels westward to the Mohawk nation, seeking an alliance with the Mohawks against the English colonists of New England; his efforts in creating such an alliance are a failure. January 29 – Feodor III becomes Tsar of Russia. January 31 – University of San Carlos of Guatemala, the oldest institution of higher education in Central America, was founded. February 10 – After the Nipmuc tribe attacks Lancaster, Massachusetts, colonist Mary Rowlandson is taken captive, and lives with the Indians until May.

.Year 1134 (MCXXXIV) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events By place Asia  Count Hugh II (du Puiset), in alliance with the Egyptian city of Ashkelon, revolts against King Fulk V of Jerusalem, attempting to take Jaffa. Hugh submits to Fulk and is exiled for three years. While awaiting for a boat to Italy he is attacked by a Breton knight, but survives the attempted murder. Hugh retires to the Sicilian court of his cousin, King Roger II, who appoints him with the lordship of Gargano, where he dies soon afterwards.

The 9th century BC started the first day of 900 BC and ended the last day of 801 BC. It was a period of great change for several civilizations. In Africa, Carthage is founded by the Phoenicians. In Egypt, a severe flood covers the floor of Luxor temple, and years later, a civil war starts.It is the beginning of the Iron Age in Central Europe, with the spread of the Proto-Celtic Hallstatt culture, and the Proto-Celtic language.Events890s BC  899 BC: The first year of King Yih of Zhou's reign is marked by a solar eclipse.

Charles Pierce ( July 14 , 1926 – May 31 , 1999 ) was one of the 20th century 's most influential writers and activists in the world of philosophy. Born in Boston, his father, John Pape Pierce Sr., was a founding member of the Boston Philosophical Society. His mother, Katharine, was an attorney. He received his undergraduate degree in mathematics from Harvard College in 1939 and spent the following two decades in the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. Hébert is a 17th-century French folk tale by François Boulanger that is often cited as one of the most influential tales in European literary history.

The European bison ( Bison bonasus ) or the European wood bison , also known as the wisent ( or Wissen ), is a semi-aquatic, nocturnal, scavenging mammal native to northwestern Europe and northwest Asia. In both subspecies, the female remains stationary during the day, while males may be active at any time. The European bison has a long trunk that extends from the tail end to the back of the neck; however, it is much lighter than the American bison, which has a shorter trunk. Its head is round, having a short, low-crested nose and a broad, oval face.

The Battle of Trafalgar (21 October 1805) was a naval engagement between the British Royal Navy and the combined fleets of the French and Spanish Navies during the War of the Third Coalition (August–December 1805) of the Napoleonic Wars (1803–1815).As part of Napoleon's plans to invade England, the French and Spanish fleets combined to take control of the English Channel and provide the Grande Armée safe passage. The allied fleet, under the command of French Admiral Villeneuve, sailed from the port of Cádiz in the south of Spain on 18 October 1805.

The earliest arrival of people in the islands now known as The Bahamas was in the first millennium AD. The first inhabitants of the islands were the Lucayans, an Arawakan-speaking Taino people, who arrived between about 500 and 800 AD from other islands of the Caribbean.Recorded history began on 12 October 1492, when Christopher Columbus landed on the island of Guanahani, which he renamed San Salvador Island, on his first voyage to the New World. The earliest permanent European settlement was in 1648 on Eleuthera. During the 18th century slave trade, many Africans were brought to the Bahamas as slaves to work unpaid.

An engagement ring is a ring indicating that the person wearing it is engaged to be married, especially in Western cultures. A ring is presented as an engagement gift by a partner to their prospective spouse when they propose marriage or directly after a marriage proposal is accepted. It represents a formal agreement to future marriage. In Western countries, engagement rings are worn mostly by women, and rings can feature diamonds or other gemstones. The neologism "mangagement ring" is sometimes used for an engagement ring worn by men. In some cultures, men and women wear matching rings, and engagement rings may also be used as wedding rings.

The 12th century BC is the period from 1200 to 1101 BC. The Late Bronze Age collapse in the ancient Near East and eastern Mediterranean is often considered to begin in this century.Events 1200 BC: The first civilization in Central and North America develops in about 1200 BC in the coastal regions of the southern part of the Gulf of Mexico. Known as the Olmec civilization, its early site is at San Lorenzo. 1200 BC: The Phoenicians found the port of Lisbon, Portugal 1197 BC: The beginning of the first period (1197 BC – 982 BC) by Shao Yong's concept of the I Ching and history.

Year 1375 ( MCCCLXXV ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Roman Empire during the reign of Theodosius. In the year 1377, the year of Theodosius I and the fall of Rome to the forces of Henry V, the House of Bonaparte seized the imperial throne and proclaimed itself emperor, but in the following years it would lose that office to Henry VI. A man is either an American, a citizen of the United States or a resident alien who holds U.S. citizenship.

Mai Elisabeth Zetterling ( ; 24 May 1925 – 17 March 1994 ) was a Swedish actress , novelist and film director, best remembered for her roles as Maria Lagerström in Hausmälle and Margot Redding in Gattaca. A member of the German Nazi Party since 1933, Zetterling went to work with Adolf Hitler's propaganda department in 1937 when he came to power following his defeat by Marshal Franz von Papen at the Second World War. She remained under his control for two years before moving to Berlin and becoming an aide to the then-Chancellor Otto von Bismarck.

Mercia (, ; ) was one of the kingdoms of the Anglo-Saxon Heptarchy. The name is a Latinisation of the Old English  or  (West Saxon dialect;  in the Mercian dialect itself), meaning "border people" (see March). Mercia dominated what would later become England for three centuries, subsequently going into a gradual decline while Wessex eventually conquered and united all the kingdoms into the Kingdom of England.The kingdom was centred on the valley of the River Trent and its tributaries, in the region now known as the English Midlands. The court moved around the kingdom, and there was no fixed capital city.

A semi-automatic rifle is an autoloading rifle that fires one round each pull of the trigger . For comparison , a semi-automatic rifle can fire 1 to 2 shots per cycle. Armenia ( տշաում ) is an area of Eastern Europe, situated between the Black Sea and Caspian Sea. It has a population of 3.6 million, making it one of the smallest states in Central Europe. In 2015, it achieved a status of "small island state", with a population of about 800,000. The capital Yerevan lies on the south-western edge of Armenia.

Year 1292 (MCCXCII) was a leap year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  April 5 – The Papal election, 1292–94 begins. November – Michael II becomes Syriac Orthodox Patriarch of Antioch. November 17 (Julian calendar) – John Balliol is selected by King Edward I of England as King of Scotland, from among 13 competitors for the Crown of Scotland; Edward then treats John as a puppet ruler and Scotland as a vassal state, eventually provoking the Wars of Scottish Independence, commencing in 1296.

Dissociative identity disorder (DID), previously known as multiple personality disorder (MPD), is a mental disorder characterized by the maintenance of at least two distinct and relatively enduring personality states. The disorder is accompanied by memory gaps beyond what would be explained by ordinary memory issues. The personality states alternately show in a person's behavior; however, presentations of the disorder vary. Other conditions that often occur in people with DID include post-traumatic stress disorder, personality disorders (especially borderline and avoidant), depression, substance use disorders, conversion disorder, somatic symptom disorder, eating disorders, obsessive–compulsive disorder, and sleep disorders.

In cosmology , the cosmological constant ( usually denoted by the Greek capital letter lambda : Λ ) , alternatively, is simply the product of the energy of all the elementary particles. It has three possible values. The most common and important value is unity: it varies from 0 to ∞ at the zero-energy end of spacetime; this value cannot be changed by any gravitational or quantum interference effects. This value remains constant even after perturbing the scalar variables. The Hebrew name קוֶרָה (or ַפְּרֹאֵיתָה) comes from a pre-existent city called Hamakim, in what is now Syria, where King Solomon built a temple dedicated to Jehovah.

Year 1511 ( MDXI ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in France, 17 June 1511 through to 6 January 1514. The date of birth is recorded as 11 November 1512, but it is not known exactly when this event took place or what the date was. It was traditionally commemorated with a celebration in Saint-Denis de la Grasse-du-Loup, but there are many stories that do not take place here. Kunming ( 關 , Kunmei ) is a central city of southern China's Shandong Province.

Year 1552 (MDLII) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–June  January 15 – Henry II of France and Maurice, Elector of Saxony, sign the Treaty of Chambord. February 12 – Pedro de Valdivia founds the Chilean city of Valdivia, as Santa María la Blanca de Valdivia. February 24 – The privileges of the Hanseatic League are abolished in England. March – The Act of Uniformity imposes the Protestant Book of Common Prayer on England. March 26 – Guru Amar Das becomes the Third Sikh Guru.

Year 1390 (MCCCXC) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 19 – The Treaty of Lyck confirms an alliance between Vytautas and the Teutonic Knights, in the Lithuanian Civil War against Vytautas's cousin, Jogaila. April 14 – John VII Palaiologos overthrows his grandfather, John V Palaiologos, as Byzantine Emperor. April 19 – Robert III succeeds his father, Robert II, as King of Scotland. May 26 – Lithuanian Civil War: The Treaty of Königsberg is signed in Königsberg, between Samogitian nobles and representatives of the Teutonic Knights.

Bacillus cereus is a Gram-positive , rod-shaped , facultatively anaerobic , motile , beta-hemolytic , spore-forming bacterium commonly found in warm water habitats. Bacterial spores are used to break down various plant and mineral substances, such as bark, wood, leaves, and other plant materials; they also produce small amounts of toxins that are inhaled by animals, causing them to die or injure their surroundings. The term bacteria is derived from the Latin prefix bacillus for "good", which suggests its importance in the health of the plants it inhabits.

Year 1212 (MCCXII) was a leap year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place   England  July 10 – The Great Fire: The most severe of several early fires of London burns most of the city to the ground; over 3,000 people die, many of them by drowning in the River Thames. According to a contemporary account: "An awful fire broke out on the Southwark side of London Bridge; while it was raging, a fire broke out at the other end also and so hemmed in the numerous crowds who had assembled to help the distressed.

A mace is a blunt weapon , a type of club or virge that uses a heavy head on the end of a staff held horizontally. A mace is generally used for slashing, kicking, striking, wrestling, throwing, and hitting enemies, though other weapons might also be used. In Latin American and South American cultures, the term mace comes from the Latin word masculare, meaning "a man who wears a helmet". This derives from the old name of an ancient city in Tuscany, which is named after a god known for his beard.

In computational complexity theory , PSPACE is the set of all decision problems that can be solved by a Turing machine; it has been studied for over 30 years, and many papers have been published since the first one in 1964. PSPACE is an interesting problem because it allows us to observe how computers learn from experience without explicit instruction, but it is still subject to much criticism. Strict formal logic is a form of algebraic data logic (DAL) derived from logics which treats logical functions as axioms. The term "strict formal logic" was used during its development in the late 19th century.

Year 1150 (MCL) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Battle of Tara: The Byzantines defeat the Serbian-Hungarian army under Grdeša, count (župan) of Travunija, near the snow-covered Tara River. The Serbs are overpowered, and Grand Prince Uroš II is forced to accept the peace agreement made by Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos). Uroš is succeeded by his brother Desa, who  becomes co-ruler of the Principality of Serbia (until 1153).

Year 1206 ( MCCVI ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) and lasting for eight weeks. It took place between 13 September and 14 December. This year's MCCVI was celebrated by Pope John XXIII who presided at the ceremony. Northeast United States of America ( NUS ) is a US state located in the eastern portion of North America west of the Rocky Mountains, between the Canadian border and the states of Montana and Washington. It borders Canada and Mexico on the east and west.

Year 1472 ( MCDLXXII ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in 1762. On 11 May 2014, an earthquake caused damage to the capital city of Baku, as well as the surrounding areas. The quake was followed by explosions across Azerbaijan. A second earthquake on 10 October triggered a tsunami that hit coastal regions, killing at least 19 people. However, many residents who were displaced by the tsunami escaped uninjured. On 6 April 2015, an 8.3 magnitude earthquake destroyed the country's eastern border with Armenia, killing at least 18 people and injuring several more.

A shank is a type of knot that is used to shorten a rope or take up slack , such as when attaching a cable to a vessel or other item, or connecting a carabiner to a harness. Shanks may also be used to attach a metal handle to the end of a rope to help secure it. One of the most common techniques for making a shank is to place a small amount of glue on the end of each end of the rope and then cut it in half with a pair of pliers. An American Eskimo (   ) is a person of Middle East origin who live in the Northern Hemisphere .

Year 1302 ( MCCCII ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) from 13 September 2013 to 7 April 2014. The year started with the English equivalent of Christmas Day and ran until 23 December, ending on 1 January 2015.The year began in England when Henry VIII married his half-sister Mary Queen of Scots on 30 July 1215 and they had two children: the son Edward VI and the daughter Catherine. History [ edit ]
This history takes place during the reign of King Edward I of England .

Robert I Estienne (; 15037 September 1559), known as Robertus Stephanus in Latin and sometimes referred to as Robert Stephens, was a 16th-century printer and classical scholar in Paris. He was the proprietor of the Estienne print shop after the death of his father Henri Estienne, the founder of the Estienne printing firm. Estienne published and republished many classical texts as well as Greek and Latin translations of the Bible. Known as "Printer to the King" in Latin, Hebrew, and Greek, Estienne's most prominent work was the Thesaurus linguae latinae which is considered to be the foundation of modern Latin lexicography.

Botulism is a rare and potentially fatal illness caused by a toxin produced by the bacterium Clostridium botulinum. The disease begins with weakness, blurred vision, feeling tired, and trouble speaking. This may then be followed by weakness of the arms, chest muscles, and legs. Vomiting, swelling of the abdomen, and diarrhea may also occur. The disease does not usually affect consciousness or cause a fever.Botulism can be spread in several ways. The bacterial spores which cause it are common in both soil and water. They produce the botulinum toxin when exposed to low oxygen levels and certain temperatures.

A killer is someone or something that kills , such as a murderer or a serial killer . Killer or killer is sometimes used in reference to someone who has killed many people. The noun "killer" means "unnatural person" or "inhuman act of aggression". The word comes from ancient Greek, which meant a person who was untrustworthy, and the verb "kill" means "to harm".The term is usually associated with criminals who kill, but can be used for people who do nothing but murder.In popular culture, "killer" often implies a malevolent or evil spirit.

Frederick II of Brandenburg  (19 November 1413 – 10 February 1471), nicknamed "the Iron" (der Eiserne) and sometimes "Irontooth" (Eisenzahn), was a Prince-elector of the Margraviate of Brandenburg from 1440 until his abdication in 1470, and was a member of the House of Hohenzollern.BiographyFrederick II was born at Tangermünde Castle (German: Burg Tangermünde), when Tangermünde was within the Margraviate of Brandenburg, to Frederick I, Brandenburg's first Hohenzollern ruler, and his wife Elizabeth, daughter of Frederick, Duke of Bavaria-Landshut, and Maddalena Visconti.

Jacques René Chirac (, , ; 29 November 193226 September 2019) was a French politician who served as President of France from 1995 to 2007. Chirac was previously Prime Minister of France from 1974 to 1976 and from 1986 to 1988, as well as Mayor of Paris from 1977 to 1995.After attending the École nationale d'administration, Chirac began his career as a high-level civil servant, entering politics shortly thereafter. Chirac occupied various senior positions, including Minister of Agriculture and Minister of the Interior. In 1981 and 1988, he unsuccessfully ran for President as the standard-bearer for the conservative Gaullist party Rally for the Republic.

A lever ( or ) is a simple machine consisting of a beam or rigid rod pivoted at a fixed position, supported by a supporting bar, attached to which a spring engages. It is typically designed to be used as a guide and control device to move the beam or rod across a surface. Other common use of a lever is to attach it to movable armatures, tools, or equipment such as forklift handles.An example of an "instantaneous lever" would be a piece of heavy equipment such as a wheelbarrow whose inertia does not allow it to stop automatically in mid-motion.

Spins are an element in figure skating in which the skater rotates, centered on a single point on the ice, while holding one or more body positions. They are performed by all disciplines of the sport, single skating, pair skating, and ice dance, and are a required element in most figure skating competitions. As The New York Times says, "While jumps look like sport, spins look more like art. While jumps provide the suspense, spins provide the scenery, but there is so much more to the scenery than most viewers have time or means to grasp".

Year 1206 (MCCVI) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  January 31 – Battle of Rusion: The Bulgarian forces (some 7,000 men) under Tsar Kaloyan defeat the remnants of the Latin army near the fortress of Rusion in Thrace. Around 120 knights supported by soldiers and cavalry are killed in battle or captured. In February, the Bulgarians attack and loot the fortified town of Rodosto (see Battle of Rodosto), defended by a Venetian garrison. Later, Kaloyan captures many more towns and fortresses.

Events January–June March – The Synod of Jerusalem brings together bishops and representatives from the whole of Eastern Orthodox Christendom with a view to formulating an ecclesial, pastoral and political programme for the future of the Church in its various historical and spiritual environments. January 28–30, 1985

December 5–15, 1988

April 25–May 26, 1993

September 27–November 29, 1995

April 2–14, 1996

March 8–11, 1997

February 24–July 30, 1998

December 17–26, 1999

June 9–10, 2000

The synod held its final session on April 21-22, 2004 at the monastery of Sibylus in Nicopolis, Georgia.

Vapor pressure ( or vapour pressure in English-speaking counties other than the US ; see spelling differences ) or equilibrium temperature, as a measure of how much gas and moisture vapor can escape from a liquid containing air. The term is used to refer to an equilibrium temperature where the amount of heat dissolving water vapor is exactly equal to the quantity of heat dissolving air, or vice versa. In practical terms, it describes the equilibrium between two quantities that are either constant or fluctuates at any given point. It should not be confused with ambient temperature, for which equilibrium is also referred to.

A horoscope ( or other commonly used names for the horoscope in English include natal chart , astrological chart , etc.) is a system of religious symbols and rituals to guide an individual towards certain beliefs, actions and/or experiences. A horoscope can also be associated with any number of traditions, including alchemy, witchcraft, divination, fortune-telling, astrology, magic, prophecy, and others.Horus has been a major figure in Jewish mythology throughout history, and there are seven books written by him in the first century BC. He is sometimes described as Moses' messiah.

Dyson's eternal intelligence concept (the Dyson Scenario), proposed by Freeman Dyson in 1979, proposes a means by which an immortal society of intelligent beings in an open universe may escape the prospect of the heat death of the universe by extending subjective time to infinity even though expending only a finite amount of energy.Bremermann's limit can be invoked to deduce that the amount of time to perform a computation on 1 bit is inversely proportional to the change in energy in the system. As a result, the amount of computations that can be performed grows over time.

The French and Indian War ( 1754–1763 ) was a theater of the Seven Years ' War , which pitted Britain against Spain, France and Russia. This is the first war to be fought with a direct military engagement on British soil, although it is commonly referred to as the War of Spanish Succession . The war was also the first battle of Waterloo between the two powers, which was won by William Penn in a series of victories on June 10, 1815. Hausa is the language spoken primarily by the Hausa people of southern Africa.

Cooking bananas are banana cultivars in the genus Musa whose fruits are generally used in cooking . They may be dried, or they can be collected fresh from trees that have produced fruit for several decades.The word "musa" derives from the English word "muses", which is a diminutive of mus (meaning "apple"), and comes from the verb mussum , to chop. New Zealand is home to over 100 species of endemic plants. There are around 200 endemic species of shrubs and tree species throughout the country.

Year 993 ( CMXCIII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Christian calendar. Its start date, November 5th, 1797, marks the beginning of Christendom's transition to Christianity and the introduction of the Christian calendar. According to traditional beliefs, the first century A.D. had its origin during the reign of Antiochus III in the Roman Empire, when his son Emperor Claudius II ordered the establishment of the world's first calendar—known as θεοβία (θεύλωπος), which would be followed by an emperor whose name is unknown.

The Khlysts or Khlysty (,  "whips") were an underground Spiritual Christian sect, which split from the Russian Orthodox Church and existed from the 1600s until the late 20th century.NameThe members of the sect referred to themselves by various names, including "God's People" (liudi bozh'i), "followers of Christ's faith" (Khristovovery), or simply "Christs" (Khristy). The appellation "Khlysty" is a derogatory term applied by critics of the sect. The origin of the term is disputed.

The governor of Montana is the head of government of Montana and the commander-in-chief of the state 's military forces.Governor Steve Bullock took office on January 1, 2006, replacing former Governor Greg Gianforte, who had been elected to his second term in 2010.Bullock became the 42nd governor of Montana in March 2011. His term ends at the end of the 2017 fiscal year. In addition to being one of the largest cities in the United States, San Francisco is a major international financial center. In 2013, Forbes magazine ranked it among the 25 most valuable cities for investors, with a total market value of US$21.9 trillion.

Year 1491 ( MCDXCI ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of King Henry the First, who is generally known as Tudor England's first Tudor king. He succeeded to the English crown in 1535, after having been assassinated by Charles I at Hampton Court in 1603. This article was originally published in June 2014. On January 1st, 1833, Thomas Jefferson announced his intention to run for president in what he called "The Great American Awakening." Since then, nearly 200 candidates have been put forth for the Republican nomination, most recently Donald Trump.

Year 1539 (MDXXXIX) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January – Toungoo–Hanthawaddy War – Battle of Naungyo, Burma: The Toungoos decisively defeat the Hanthawaddys. January 12 – Treaty of Toledo: Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor (and Charles I of Spain) and Francis I of France agree to make no further alliances with England. The treaty comes after Henry VIII of England's split with Rome and Pope Paul III. January 14 – Spain annexes Cuba.

Frederick (Middle High German: Friderich, Standard German: Friedrich; 21 September 1371 – 20 September 1440) was the last Burgrave of Nuremberg from 1397 to 1427 (as Frederick VI), Margrave of Brandenburg-Ansbach from 1398, Margrave of Brandenburg-Kulmbach from 1420, and Elector of Brandenburg (as Frederick I) from 1415 until his death. He became the first member of the House of Hohenzollern to rule the Margraviate of Brandenburg.Biography Frederick was born in Nuremberg, the second-born son of Burgrave Frederick V (1333–1398) and the Wettin princess Elisabeth of Meissen.

Year 1384 ( MCCCLXXXIV ) was a leap year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) with its 12 th and 14 th day being dedicated to Henry VIII. It is the second most common of the four Gregorian calendars. The Julian calendar was originally proposed in 1564, although the exact dates have not been officially confirmed for over 130 years. The French Revolution was a national uprising that took place in 1789 during the reign of Joseph-Jacques Philippe. It was led by Georges-Auguste Fournier, heir to the French throne, who overthrew the monarchy after a military coup against his brother Louis XVI.

Perpignan (, , ;  ;  ;  ) is the prefecture of the Pyrénées-Orientales department (known as Northern Catalonia) in southern France, in the heart of the plain of Roussillon, at the foot of the Pyrenees a few kilometres from the Mediterranean Sea and the scrublands of the Corbières massif. It is the centre of the Perpignan Mediterranée Métropole metropolitan area.In 2016 Perpignan had a population of 121,875 (Perpignanais(e) in French, Perpinyanés(a) in Catalan) in the commune proper, and the metropolitan area had a total population of 268,577, making it the last major French city before the Spanish border.

Frederick ( Middle High German : Friderich , Standard German : Friedrich ; 21 September 1371 – 20 September 1440) was an American statesman and one of the most influential politicians in the history of the United States. Lebanon is a sovereign, self-governing, democratic republic in the western part of the Middle Eastern Desert, bordering Saudi Arabia and the Jewish state of Israel on the West Coast. Lebanon borders Syria, Egypt, Jordan, Israel, Palestine, Turkey, Iran, Iraq, Kuwait, Qatar, Oman, and other countries in the Middle East and North Africa.

The French and Indian War (1754–1763) was a theater of the Seven Years' War, which pitted the North American colonies of the British Empire against those of the French, each side being supported by various Native American tribes. At the start of the war, the French colonies had a population of roughly 60,000 settlers, compared with 2 million in the British colonies. The outnumbered French particularly depended on the natives.Two years into the French and Indian War, in 1756, Great Britain declared war on France, beginning the worldwide Seven Years' War.

Ice hockey at the 2002 Winter Olympics was held at the E Center in West Valley City and Peaks Ice Arena in Snowmass, Minnesota. It attracted over 3,000 participants from all over North America and more than 60 countries around the world. Since then, four more competitions have been held at the National Hockey League facility: the 2006 World Junior Championship, the 2015 World Championships in Sweden, the 2012 World Championships in Canada and the 2014 World Juniors in Russia. The final is held in December each of the following years.The event's name derives from a game called ice hockey that originated in Europe during the late 1500s.

Year 1533 (MDXXXIII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 25 – King Henry VIII of England formally but secretly marries Anne Boleyn, who becomes his second queen consort. January 26 – Thomas Audley, 1st Baron Audley of Walden, is appointed Lord Chancellor of England. March 30 – Thomas Cranmer becomes Archbishop of Canterbury. April – The Statute in Restraint of Appeals in England declares the king to be the supreme sovereign and forbids judicial appeals to the papacy.

Events  January–March  January 8 – Carolean Death March begins: A catastrophic retreat by a largely-Finnish Swedish-Carolean army under the command of Carl Gustaf Armfeldt across the Tydal mountains in a blizzard kills around 3,700 men and cripples a further 600 for life. January 23 – The Principality of Liechtenstein is created, within the Holy Roman Empire. February 3 (January 23 Old Style) – The Riksdag of the Estates recognizes Ulrika Eleonora's claim to the Swedish throne, after she has agreed to sign a new Swedish constitution. Thus, she is recognized as queen regnant of Sweden.

Year 1556 (MDLVI) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 16 – Charles V, having already abdicated as Holy Roman Emperor, resigns the Kingdom of Spain in favour of his son, Philip II, and retires to a monastery. January 23 –  The Shaanxi earthquake, the deadliest earthquake in history, occurs with its epicenter in Shaanxi province, China; 830,000 people may have been killed. February 5 – Truce of Vaucelles: Fighting temporarily ends between France and Spain.

In physics , quintessence is a hypothetical form of dark energy , more precisely a scalar field , postulated as an infinite quantity due to Einstein's special theory of relativity . In quantum theory, it is defined by a mathematical equation.The most commonly used version is described in classical terms as a field that acts on the particles at a distance. It is similar to electromagnetic waves, with some differences.According to classical geometry, when two objects appear to touch each other, the gravitational force between them will be proportional to the square root of their mass.

Casimir IV (in full Casimir IV Andrew Jagiellon;  ; Lithuanian: ; 30 November 1427 – 7 June 1492) was Grand Duke of Lithuania from 1440 and King of Poland from 1447, until his death. He was one of the most active Polish-Lithuanian rulers, under whom Poland, by defeating the Teutonic Knights in the Thirteen Years' War recovered Pomerania, and the Jagiellonian dynasty became one of the leading royal houses in Europe.The great triumph of his reign was bringing Prussia under Polish rule. The rule of Casimir corresponded to the age of "new monarchies" in western Europe.

Year 1384 (MCCCLXXXIV) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  May – September 3 – Siege of Lisbon by the Castilian army, during the 1383–85 Crisis in Portugal. August 16 – The Hongwu Emperor of Ming China hears a case of a couple who tore paper money notes, while fighting over them. Under the law, this is considered to be destroying stamped government documents, which is to be punished by a caning with a bamboo rod of 100 strokes. However, the Emperor decides to pardon them, on the grounds that it was unintentional.

Year 1213 (MCCXIII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  May 15 – King John of England submits to Pope Innocent III, who in turn lifts the interdict of 1208. May 30 – Battle of Damme: The English fleet under William Longespée, 3rd Earl of Salisbury, destroys a French fleet off the Belgian port in the first major victory for the fledgling Royal Navy. September 12 – Battle of Muret: The Toulousain and Aragonese forces of Raymond VI of Toulouse and Peter II of Aragon are defeated by the Albigensian Crusade, under Simon de Montfort.

Year 1396 (MCCCXCVI) was a leap year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  May 19 – Martin I succeeds his brother, John I, as King of Aragon (modern-day north-east Spain). July 20 – Queen Margaret I of Denmark, Norway and Sweden publishes the Treaty of Kalmar, proposing the personal union of the three kingdoms of Denmark, Norway (with Iceland, Greenland, the Faroe Islands, Shetland and Orkney) and Sweden (including Finland and Åland). July 23 – Queen Margaret makes her great-nephew and adopted son Eric of Pomerania joint ruler of Sweden.

Year 1377 (MCCCLXXVII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January – Battle of Đồ Bàn: Trần Duệ Tông, Trần dynasty Emperor of Đại Việt (Vietnam), is killed. January 17 – Pope Gregory XI moves the Papacy back from Avignon to Rome. January 27 – The Bad Parliament begins sitting in England. Influenced by John of Gaunt, 1st Duke of Lancaster, it undoes the work done by the Good Parliament, the previous year, to reduce corruption in the Royal Council.

EventsJanuary–March  January 20 – The Parliament of England (under Tory dominance) limits the size of the country's standing army to 7,000 'native born' men; hence, King William III's Dutch Blue Guards cannot serve in the line. By an Act of February 1, it also requires disbandment of foreign troops in Ireland. January 26 – The Republic of Venice, Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth and Holy Roman Empire sign the Treaty of Karlowitz with the Ottoman Empire, marking an end to the major phase of the Ottoman–Habsburg wars, including the Morean War between Venice and the Ottomans.

Events <onlyinclude>January–March  January 1 – The Abenaki tribe and the Massachusetts colonists sign a treaty, ending the conflict in New England. January 4 – The Palace of Whitehall in London, England is destroyed by fire. January 23 – George Louis (who in 1714 will become King George I of Great Britain) becomes Elector of Hanover upon the death of his father, Ernest Augustus. Because the widow of Ernest Augustus, George's mother Sophia, was heiress presumptive as the cousin of Anne, Queen of Great Britain, and Anne's closest eligible heir, George will become King of Great Britain.

Aloysius Lilius ( c. 1510 – 1576 ) , also variously referred to as Luigi Lilio , Luigi Giglio , or by the nickname "Luigi" . He was an Italian composer born into a wealthy household, and his father was a lawyer and member of the Order of Pietras in Florence. His family was well educated, and one of his uncle's two sons became famous for composing operas known as La Dolce Vita ("Dolce Vita" means "Peace").Leliège is situated along the Danube river between Rome and its southern suburbs.

Year 1486 ( MCDLXXXVI ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full Julian calendar at https://www.saintpilgrim.org/index.htm ) and ending on the last Sunday after Pentecost ( link will display the full Julian calendar at https://www.saintpilgrim.org/publications/Julian-calendar/. Atomic Energy Council  is a global nonprofit research and educational organization devoted to reducing the costs of nuclear energy, building safe and environmentally sound reactors, improving the design of nuclear power plants, developing new nuclear technologies, and supporting the scientific and technological progress of nuclear energy. Founded in 1986, the group is headquartered in Washington, DC.

Year 1578 (MDLXXVIII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 31 – Battle of Gembloux: Spanish forces under Don John of Austria and Alexander Farnese defeat the Dutch; Farnese begins to recover control of the French-speaking Southern Netherlands. April 27 – The Duel of the Mignons claims the lives of two favorites of Henry III of France, and two favourites of Henry I, Duke of Guise. May 26 – The Alteratie in Amsterdam ends Catholic rule, and open Catholic worship there.

Frederick James Prinze ( born Frederick Karl Pruetzel ; June 22 , 1954 – January 29 , 1977 ) was an American musician, composer, and vocalist. He is also known as the founder of experimental pop music.As a singer, he wrote numerous hits in the 1970s and early 1980s, often performed with other rock bands including the Who, Black Sabbath, and Pearl Jam. His earliest recordings were produced by his wife, Minka; they have not been released.Early lifePruetzel was born on June 22, 1954 in Brooklyn, New York, the youngest of five siblings.

Year 1541 ( MDXLI ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending at 11:59:59 UTC. The date of the day in MDXLI was set by Edward VI as May 3, but it is believed that some early medieval writers may have set the date for the end of the summer solstice according to their own custom. It can be viewed as an "exception" to the normal spring/summer solstice when it does not start until July 5 and ends before August 30. The Duchy of Aquitaine is one of the constituent territories of France.

The Cathedral of St. John the Divine ( sometimes referred to as St. John 's and also nicknamed St. John the Evangelical), is a Roman Catholic cathedral situated in the heart of Milan. It is the third-most visited Roman Catholic cathedral in Europe and was founded in 1762.Its exterior features consist mostly of red and white columns and domes adorned with mosaics and frescoes. Its interior has been described by some as resembling a "gothic cathedral", while others call it the Gothic City of Rome. The church itself consists of three main parts—a sanctuary, an upper gallery and the choir loft.St.

Pearl Harbour is a small harbour at the head of the Waiau River, in the town of Manapouri on the South Island of New Zealand.The harbour and town are located at the south-east corner of Lake Manapouri. The name was given to the harbour soon after the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor, Hawaii in 1941.Pearl Harbour is used mainly by ferry and water taxi operators transporting Meridian Energy staff  across Lake Manapouri to the Manapouri Hydroelectric Power Station, on the West Arm of the lake. Ferries also carry tourists travelling to the power station and onwards to Doubtful Sound, located on the coast 10 km beyond the West Arm.

Mariner 10 was an American robotic space probe launched by NASA on 3 November 1973, to fly by the planets Mercury and Venus. It was the first spacecraft to perform flybys of multiple planets.Mariner 10 was launched approximately two years after Mariner 9 and was the last spacecraft in the Mariner program. (Mariner 11 and Mariner 12 were allocated to the Voyager program and redesignated Voyager 1 and Voyager 2. )The mission objectives were to measure Mercury's environment, atmosphere, surface, and body characteristics and to make similar investigations of Venus.

Year 1321 (MCCCXXI) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December c. May–June – Leper scare: Rumours that lepers (acting on the orders of Jews bribed by Moors) are attempting to poison the Christian population spread throughout southern France. August 14 – King Edward II of England reluctantly agrees to demands from his barons to send Hugh le Despenser, 1st Earl of Winchester, and his son Hugh Despenser the Younger into exile. October 29 – King Stephen Uroš II Milutin of Serbia dies.

The Polish People 's Party ( , PSL ) is an agrarian political party in Poland . It is currently led by Law and Justice leader Jarosław Kaczyński, who was appointed as president of the ruling Civic Platform for a term that will end on 16 November 2018. The party won the 2015 general election by more than 17%, the second-highest result of any party in Poland.Political parties are legally regulated through a parliamentary committee with five members to consider all proposals for legislative change. The Central Elections Commission administers elections and publishes results. Hindus and Muslims live in peace and mutual trust with each other.

Banksia is a genus of around 170 species in the plant family Proteaceae . These Australian wildflowers and popular garden plants are usually grown for their oil, but have become widely used for many uses such as ornamental or ornamental food production. They have been cultivated since the late 19th century, although botanists still doubt that they were ever domesticated. A berry is an edible fruit that grows mostly in its natural form. The most commonly known fruits are cherries, apricots, plums, figs, nectarines, pomelos, peaches, prunes, strawberries, and zucchinis.

Bobsleigh or bobsled is a team winter sport that involves making timed runs down narrow, twisting, banked, iced tracks in a gravity-powered sleigh. International bobsleigh competitions are governed by the International Bobsleigh and Skeleton Federation, also known as FIBT from the French . National competitions are often governed by bodies such as the United States Bobsled and Skeleton Federation, Bobsleigh Canada Skeleton, and the German Bobsleigh, Luge, and Skeleton Federation.The first bobsleds were built in the late 19th century in St. Moritz, Switzerland, by wealthy tourists from Victorian Britain who were staying at the Palace Hotel owned by Caspar Badrutt.

Nvidia Corporation  is an American multinational technology company incorporated in Delaware and based in Santa Clara, California. It is a fabless company which designs graphics processing units (GPUs) for the gaming and professional markets, as well as system on a chip units (SoCs) for the mobile computing and automotive market. Its primary GPU line, labeled "GeForce", is in direct competition with the GPUs of the "Radeon" brand by Advanced Micro Devices (AMD). Nvidia expanded its presence in the gaming industry with its handheld game consoles Shield Portable, Shield Tablet, and Shield Android TV and its cloud gaming service GeForce Now.

Eric Arthur Heiden ( born June 14 , 1958 ) is an American physician and a former long track speedskater from Chicago, Illinois. He held the Guinness World Record for fastest skater-to-rider distance on July 27, 2005. Born in New York City, Heiden began training at age ten as a street racer before joining the US Army Air Force. Hoboken, New Jersey was the fifth-largest U.S. city in 2007, after San Francisco, Los Angeles, Chicago, and Philadelphia. In addition to the borough of Hoboken, the city has two airports, one of which serves as both its primary and terminal airport.

Year 1443 (MCDXLIII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events <onlyinclude>January–December  July 22 – Battle of St. Jakob an der Sihl (Old Zürich War): The forces of the city of Zürich are defeated, but the Swiss Confederacy have insufficient strength to besiege and take the city. November 8 – Battle of Niš: John Hunyadi and the army of the Crusade of Varna defeat three armies of the Ottoman Empire, and capture the city of Niš in modern-day Serbia; Skanderbeg deserts the Ottoman camp and goes to Albania.

Year 1329 ( MCCCXXIX ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the reign of King Charles I , who ruled from 1324 until his death. The year is also sometimes known as the Feast of Exaltation, which takes place on December 7 each year, but is often referred to simply as "Exaltation" for simplicity's sake. On July 15, 1757, England's Queen Victoria and Prince Albert arrived in Perth, Australia to celebrate the anniversary of the English victory over France in the Battle of St Lawrence.

Year 1027 ( MXXVII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) and lasting for one day, or until sunrise. It began with the Sun setting in Leo, then became Sagittarius, Capricorn in Virgo and Taurus, and Uranus in Cancer. As of 2017 there are 3 known versions of Caliph Abu Bakr  ( بالبين بثفر ), commonly known as Abu Bakr al-Siddiq . The oldest known manuscript of his is found in Cairo, Egypt , dating to between 1177–1193 BC, but other extant texts exist that suggest that it may predate this period.

Arthur Andersen LLP was an American holding company based in Chicago . Formerly one of the `` Big Five '' banks, it became a major financial center in the United States when its founder John J. Bogle took the helm on September 1, 1996.Bogle was born August 15, 1926, in Lake Forest, Illinois. His father, who worked for President Woodrow Wilson, was a member of the National Guard serving in France at the time of WWII.At age 10, his family moved to Rock Island, Illinois, making him the youngest of seven children with a single-mother.

A lever ( or ) is a simple machine consisting of a beam or rigid rod pivoted at a fixed hinge, or fulcrum. A lever is a rigid body capable of rotating on a point on itself. On the basis of the locations of fulcrum, load and effort, the lever is divided into three types. Also, leverage is mechanical advantage gained in a system. It is one of the six simple machines identified by Renaissance scientists. A lever amplifies an input force to provide a greater output force, which is said to provide leverage.

Year 1344 ( MCCCXLIV ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) to celebrate Pope Clement VI's victory of the Thirty-fourth Synod in 1539. At the time, the Catholic Church regarded it as one of the greatest achievements in the annals of Holy Roman Emperor Ferdinand III and he was proclaimed the first Pope of the Catholic Church. History [ edit ]
Historical Background [ edit ]
After the death of Philip II of Macedon in 1095 AD, the Greek kingdom of Greece fell into decline due to frequent invasions from the North African tribes.

Bamboos are a diverse group of evergreen perennial flowering plants in the subfamily Bambusoideae of the grass family Poaceae . Their native range consists of southeastern Europe and western Africa, as well as eastern South America. The species includes many varieties, all of which originate from either North American Indian or African sources.The broadleaf bush of the genus is divided into 7 genera by physical appearance. The common name (or genus) "bush" is given to them by botanists since it has been used over several centuries to indicate their general shape and uniformity.

Year 1027 (MXXVII) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  March 26 – Pope John XIX crowns Conrad II ("the Elder") and his wife Gisela of Swabia as Holy Roman Emperor and Empress, respectively, in Old St. Peter's Basilica in Rome. Cnut the Great, King of Denmark and England, attends the coronation, proving his position as sole ruler of the Danish North Sea Empire. May 14 – King Robert II of France ("the Pious") sues for peace with his sons.

Year 1470 (MCDLXX) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 12 – Wars of the Roses in England – Battle of Losecoat Field: The House of York defeats the House of Lancaster. March 20 (Julian calendar) – The Battle of Nibley Green is the last fought between the private armies of feudal magnates in England. Spring: Anglo-Hanseatic War: Hanseatic League privateers set sail. May 15 – Charles VIII of Sweden, who has served three terms as King of Sweden, dies.

Year 1452 ( MCDLII ) was a leap year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on September 19th. It was widely celebrated around the world, and in Europe, Japan and the United States, but particularly popular in Scotland.The date was adopted by Scottish government as a day of national celebration on 12 June 1554. Happenstance is one of the most significant events in the history of the Christian faith. According to Romans 2:3-9, God made all things by His power, that every man might become a fit instrument in Jesus' salvation for his fellowmen.

The history of Anguilla runs from the beginning of human habitation , probably via settlement from South America , through the Late Pleistocene (about 11,000 – 9,500 B.C. ), to the Early Holocene, which began about 1.6 million years ago.From the earliest humans discovered by archaeologists in the 17th century, it was believed that Anguillas had been populated by hunter-gatherers before Europeans arrived. At that time, they were considered as primitive and a separate species from the ancestors of modern people. Fluid flow is the natural tendency of fluids to condense into solid droplets with a particular density when they come into contact with each other or are separated.

Tropical Storm Karen was a system that brought record-breaking rainfall and flooding to southeastern Pennsylvania and other Mid-Atlantic states in the summer months of August 2013. It had its strongest winds ever recorded, reaching over 170 miles per hour (360km/h) in southwestern Pennsylvania, and then moved northeastward into the mid-Atlantic region with maximum wind speeds near 130 mph (200 km/h). On February 12, 1878, the American political philosopher John Dewey published his first book, Philosophical Essays on Philosophy. A year later, William James's On the Natural History of Morals appeared, which contained several essays he had written that were critical of Hegel.

The Asian Games, also known as Asiad, is a continental multi-sport event held every four years among athletes from all over Asia. The Games were regulated by the Asian Games Federation (AGF) from the first Games in New Delhi, India, until the 1978 Games. Since the 1982 Games, they have been organized by the Olympic Council of Asia (OCA), after the breakup of the Asian Games Federation. The Games are recognized by the International Olympic Committee (IOC) and are described as the second largest multi-sport event after the Olympic Games.There have been nine nations that have hosted the Asian Games.

Year 1182 (MCLXXXII) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  April – Massacre of the Latins: The Roman Catholic (called "Latin") inhabitants of Constantinople massacre the Venetian, Genoan, and other Latin officials and traders who rule as agents of Empress Maria of Antioch. She is the mother and regent of 12-year-old Emperor Alexios II. In August, Andronikos Komnenos, a cousin of Maria's late husband, Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos), raises an army and enters the city, representing himself as the 'protector' of Alexios.

Year 1501 ( MDI ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) from the 11th day before the first Sunday in May until the 31st day of April. In England and Wales, it was not a legal festival or an official one.In Ireland, MDCI falls on the 20th day after Easter, although many celebrate MDCI on the first Sunday in Lent instead. Médecins de l'Académie des Beaux-Arts ( MDE ), also known as the Academia de l'Éducation d'Avant-Garde ( AEGA ), is a French arts organization founded in 1825.

Johan August Arfwedson (12 January 1792 – 28 October 1841) was a  Swedish chemist who discovered the chemical element lithium in 1817 by isolating it as a salt.Life and work Arfwedson belonged to a wealthy bourgeois family, the son of the wholesale merchant and factory owner Jacob Arfwedson and his spouse, Anna Elisabeth Holtermann. The younger Arfwedson matriculated as a student at the University of Uppsala in 1803 (at the time, matriculating at a young age was common for aristocratic and wealthy students), completed a degree in Law in 1809 and a second degree in mineralogy in 1812.

Donnybrook  is a district of Dublin, Ireland. It is situated on the southside of the city, in the Dublin 4 postal district, and is home to the Irish public service broadcaster Raidió Teilifís Éireann (RTÉ). It was once part of the Pembroke Township. Its neighbouring suburbs are Ballsbridge, Sandymount, Ranelagh and Clonskeagh.Donnybrook is also a civil parish mainly situated in the old barony of Dublin.HistoryDonnybrook Fair dates from a charter of King John of England in 1204 and was held annually until 1855. It began as a fair for livestock and agricultural produce but later declined, growing into more of a carnival and funfair.

Tequila is a distilled beverage made from the blue agave plant , primarily in the area surrounding the city of Ocala. It is considered by many to be among the world's most unique spirits because of the distinctive color of the agave, known as taquila, and also because of its unique aroma.There are four different varieties of taquila: Blue agave, orange agave, tequila agave, and tequila cibilla.Blue agave
Inventor - (1862–1965)
Born in San Luis Obispo County, he was an American-born Mexican-American musician who recorded and produced music throughout the United States.

Gravity , or gravitation, is a natural phenomenon by which all things with mass or energy, including planets, stars, galaxies and even light, are attracted to (or gravitate toward) one another. On Earth, gravity gives weight to physical objects, and the Moon's gravity causes the tides of the oceans. The gravitational attraction of the original gaseous matter present in the Universe caused it to begin coalescing and forming stars and caused the stars to group together into galaxies, so gravity is responsible for many of the large-scale structures in the Universe.

Year 1484 ( MCDLXXXIV ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the 13th December. It is often called the "first day of November". The name derives from the fact that it is one of two days on the second day after the solstices but in reality it occurs before the solstices; it is an astronomical expression used to refer to the first half of December.In ancient mythology, the First Epiphany was the last day of Christmas and the Day of Triumph at the Roman festival of Vespers.

Year 1176 ( MCLXXVI ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) to commemorate the first recorded use of the Latin calendar in western Asia, which occurred in the early Middle Ages. The United States Geological Survey ("USGS") is a federal agency established by the U.S. Congress and overseen by the USGS headquarters in St. Louis, Missouri. Its mandate is to ensure that all aspects of the physical, geologic, economic, social, cultural, and environmental aspects of the United States are maintained in a healthy, functional, and sustainable state.

Year 1456 ( MCDLVI ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Friday. It is often referred to as the first spring holiday of the Middle Ages, though other historians have described it in different ways.It was celebrated on April 24, during the Christian feast of Saturnalia.The festival's theme is an allegory for the coming of Christ in the form of the Second Coming, where He returns to save the world by bringing about the establishment of the Roman Empire and the end of the Tribunate at Jerusalem.

Year 1056 (MLVI) was a leap year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  August 31 – Empress Theodora (a sister of the former Empress Zoë) dies after a 18-month reign, by a sudden illness at Constantinople. She is succeeded by Michael VI (the Old), who had served as military finance minister under the former Emperor Romanos III. Michael is appointed through the influence of Leo Paraspondylos, Theodora's most trusted adviser. This ends the Macedonian Dynasty.

EventsJanuary–March  January 1 – Prince Muhammad Akbar, son of the Mughal Emperor Aurangzeb, initiates a civil war in India. With the support of troops from the Rajput states, Akbar declares himself the new Mughal Emperor and prepares to fight his father, but is ultimately defeated. January 3 – The Treaty of Bakhchisarai is signed, between the Ottoman vassal Crimean Khanate and the Russian Empire. January 18 – The "Exclusion Bill Parliament", summoned by King Charles II of England in October, is dissolved after three months, with directions that new elections be held at that a new parliament be convened in March in Oxford.

Year 1361 ( MCCCLXI ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) in England during the reign of King Henry II from June 12th, 1357 to January 22nd, 1360. In medieval times, Saint Patrick became patron saint of Ireland, Britain and northern France, among other places. His name was derived from St. Pio, Bishop of Seville , who established him as archbishop over his native country. The patron saint was also the patron saint of Scotland and the islands of Iona, Lothian, and Derry .

Year 993 (CMXCIII) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Spring – The 12-year-old King Otto III gives the Sword of Saints Cosmas and Damian (also known as the Sword of Essen) as a gift to the convent in Essen. It symbolises the martyrdom of Cosmas and Damian, the patron saints of the city. Charles, duke of Lower Lorraine, dies in prison in Orléans (see 991). He is succeeded by his son Otto II, who inherits the full dukedom and pledges his allegiance to Otto III.

Kazimierz Funk (; February 23, 1884 – November 19, 1967), commonly anglicized as Casimir Funk, was a Polish and American biochemist, generally credited with being among the first to formulate (in 1912) the concept of vitamins, which he called "vital amines" or "vitamines".AchievementsAfter reading an article by the Dutchman Christiaan Eijkman that indicated that persons who ate brown rice were less vulnerable to beri-beri than those who ate only the fully milled product, Funk tried to isolate the substance responsible, and he succeeded. Because that substance contained an amine group, he called it "vitamine".

Phillis Wheatley Peters , also spelled Phyllis and Wheatly ( c. 1753 – December 5 , 1784 ) was an American actress, writer, and dramatist who first gained international fame in Shakespeare's King Lear. She received considerable attention for her roles opposite Henry Fonda in The Nutcracker and Meryl Streep in Citizen Kane.Prior to becoming famous, she had studied dance at University of the Arts in New York City.Her acting career spanned 20 years, beginning as a child actress and continuing over the next three decades as a playwright, choreographer, singer, musician, and poet.

Year 1031 (MXXXI) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  July 20 – King Robert II (the Pious) dies at Melun, after a 35-year reign. He is succeeded by his 23-year-old son, Henry I, who becomes the sole ruler of France. Henry's mother, Queen dowager Constance of Arles, prefers her third son, Robert, as heir to the throne and, with the help of Count Odo II, begins a war against Henry.

Events  January–June  January 11 – The Cortes of Castile approves a new subsidy, the millones. March – Maurice of Nassau, Prince of Orange, takes Breda, by concealing 68 of his best men in a peat-boat, to get through the impregnable defences. March 14 – Battle of Ivry: Henry IV of France again defeats the forces of the Catholic League, under Charles, Duke of Mayenne. May–August – Henry IV of France unsuccessfully attempts to besiege Paris. Henry is forced to raise the siege, when Alexander Farnese, Duke of Parma comes to its rescue with a Spanish army.

Samuel de Champlain (; c. 13 August 1567 – 25 December 1635) was a French colonist, navigator, cartographer, draftsman, soldier, explorer, geographer, ethnologist, diplomat, and chronicler. He made between 21 and 29 trips across the Atlantic Ocean, and founded Quebec, and New France, on 3 July 1608. An important figure in Canadian history, Champlain created the first accurate coastal map during his explorations, and founded various colonial settlements.Born into a family of sailors, Champlain began exploring North America in 1603, under the guidance of his uncle, François Gravé Du Pont.

OCaml ( , formerly Objective Caml) is a general-purpose, multi-paradigm programming language which extends the Caml dialect of ML with object-oriented features. OCaml was created in 1996 by Xavier Leroy, Jérôme Vouillon, Damien Doligez, Didier Rémy, Ascánder Suárez, and others.The OCaml toolchain includes an interactive top-level interpreter, a bytecode compiler, an optimizing native code compiler, a reversible debugger, and a package manager (OPAM). OCaml was initially developed in the context of automated theorem proving, and has an outsize presence in static analysis and formal methods software.

Events  January–March  January 7 – the Republic of Genoa forbids the unauthorized printing of newspapers and all handwriten newssheets. The ban is lifted after three months. January 12 – Scottish minister James Renwick, one of the Covenanters resisting the Scottish government's suppression of alternate religious views, publishes the Declaration of Lanark. January 21 – The Ottoman Empire army is mobilized in preparation for a war against Austria that culminates with the 1683 Battle of Vienna. January 24 – The first public theater in Brussels, the Opéra du Quai au Foin, is opened.

Sigismund of Luxembourg ( 15 February 1368 – 9 December 1437 ) was a monarch who reigned as king of Luxemburg under the Visigoths in Westphalia. He was the son of the Emperor Joachim I and Queen Isabella of Saxony, and the grandson of the Hapsburg Emperor Franz Ferdinand of Russia. He is best remembered for defeating the Burgundians in the battle of Manzanares in 1410. Kamloops, B.C. ( Canada ) is North America's largest independent town with an population of about 4,000 . It is located north of Vancouver on the west shore of Lake Superior.

A conjugate acid , within the Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory , is a chemical compound formed when an acid donates a bivalent metal with one or more cationic electrons. The reaction catalyzes the production of a branched aromatic ring and a pyrrolidine group in the alkyl group at the C–C bond. It is generally considered to be a functional acid; it does not, however, have a positive ionic charge and does not react with other molecules. A branched organic acid may also be described as an aminocoumarins (ACO). Brutella is a gram-negative bacterial pathogen that causes gastroenteritis due to its highly pathogenic growth and virulence.

The Quirinal Hill ( ; ; ) is one of the Seven Hills of Rome , at the north-east of the Apennines mountains. The hill is situated on a ridge along the River Teutoburger, close to the city of Palatinate in Iulia.A large number of churches were established around the hills, and a great many religious shrines surrounded the hill. The area surrounding the hill is called the Quirinal Hill by the Romans as well as the Hill of the House of Caesarea by Christians. Witchcraft ( ; ; ) is a system of magic or witchcraft which involves the use of occult practices and rites to influence the actions of mortals.

Year 1362 ( MCCCLXII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Sunday of the following week, as part of a period of civil government. It commemorated King William IV's accession to England in 1215 and was held every four years until 1549. The Battle of Hastings is one of the most decisive battles of all time. It occurred in October 1066 when Anglo-Saxon forces commanded by Harold Godwinson came under attack by the Huns who had taken possession of the island of Hastings.

Lullingstone Roman Villa is a villa built during the Roman occupation of Britain, situated in Lullingstone near the village of Eynsford in Kent, south eastern England. The villa is located in the Darent Valley, along with six others, including those at Crofton, Crayford and Dartford. Constructed in the 1st century, perhaps around 80-90 CE, the house was repeatedly expanded and occupied until it was destroyed by fire in the 4th or 5th century. The villa was occupied over various periods within the Romano-British period, but after its destruction, it is only thought to have been reoccupied during the Medieval Times.

Year 1212 ( MCCXII ) was a leap year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) that marked the end of winter and spring solstice in December. It was followed by , an elongated leap year which saw the return of summer solstice. It is sometimes known as "the Little Flanders Leap" from the early 16th century, due to the small area it covered. The date was chosen by William III of Aquitaine, English monarch, as a measure of England's economic stability and independence during this time period.

Year 1525 ( MDXXV ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) in England, Ireland and France from January 1525 to January 1530. It has long been known as 'the first summer' or 'the first winter', but no exact date for its beginning has been established.It took place in the English Channel from January 1525 until March 1607, ending with the Battle of Bosworth Bay. In the spring of 1526, the Anglo-Saxon king Henry I defeated King Charles V and restored the throne of England to him.

Year 1216(MCCXVI) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  England  Spring – First Barons' War: The English army, led by King John (Lackland), sacks the town of Berwick-on-Tweed (or Berwick), and raids southern Scotland. John pushes up towards Edinburgh over a ten-day period. On his return, he puts down a revolt in East Anglia. On March 24, King John arrives at Hertford, to deal with the challenge of a coming French invasion.

New England Digital Corporation (1976–1993) was founded in Norwich, Vermont, and relocated to White River Junction, Vermont. It was best known for its signature product, the Synclavier Synthesizer System, which evolved into the Synclavier Digital Audio System or "Tapeless Studio." The company sold an FM digital synthesizer/16-bit polyphonic synthesizer and magnetic disk-based non-linear 16-bit digital recording product, referred to as the "Post-Pro." The Synclavier was developed as the "Dartmouth Digital Synthesizer" by Dartmouth College Professors Jon Appleton and Frederick J. Hooven, in association with NED co-founders Sydney A. Alonso and Cameron W. Jones.

A Tesla coil is an electrical resonant transformer circuit designed by inventor Nikola Tesla in 1891 . It is used to convert alternating current to alternating current with magnetic field induced by the application of magnetic field lines. Taoism ( 河太大, ) is a polytheistic religious system that has been widely studied since its earliest origins in Japan, though it has been practiced in Tibet and China for several thousand years. It consists of five main schools: the Daoists (  ), the Tathagata School of Buddhism , the Pure Land School, the Taoist School and the Hinayana School of Buddhism, while other schools have existed as well.

Year 1193 (MCXCIII) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Levant  March 4 – Saladin (the Lion) dies of a fever at Damascus. The lands of the Ayyubid Dynasty of Syria and Egypt are split among his relatives. During his reign, he briefly unites the Muslim world, and drives the Crusaders out of Jerusalem to a narrow strip of coast. At the time of his death, Saladin has seventeen sons and one little daughter. Al-Afdal succeeds his father as ruler (emir) of Damascus, and inherits the headship of the Ayyubid family.
