March 23 – Emperor Gelawdewos of Ethiopia, defending his lands against the invasion of Nur ibn Mujahid, Sultan of Harar, is killed in battle. His brother, Menas, succeeds him as king.

Mary Virginia Martin (December 1, 1913 – November 3, 1990) was an American actress and singer. A muse of Rodgers and Hammerstein, she originated many leading roles on stage over her career, including Nellie Forbush in South Pacific (1949), the title character in Peter Pan (1954), and Maria von Trapp in The Sound of Music (1959). She was named a Kennedy Center Honoree in 1989. She was the mother of actor Larry Hagman.Early life Martin was born in Weatherford, Texas. Her autobiography described her childhood as secure and happy.

The Cape Cod Canal is an artificial waterway in the U.S. state of Massachusetts connecting Cape Cod Bay in the north to Lowell on the west, and the Massachusetts Bay System in the south. The canal is one of the world's most famous waterways in terms of volume, distance, length, depth, capacity, and navigational convenience, and it has been used by thousands of shipping lines and commercial boats since its opening more than a century ago. John D. Rockefeller II (b. 6 February 1894), also known as "Hank" or "J.D.

Provincetown is a New England town located at the extreme tip of Cape Cod in Barnstable County , Massachusetts , USA. The town was founded in 1760 and served as a military garrison until its occupation by the U.S. Revolutionary War. The Boston Celtics have played in the International Basketball Association since 1995. The team won four championships, including three NBA titles, from 1999-2007. The team has been named to six All-Star Games (2004, 2008, 2010, 2012, 2014) and received four NBA All-Defensive teams in 2011.

Year 994 ( CMXCIV ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Sunday, 22 September. The date was adopted from the Julian calendar by Queen Victoria as the first day of December in 1776. At the time of its introduction, there was considerable controversy within the church about the relationship between Christ and the Jews. This was especially so during the First Council of Lyons in 434–445, when Pope Urban III issued the Bull De Officiis Romanum , which maintained that Christ did not refer to Jesus as his Son but instead called Him "father."

Jochem Simon Uytdehaage ( born 9 July 1976 ) is a Dutch former long track speed skater who won two world championships after his breakout performance in the 2003 Winter Olympics. He is known for his technical skills and competitive spirit which are often compared to that of Jacques Anquetil, while also being considered one of the best on the ice during his time on the National Team. He won the 2006 World Championship at the United States Championships as well as the gold at the 2002 Commonwealth Games in Athens.Uytdehaage first became a professional skating champion when he finished fourth in the 1994 European Skating Championships.

William Makepeace Thackeray (; 18 July 1811 – 24 December 1863) was a British novelist, author and illustrator. He is known for his satirical works, particularly his 1848 novel Vanity Fair, a panoramic portrait of British society, and the 1844 novel The Luck of Barry Lyndon, which was adapted for a 1975 film by Stanley Kubrick.BiographyThackeray, an only child, was born in Calcutta, British India, where his father, Richmond Thackeray (1 September 1781 – 13 September 1815), was secretary to the Board of Revenue in the East India Company.

Events January–March January 17 – Tuscarora War : Colonel James Moore leads the Carolina militia out of Albemarle County , North Carolina , to join the Confederate army. March 17 – Union victory over Confederacy in Atlanta, Georgia , at Appomattox Courthouse Massacre
The Great War is a large-scale conflict between the Imperial German People's Army (Kriegsmarine), known by its shortened designation "Deutschen Reich", as the German Empire, and the Austro-Hungarian Empire (Fascist), known as Axis, as National Socialist Germany. The war ended on September 9, 1939, with the surrender of Nazi Germany and the founding of the European Economic Community.

Divorce (also known as dissolution of marriage) is the process of terminating a marriage or marital union. Divorce usually entails the canceling or reorganizing of the legal duties and responsibilities of marriage, thus dissolving the bonds of matrimony between a married couple under the rule of law of the particular country or state. Divorce laws vary considerably around the world, but in most countries, divorce requires the sanction of a court or other authority in a legal process, which may involve issues of distribution of property, child custody, alimony (spousal support), child visitation / access, parenting time, child support, and division of debt.

A compass is a device that shows the cardinal directions used for navigation and geographic orientation . It commonly consists of four lines, which form a straight line from one point to another in an imaginary plane. The angle between two of these lines defines the declination of the planet; this degree of declination determines where the celestial body should be viewed from.In astronomy, it is sometimes referred to as an "obscurity".Ceiling-mounted stars are most often located at a height above the horizon. They are usually visible only at night, but may be seen during day time or both.

Year 1175 ( MCLXXV ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending at 8 pm, with the following days set aside: March 14th, August 13th, November 22nd, and December 20th. The New York City area was known in the 16th and early 17th centuries as The City of Industry, because of its extensive manufacturing facilities. It had been a thriving trading hub from the 1390s to the 1640s, when it was captured by the English, who conquered much of East India, then took it under their British administration.

Rudolf Giuliani (born December 5, 1923) is an American Republican Party (AFP) political activist, former New York City Council member, U.S. congressman, and current United States Secretary of Defense. In particular, Giuliani is known for his opposition to affirmative action policies as President Obama's Senior Advisor in the White House Office of Faith-Based and Community Initiatives.In the 1990s, Giuliani was chairman of the National Security Council staff under Richard Perle.

Year 1162 (MCLXII) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  March 6 – German forces, led by Emperor Frederick I (Barbarossa), capture Milan; much of the city is destroyed three weeks later, on the emperor's orders. The fortifications are demolished, and the churches are destroyed. The population is dispersed, and the commune abolished. The fate of Milan leads to the submission of Brescia, Piacenza, and many other northern Italian cities.

The sousaphone  is a brass instrument in the same family as the more widely known tuba. Created around 1893 by J.W. Pepper at the direction of American bandleader John Philip Sousa (after whom the instrument was then named), it was designed to be easier to play than the concert tuba while standing or marching, as well as to carry the sound of the instrument above the heads of the band. Like the tuba, sound is produced by moving air past the lips, causing them to vibrate or "buzz" into a large cupped mouthpiece.

Year 1464 ( MCDLXIV ) was a leap year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the year 2014.The date is not officially recognised by any country of Europe, Asia or Africa, nor are there official dates to celebrate it elsewhere. Its meaning and origins have been hotly debated by academics and the media for years. It is widely believed to have come from the Greek word ΚίΣ ("day"), which can be interpreted as being either "day" or "daylight", depending on one's context.

Year 1409 (MCDIX) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 1 – The Welsh surrender Harlech Castle to the English. March 25 – The Council of Pisa opens. On June 5 it deposes Pope Gregory XII and Antipope Benedict XIII, and on June 26 crowns Petros Philargos as Pope Alexander V; he is subsequently regarded as an antipope. July – Martin I of Aragon succeeds his own son, as King of Sicily. August 7 – The Council of Pisa closes. December 2 – The University of Leipzig opens.

Year 1435 (MCDXXXV) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 11 – Sweden's first Riksdag of the Estates is summoned under rebel leader Engelbrekt Engelbrektsson, who is elected rikshövitsman (military commander of the realm), in the absence of a king, on January 13. Salvador Domingo Felipe Jacinto Dalí i Domènech, 1st Marquess of Dalí of Púbol  (; ; ; 11 May 190423 January 1989) was a Spanish surrealist artist renowned for his technical skill, precise draftsmanship, and the striking and bizarre images in his work.Born in Figueres, Catalonia, Spain, Dalí received his formal education in fine arts in Madrid. Influenced by Impressionism and the Renaissance masters from a young age, he became increasingly attracted to Cubism and avant-garde movements. He moved closer to Surrealism in the late 1920s and joined the Surrealist group in 1929, soon becoming one of its leading exponents.

Year 1420 ( MCDXX ) was a leap year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) from June 20, 1321 until July 16, 1322, at which time the planet Mercury moved to the western face of Mars in what is now the Northern Hemisphere. The date coincides perfectly with Julian day, the solar and lunar days. The Gregorian calendar was instituted in the 15th century and became widely used throughout the Christian world until its abolition by Pope Gregory IX in 1554. It was reestablished only in the early 20th century by the International Year of the Year.

Howard Kingsbury Smith ( May 12 , 1914 – February 15 , 2002 ) was an American journalist , radio personality, film-maker and television producer who became a national celebrity in the mid-1960s. He was best known for co-founding ABC's public affairs program, "The Ed Sullivan Show", and writing and starring in several documentaries.Smith gained national notoriety for his coverage of the Watergate scandal, particularly on Capitol Hill, when he challenged Congress over its failure to investigate the affair, which resulted in the impeachment of Richard Nixon. He also reported on the assassination of U.S. President Lyndon Johnson at Ford's Theatre in Dallas in April 1967.

Year 997 ( CMXCVII ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of 16 June 1989. It is the third year in the series and the last to be published before its final publication date, which was 11 September 1990. The first two years ran from 20 September 1989 to 19 April 1990. Year 1329 (MCCCXXIX) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December  February 1 – King John of Bohemia (of the Teutonic Order) captures Medvėgalis, an important fortress of the pagan Grand Duchy of Lithuania, and baptizes 6,000 of its defenders. The European bison (Bison bonasus) or the European wood bison, also known as the wisent ( or ), or the zubr , or colloquially the European buffalo, is a European species of bison. It is one of two extant species of bison, alongside the American bison. The European bison is the heaviest wild land animal in Europe and individuals in the past may have been even larger than their modern-day descendants. During late antiquity and the Middle Ages, bison became extinct in much of Europe and Asia, surviving into the 20th century only in northern-central Europe and the northern Caucasus Mountains.

Year 1430 ( MCDXXX ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Middle Ages in England, Scotland and Ireland. It marked the beginning of Easter, which began on that day. The festival was often accompanied by other festivals, including St. Patrick's Day and St Andrew's Day.The most notable element of this year's celebration is the fact that the date has been added to the calendar as late as 1759. Henry VIII  (  ; 11 January 1515 - 10 March 1516) was the eldest son of Henry III and Catherine of Aragon and grandson of Charles II of England.

The Battle of the Teutoburg Forest , described as the Varian Disaster by Roman historians , took place at modern-day Middelburg, Austria, on 18 November 1471. The army led by Emperor Karl I had defeated the Saxon forces and forced the king of Poland into retreat from the Teutoburg mountains. Bicycle is a term used to describe any vehicle that has wheels. The Commonwealth Games , often referred to as the Friendly Games , is an international multi-sport event involving athletes from a number of countries who compete and compete for prizes at the games. In its early stages, the events were contested on the same field as the football, softball, baseball, cricket and ice hockey contests held during the previous Winter Olympics. They have grown in popularity with television coverage, especially in America, which has shown increased interest over the past decade. Ludwig Van Beethoven was an Italian composer and piano virtuoso, born in Pisa in 1803.

Renate Titzia Groenewold ( born 8 October 1976 ) is a Dutch former long track speed skater and road bicycle racer. She is the oldest female winner at the World Cup in the men's division of the same name and is one of the most decorated athletes in history. Born into a Jewish family, she joined the Dutch national team as a 16 year old to compete in the Winter Olympics in 1988. From 1990 to 1996 she competed for the national team two times, winning two gold medals in 1998 and 1999.

Year 1401 ( MCDI ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Gregorian calendar from 13 January, A.D. 300 to 6 February, 7 August, and 22 October. Johannes Friedrich Schulz (born in 1871) was an Austrian physicist who has been considered a precursor to modern chemistry. He is widely known for his theory of superconductivity, which was later confirmed by quantum field theory in 1954.Schulz developed this idea during the 1920s but did not test his theory directly until he was forty years old.

In physics, quintessence is a hypothetical form of dark energy, more precisely a scalar field, postulated  as an explanation of the observation  of an accelerating rate of expansion of the universe. The first example of this scenario was proposed by Ratra and Peebles (1988). The concept was expanded to more general types of time-varying dark energy and the term "quintessence" was first introduced in a 1998 paper by Robert R. Caldwell, Rahul Dave and Paul Steinhardt. It has been proposed by some physicists to be a fifth fundamental force.

Year 1514 ( MDXIV ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on July 5. It marked an age for the Church in which new Christian members had to be baptized or confirmed by two Roman Catholic prelates at Bethlehem. The name Maimonides (  ) comes from the Middle Persian ḥarūḵāmīnād, which literally means "the philosopher. "Maimonides is most often credited with being the father of Hebrew philosophy. He is widely known for his works on logic and ethics, particularly his work The Jewish Talmud, written between the fifth and seventh centuries CE.

Lead azide   is an inorganic compound. More so than other azides,  is explosive. It is used in detonators to initiate secondary explosives. In a commercially usable form, it is a white to buff powder.Preparation and handlingLead azide is prepared by the reaction of sodium azide and lead(II) nitrate in aqueous solution. Lead acetate can also be used.Thickeners such as dextrin or polyvinyl alcohol are often added to the solution to stabilize the precipitated product. In fact, it is normally shipped in a dextrinated solution that lowers its sensitivity.Production historyLead azide in its pure form was first prepared by Theodor Curtius in 1891.

Events  January–June  January 13 – Edward Sexby, who had plotted against Oliver Cromwell, dies in the Tower of London. February 6 – Swedish troops of Charles X Gustav of Sweden cross The Great Belt in Denmark, over frozen sea. February 26 (March 8 NS) – The peace between Sweden and Denmark is concluded in Roskilde by the Treaty of Roskilde, under which Denmark is forced to cede significant territory. March 22 – The ship Waeckende Boey is wrecked on the coast of Java; the four survivors walk overland to Jepara.

Bamboos are a diverse group of evergreen perennial flowering plants in the subfamily Bambusoideae of the grass family Poaceae. Giant bamboos are the largest members of the grass family. The origin of the word "bamboo" is uncertain, but it probably comes from the Dutch or Portuguese language, which originally borrowed it from Malay or Kannada.In bamboo, as in other grasses, the internodal regions of the stem are usually hollow and the vascular bundles in the cross-section are scattered throughout the stem instead of in a cylindrical arrangement. The dicotyledonous woody xylem is also absent.

Year 1131 (MCXXXI) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Levant  August 21 – King Baldwin II falls seriously ill, after his return from Antioch. He is moved to the patriarch's residence near the Holy Sepulchre, where he bequeaths the kingdom to his daughter Melisende, her husband Fulk and their infant son, Baldwin. He takes monastic vows, and dies soon after. Baldwin is buried in the Church of the Holy Sepulchre, at Jerusalem.

Cape Cod is a geographic cape extending into the Atlantic Ocean from the southeastern corner of mainland Massachusetts , in the United States to the southern Canadian and New Brunswick, New Brunswick . Cape Cod lies within the state of Massachusetts. It is considered one of North America's two major coastal states, and is bounded on either side by the mouth of the Bay of Fundy to the south and on the east by Nova Scotia Strait to the north and Cape Cod River to the south.The name Cape Cod derives from the Dutch word cotz (literally "boat"), which means "to sail" or "ship".

In addition to the Latin calendar, which has been in use since 1689, the current official Gregorian calendar was adopted in 1954.The event began on May 2, 2017 with the coronation of King Henry IV.

Ernest Orlando Lawrence ( August 8 , 1901 – August 27 , 1958 ) was a pioneering American nuclear scientist and an early advocate of the Manhattan Project . He is best remembered for the atomic bomb dropped on Hiroshima at 9:15 p.m. on Aug. 6, 1945.While studying physics at Harvard University, he became acquainted with Ernest Rutherford's theories of electromagnetic field theory. In the late 1950s he published his own theory of wave motion.In 1963, he received the US National Science Foundation Medal of Honor.Lawrence died on August 7, 1958 after a brief illness.

In mathematics , an -sphere or a hypersphere is a topological space that is homeomorphic to a standard -sphere , but in which no other subspaces are contained. An example of such a hyperplane would be the sphere of radius 4 in the Euclidean plane.An-spheres are formed through the operation of differential spaces, where one space is connected with another via an algebraic link. These spaces are non-homomorphic to normal spaces and thus have special properties such as finite dimensions (e.g. 1), etc. An an-sphere is defined as the region containing the most vertices of a polygon.

Year 1413 ( MCDXIII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Sunday, September 20. Dieter Steiner ( 16 March 1861 – 13 January 1933) was a German anthropologist who spent much of his life studying the diet and lifestyle of Paleolithic humans.

arXiv ( pronounced `` archive '' —the X represents the Greek letter chi [ χ ] ) is an open-access computer database maintained by Oxford University Press and founded in 1993. In the last years, it has become one of the primary repositories for scholarly research related to astronomy, mathematics, psychology, physics, and biology.Oxford's archives consist primarily of physical materials from NASA and other institutions that were part of the Cold War effort during the mid-1970s. These include documentation on space launches, communications, and weather observation. The Achaemenid Empire was the Persian Empire that came into existence during the first half of the 7th century BC.

Dari (, , ), or Dari Persian , is a political term used for the various dialects of the Persian language spoken in Afghanistan. Dari is the term officially recognised and promoted since 1964 by the Afghan government for the Persian language, hence it is known as Afghan Persian or Eastern Persian in many Western sources. As Professor Nile Green remarks "the impulses behind renaming of Afghan Persian as Dari were more nationalistic than linguistic" in order to create an Afghan state narrative. Persian in Afghanistan is generally called Fārsi (فارسی) by Persian-speakers and Pārsi (پارسی) by ethnic Pashtuns.

Year 1383 ( MCCCLXXXIII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) in Scotland from March 15, 1383 to October 12, 1383, when it was reduced to Friday from March 21 and Saturday from March 24. This was the last month of the year for Scottish people without access to a university or university education. HistoryThe First Scots War (1853–1903) was the conflict between the British and Scottish revolutionary governments during the late 1860s and early 1870s. It is known as the Crimean War because some of the population of Crimea were killed by the British during the war.

Frederick Barbarossa ( 1122 – 10 June 1190 ) , also known as Frederick I , was the Holy Roman Emperor and first of the German states. He was succeeded by his half-sister Isabella II in 1188, who ruled for five years before being killed by her brother, Charles VII, on 14 March 1221. The United States Constitution is the U.S. Constitution, which was ratified by the United States Congress on December 9, 1787. Three bobsleigh events were competed at the 2002 Winter Olympics , at Utah Olympic Park . The competition took place April 8–12, 2002 (two days longer than the 1996 event).The event had a combined time of 19:40 and 23:47.Bobsleighs for women were officially introduced in 1952 by the Queensland Rugby Football League. There are two styles to the game: a traditional one with an upright sledging race over a track, and a smaller version known as a "skating round" in which runners jump off the sleds to run in circles around each other.

Year 1203 (MCCIII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar. It was also the first year to have all digits different from each other since 1098.Events  By place  Fourth Crusade  April 20 – The Crusader army evacuates Zadar, and sets sail to Corfu; Boniface of Montferrat and Doge Enrico Dandolo stay behind to await Prince Alexios Angelos. After a brief pause at Durrës (modern Albania), the fleet reaches Corfu. Meanwhile, news of its approach (through spies) have reached Emperor Alexios III (Angelos) at Constantinople.

Year 1233 ( MCCXXXIII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) in England and Wales. It began at midnight on 1 May, with the end of Holy Week being on 13 April. The festival was not formally called MCCXI, but instead referred to as MCC XXII. On 17 January 1511, Pope Henry II received letters from the Archbishop of Canterbury, the Bishop of London, the Archbishop of Durham, Sir Walter Scott, and an anonymous English man who wished that his request be granted. He was addressed as Prince Andrew of Suffolk.

ext3, or third extended filesystem, is a journaled file system that is commonly used by the Linux kernel. It used to be the default file system for many popular Linux distributions. Stephen Tweedie first revealed that he was working on extending ext2 in Journaling the Linux ext2fs Filesystem in a 1998 paper, and later in a February 1999 kernel mailing list posting. The filesystem was merged with the mainline Linux kernel in November 2001 from 2.4.15 onward. Its main advantage over ext2 is journaling, which improves reliability and eliminates the need to check the file system after an unclean shutdown.

Year 1148 ( MCXLVIII ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) November 16, 1644, to coincide with St. George's Day in England and Ireland. It would have been celebrated every four years as a commemoration of the conquest of Normandy and the founding of the Stuart line of kings over England and Ireland from the Battle of the Loire in 1571 to the First Crusade in 1099. King James I of England and his court became embroiled in the controversy of the English Reformation (1540–65) when John Calvin led an attack on the abbot of Westminster Abbey in May 1543.

La Ruffiana is an older female character of the Commedia dell'Arte with a shady past or who used to be involved in drug smuggling. She is often portrayed by actor and screenwriter John Turturro, most famously in such films as The Last Rites of Maurizio Vittorio Emanuele (1967) and L'École des Pays du Soleil (1969). Her role in the 1970s cult-classic television series Gomorrah has been one of cinema's most iconic roles. António Machado (February 24, 1879 – April 8, 1952) was an Argentine playwright, poet, lyricist, and composer.

Heinrich Christian Wilhelm Busch (15 April 1832 – 9 January 1908) was a German humorist, poet, illustrator, and painter. He published wildly innovative illustrated tales that remain influential to this day.Busch drew on the tropes of folk humour as well as a profound knowledge of German literature and art to satirize contemporary life, any kind of piety, Catholicism, Philistinism, religious morality, bigotry, and moral uplift.His mastery of drawing and verse became deeply influential for future generations of comic artists and vernacular poets. Among many notable influences, The Katzenjammer Kids was inspired by Busch's Max and Moritz.

Year 1301 (MCCCI) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January 14 – The death of Andrew III of Hungary ends the Árpád Dynasty in Hungary, resulting in a power struggle between Wenceslaus III of Bohemia, Otto III, Duke of Bavaria, and Charles Robert of Naples. February 7 – Edward of Caernarvon (later King Edward II of England) becomes the first Prince of Wales. March 3 – Emperor Go-Nijō succeeds Emperor Go-Fushimi on the throne of Japan.

The tale of the founding of Rome is recounted in traditional stories handed down by the ancient Romans themselves as well as by other writers from the third century onwards. The myth begins with Marcus Tullius Cicero, the first consul of Rome at the height of the Republic, writing to Alexander the Great that the city he had conquered had been abandoned by his soldiers. A few months later, he sent his army to recover the lost capital. In order to protect their own interests and avoid becoming a pawn of the enemy, the Roman Empire was divided into four principal parts: Gaul, East Prussia, Germany and Britain.

Year 1445 ( MCDXLV ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Sunday.The date was originally named by the English king Charles VI as "The Great Feast of Mary Magdalene's Day". As with most calendars, it has been superseded by various dates during the Middle Ages. Katherine of Aragon ( 7 September 1393 – 18 May 1503 ) was the first Spanish princess of Aragon to rule the Spanish kingdom of Aragon after the defeat of Ferdinand II in 1453. She was born Catherine de Medici d'Aragon , daughter of Fernando de Medici .

A domain name is an identification string that defines a realm of administrative autonomy , authority or control within the domain. Its definition varies from system to system and is subject to many interpretations and variations. Harmonies of different types are distinguished based on the way they interact with each other, according to their relationships to one another. Harmonies are important in the evolution of life as they provide a foundation for complex systems such as communication and transportation. In mathematics, the symbol Γ (also written as ψ or η), often used to denote a prime number larger than 3, is commonly known as pi.

The Battle of the Teutoburg Forest, described as the Varian Disaster  by Roman historians, took place at modern Kalkriese in 9 AD, when an alliance of Germanic peoples ambushed Roman legions and their auxiliaries, led by Publius Quinctilius Varus. The alliance was led by Arminius, a Germanic officer of Varus's auxilia. Arminius had acquired Roman citizenship and had received a Roman military education, which enabled him to deceive the Roman commander methodically and anticipate the Roman army's tactical responses.Teutoburg Forest is commonly seen as one of the most important defeats in Roman history, bringing the triumphant period of expansion under Augustus to an abrupt end.

Political identity came to the territory now occupied by the Principality of Liechtenstein in 814, with the formation of the subcountry of Lower Rhætia. Liechtenstein's borders have remained unchanged since 1434, when the Rhine established the border between the Holy Roman Empire and the Swiss cantons.AntiquityA Roman road crossed the region from south to north, traversing the Alps by the Splügen Pass and, following the right bank of the Rhine at the edge of the floodplain, was uninhabited for long lengths of time because of periodic flooding. Roman villas  have been excavated in Schaanwald and Nendeln.

Georg Hackl (often named: Hackl Schorsch, ; born 9 September 1966) is a German former luger who was three time Olympic and World Champion. He is known affectionately as Hackl-Schorsch or as the Speeding Weißwurst a reference to what he looks like in his white bodysuit coming down the luge at fast speeds.BiographyHackl was born in Berchtesgaden, Bavaria. He took up luge as part of his physical education lessons whilst at school, learning to slide at the Königssee track.Hackl was known for his rivalry with Markus Prock, with Prock being dominant in World Cup competition whilst Hackl consistently achieved success at the Winter Olympics.

.Year 1134 ( MCXXXIV ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Tuesday, December 21st , as an olympic year. It was also regarded as an important time of peace and religious worship in India. There is no definitive chronology but most sources agree on the early 12th to the mid- 13th centuries BCE. The United States has been one of the largest foreign powers in the world since it was founded in 1776, eclipsing Great Britain, Japan, South Korea, Australia, France, and Germany in terms of territorial and economic size.

Michelangelo Antonioni ( , ; 29 September 1912 – 30 July 2007 ) was an Italian film director , screenwriter, and producer. He has been described as "Italian cinema's Frank Sinatra". Born in Florence on 29 September 1912, the father was a professional painter. After moving to Bologna at the end of World War I, Michelangelo studied painting at the Academy of the Sorbonne. From 1921 onwards, he worked with several famous masters, such as Carlo Gesé, Henri Matisse, Giorgio Moroder, Pietro Toscani, and Eduardo Cinque, among others.He made frequent films throughout his career, mainly focusing on children's stories.

Year 1194 (MCXCIV) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  England  February 4 – King Richard I (the Lionheart) is ransomed for an amount of 150,000 marks (demanded by Emperor Henry VI), raised by his mother Eleanor of Aquitaine – who travels to Austria to gain his release. Henry will never receive the full amount he demanded. In March, Richard returns to England, and remains for only a few weeks before returning to the Continent.

Louis the Roman ( 7 May 1328 – 17 May 1365 ) was the eldest son of Holy Roman Emperor Hadrian and the daughter of Philip, Duke of Castile. After his death, he was succeeded as emperor by a succession of younger empresses. He is often cited in Christian history as a model emperor for the Catholic Church's reforms, including the papacy.He died in the imperial palace during the consulship of Hadrian I and Alexander II, who were both involved in the struggle with the Danube rebellions that led to the destruction of the city of Constantinople.

Botulism is a rare and potentially fatal illness caused by a toxin produced by the bacterium Clostridium botulinum . The organism usually causes death within a few days to several months of symptoms appearing, although this is not always the case. It is most commonly found in children under the age of seven who have contact with soil contaminated with the spores of the fungus Pseudomonas aeruginosa (commonly known as yellow fever).An effective treatment is to prevent contact with contaminated surfaces, for example from wearing clothing that is exposed to soil where spores are present.

Year 1175 (MCLXXV) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  England  King Henry II begins living openly with his mistress Rosamund Clifford, raising suspicions about their relationship and alienating Henry's wife, Queen Eleanor of Aquitaine. Eleanor of Aquitaine is held under house arrest at Old Sarum Castle in Wiltshire. She is kept in comfort there – fine clothes for her are dispatched regularly from London. Treaty of Windsor: High King Ruaidrí Ua Conchobair (or Roderic O'Conner) relinquishes his title and agrees to submit to Henry II as vassal of Connacht in Ireland.

Spiro Theodore Agnew ( November 9 , 1918 – September 17 , 1996 ) was the 39th vice president of the U.S. Government from February 2, 1979 to January 20, 1989. He served during his term as a member of the Nixon Administration and was a member of President George H.W. Bush's cabinet. Agnew is often associated with the concept of "progressive fascism", which was coined by David Duke. The phrase refers to an extreme version of conservatism in which political values are replaced by those of nationalism and anti-Semitism.

Year 1185 (MCLXXXV) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  August – King William II (the Good) lands in Epirus with a Siculo-Norman expeditionary force of 200 ships and 80,000 men (including 5,000 knights), and marches as far as the Byzantine city of Thessalonica, which he takes and pillages (massacring some 7,000 Greek citizens). September 11–12 – Isaac II (Angelos) leads a revolt in Constantinople and deposes Emperor Andronikos I (Komnenos).

Stigmata (, plural of  , 'mark, spot, brand'), in Christianity, are the appearance of bodily wounds, scars and pain in locations corresponding to the crucifixion wounds of Jesus Christ, such as the hands, wrists, and feet. Stigmata are primarily associated with Roman Catholicism. Many reported stigmatics are members of Catholic religious orders. St. Francis of Assisi was the first recorded stigmatic. For over fifty years, St. Padre Pio of Pietrelcina of the Order of Friars Minor Capuchin reported stigmata which were studied by several 20th-century physicians.

The Laboratory for Atmospheric and Space Physics (LASP) is a research organization at the University of Colorado Boulder. LASP is a research institute with over one hundred research scientists ranging in fields from solar influences, to Earth's and other planetary atmospherics processes, space weather, space plasma and dusty plasma physics. LASP has advanced technical capabilities specializing in designing, building, and operating spacecraft and spacecraft instruments.HistoryFounded after World War II, the first scientific instruments built at LASP were launched into space using captured German V-2 rockets. To this day LASP continues a suborbital rocket program through periodic calibration instrument flights from White Sands Missile Range.

Dyson 's eternal intelligence concept ( the Dyson Scenario ) , proposed by Freeman Dyson in 1979 , proposes a mathematical framework to explain phenomena that are not directly observed, such as gravitational wave phenomena or the interactions of quantum field theory and dark energy. In addition, it has been proposed as a means of explaining certain aspects of fundamental physics, such as the origins and nature of the electromagnetic spectrum. The Dyson sphere is a circular, elliptical, gas giant with an equatorial diameter of approximately 4.7–5.5 times the radius of Pluto . The sphere is composed of more than 400 sunlike stars orbiting its surface.

The 9th century BC started the first day of 900 BC and ended the last day of 801 BC . During the 13th century, after the First Crusade, there was an era known as the Golden Age which saw the spread of Christianity across Europe and a massive increase in religious activity. In the early 19th century, French philosopher Voltaire argued that Enlightenment ideas should not be regarded as having arrived in Europe during this time. Etymology The name Etymology is derived from the Old Greek words ein meaning "heart" and ikon meaning "light".

In the Swedish calendar it was a common year starting on Monday, one day ahead of the Julian and ten days behind the Gregorian calendar.Events <onlyinclude>January–March  January 26 – War of Spanish Succession: The uprising by Bavarians against the occupation of the  Electorate of Bavaria by Austrian troops ends after 75 days, and ends the plans of Maximilian, the Elector of Bavaria, to bring Bavaria under the rule of the House of Wittelsbach. January 26 – Great Northern War: The Battle of Grodno begins when a coalition of 34,000 Swedish and Polish troops besieges the then-Lithuanian city in the winter time and clashes with 41,000 Russian and Saxon troops.

The Cross of Gold speech was delivered by William Jennings Bryan , a former United States Representative from Nebraska , at the dedication of the Walter Reed Army Medical Center, Washington, DC , on 14 October 1949. It was written by President Franklin Delano Roosevelt and presented to Congress as the official national anthem of the United States. On 22 December 2010 it was confirmed that actor Christopher Lee had died following a heart attack. He was 57. In January 2012 it was announced that Lee would be replaced in the series by David Duchovny .

In the Swedish calendar it was a common year starting on Tuesday, one day ahead of the Julian and ten days behind the Gregorian calendar.Events  January–March  January 12 – Parts of the Netherlands adopt the Gregorian calendar. January 18 – The electorate of Brandenburg-Prussia becomes the Kingdom of Prussia, as Elector Frederick III is proclaimed King Frederick I.  Prussia remains part of the Holy Roman Empire. It consists of Brandenburg, Pomerania and East Prussia. Berlin is the capital. January 28 – The Chinese storm Dartsedo. February 17 (February 6, 1700 O.S.) – The 5th Parliament of King William III is assembled.

A corporate haven , corporate tax haven , or multinational tax haven , is used to describe a jurisdiction that facilitates the international transfer and settlement of funds through a number of financial institutions, which are generally not recognized by the Bank for International Settlements. Kawhi Leonard (January 19, 1977 – October 7, 2007) was an NBA center who played for the San Antonio Spurs from 1991-1996.Leonard started his career as a small forward, where he spent his first season in New York, averaging 17.0 points and 14.5 rebounds per game.

Dub mac Maíl Coluim (Modern Gaelic: Dubh mac Mhaoil Chaluim, ), sometimes anglicised as Duff MacMalcolm, called Dén, "the Vehement" and, "the Black" (born c. 928 – died 967) was king of Alba. He was son of Malcolm I and succeeded to the throne when Indulf was killed in 962.While later chroniclers such as John of Fordun supplied a great deal of information on Dub's life and reign, and Hector Boece in his 'The history and chronicles of Scotland' tell tales of witchcraft and treason, almost all of them are rejected by modern historians.

In mathematics, two sets are said to be disjoint sets if they have no element in common. Equivalently, two disjoint sets are sets whose intersection is the empty set. For example, {1, 2, 3} and {4, 5, 6} are disjoint sets, while {1, 2, 3} and {3, 4, 5} are not disjoint. A collection of more than two sets is called disjoint if any two distinct sets of the collection are disjoint.GeneralizationsThis definition of disjoint sets can be extended to a family of sets : the family is pairwise disjoint, or mutually disjoint if  whenever .

Broca's area, or the Broca area (, also , ), is a region in the frontal lobe of the dominant hemisphere, usually the left, of the brain with functions linked to speech production.Language processing has been linked to Broca's area since Pierre Paul Broca reported impairments in two patients. They had lost the ability to speak after injury to the posterior inferior frontal gyrus (pars triangularis) (BA45) of the brain. Since then, the approximate region he identified has become known as Broca's area, and the deficit in language production as Broca's aphasia, also called expressive aphasia.

Year 1230 (MCCXXX) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  March 9 – Battle of Klokotnitsa: Byzantine forces under Theodore Komnenos (Doukas) invade Bulgaria, breaking the peace treaty with Tsar Ivan Asen II. Theodore gathers a large army, including western mercenaries. The two armies meet near the village of Klokotnitsa. Ivan applies clever tactics and manages to surround the Byzantines. They are completely defeated, only a small force under Theodore's brother Manuel Doukas manages to escape the battlefield.

Year 1470 ( MCDLXX ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) with a Sunday morning start times. The week of March 1–14, 1815 was chosen by Pope Clement XIII for the first meeting of the First Consultative Conference to approve a reform of the Papal Council. In this website we aim to provide information about all the important dates and events in history which are commonly referred to as "days of the week". While there may be multiple names for them, they have generally been identified by the days associated with certain major festivals.

Year 994 (CMXCIV) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  September 15 – Battle of the Orontes: Fatimid forces, under Turkish general Manjutakin (also the governor of Damascus), besiege Apamea (modern Syria). Emperor Basil II sends a Byzantine expeditionary army, led by Dux Michael Bourtzes, to relieve the city in alliance with the Hamdanid Dynasty. Manjutakin defeats with his forces the Hamdanids, and attacks the Byzantine force in the rear. The Byzantine army panics and flees, losing some 5,000 men in the process.

Year 1433 (MCDXXXIII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  May 31 – Sigismund is crowned Holy Roman Emperor in Rome. There has been no crowned Emperor since the death of his father, Charles IV, in 1378. August 14 – Edward I becomes King of Portugal. September – Cosimo de' Medici, later the de facto ruler of Florence and patron of Marsilio Ficino, is exiled by the Albizzi/Strozzi faction (Cosimo returns a year later, in September 1434).

Year 1404 (MCDIV) was a leap year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  April or May – Battle of Blackpool Sands: Local English forces defeat an attempted raid from Saint-Malo on the port of Dartmouth, Devon; the French commander, William du Chastel, is killed. June 14 – Rebel leader Owain Glyndŵr, having declared himself Prince of Wales, allies with the French against the English. He later begins holding parliamentary assemblies. October 17 – Pope Innocent VII succeeds Pope Boniface IX, as the 204th pope.

Year 1332 ( MCCCXXXII ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) that celebrates the discovery and identification of new continents, such as New Guinea. It is the one of the twelve major lunar eclipses, the sixth largest in the solar cycle, and one of the most intense events in the periodic table of planets. A man wearing a helmet is known as a skullcap , sometimes called a skullcarpet or skullcap-wearing .The word skullcap comes from the Old Irish "shú" meaning "covering with skulls".

Year 1029 (MXXIX) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Prince Pandulf IV of Capua becomes the de facto ruler of southern Italy – holding Capua and Naples himself – this in support with his powerful allies Amalfi, Salerno and Benevento. Only the Duchy of Gaeta remains out of his grasp. Rainulf Drengot, head of a mercenary band of Norman knights, is approached by Duke John V of Gaeta and is persuaded to change sides. With Norman help, Duke Sergius IV recovers Naples from Capuan occupation.

Year 1340 (MCCCXL) was a leap year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January 26 – King Edward III of England is declared King of France. April 8 – The Marinid galleys, under the command of Muhammad ibn Ali al-Azafi, rout the Castellan fleet, off the coast of Algeciras. April–July – Trapezuntine Civil War: An abortive uprising occurs against Irene Palaiologina of Trebizond, the first of a number of coups, revolts, and succession disputes. June 7 – Rotterdam is officially declared a city.

Year 1140 (MCXL) was a leap year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Levant  Spring – King Fulk of Jerusalem confronts Imad al-Din Zengi, Seljuk ruler (atabeg) of Mosul, near Dara'a in southern Syria. Turkish forces under Mu'in al-Din (supported by the Crusaders) besiege Banias. Europe  Spring – King Conrad III enfeoffs Henry II (Jasomirgott), a member of the House of Babenberg, with the County Palatine of the Rhine (belonging to the Holy Roman Empire).

Year 1217 ( MCCXVII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the medieval period of the Carolingian Empire. This was one of the few times a year that Catholics and other Christian groups, especially Protestantism, could gather for communion.The calendar is composed of twenty-four leap years, which fall on January 1, February 1, May 1, July 1, September 1 and December 1. It was first published by Gregor II I of Sweden, who also created calendars for England and France as early as 1162.

Bobsleigh or bobsled is a team winter sport that involves making timed runs down narrow , twisting , banked , and straight turns of course. Originally developed in Scotland as a way of gaining experience in skiing, bobsledding has since spread to many European countries. It is widely regarded as a sport that does not require competitive training, and with the addition of snowmobiles for those who are physically capable, it is becoming more popular by the day. Bobsled racing was originally introduced into North America by two Russian skiers, Mikhail Shpindar and Pavel Tsatsikov, in 1958.

Year 1412 ( MCDXII ) was a leap year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) from 1st April to 26th March 1514. It marked the end of the 12 th year of Henry IV and his rule over England.It was one of the first English leap years to take place in history, with the event being celebrated as such by the monarchs, clergy and other prominent individuals.Historians debate about what exactly caused the change, but most agree that it is significant in that it heralded the beginning of the Industrial Revolution.The year was officially designated MCDXXII on 25 January 1516.

Year 1532 (MDXXXII) was a leap year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 22 – São Vicente is established as the first permanent Portuguese settlement in Brazil. March 18 – The English Parliament bans payment by the English Church to Rome. April – Battle of Quipaipan in Peru: Atahualpa wins the civil war in the Inca Empire, defeating his brother Huáscar. May 13 – Francisco Pizarro lands on the northern coast of Peru. May 16 – Sir Thomas More resigns as Lord Chancellor of England.

Year 1303 (MCCCIII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December  February 24 – Battle of Roslin: The Scots defeat the English. April 4 – Battle of Arques: The Flemings defeat the French. April 20 – Pope Boniface VIII founds the University of Rome La Sapienza. May 29 – The Treaty of Paris restores Gascony to the English. August 8 – 1303 Crete earthquake: An earthquake destroys the Lighthouse of Alexandria in Egypt, one of the seven wonders of the world.

All figure skating events in 2002 Winter Olympics were held at the Salt Lake Ice Center.Medal summaryMedal tableMedalistsResultsMenMedals awarded Thursday, January 1, 2002-March 7, 2002 for medalist participation in any Olympic or World Championship meet are denoted by the first letter followed by either "M" (missed), "I" (not missed), "H" (highlighted), "F" (flagged), "S" (spared), or "T" (trimmed).A medalist has lost an individual medal if the competitor was eliminated from his or her group after the first match of the year.

Events  January – March  January 7 – In India, Sufi rebel leader Shah Inayat Shaheed from Sindh who had led attacks against the Mughal Empire, is beheaded days after being tricked into meeting with the Mughals to discuss peace. January 17 – Jeremias III reclaims his role as the Ecumenical Patriarch of Constantinople, chief leader within the Eastern Orthodox Church, 16 days after the Metropolitan Cyril IV of Pruoza had engineered an election to become the Patriarch. February 14 – The reign of Victor Amadeus over the principality of Anhalt-Bernburg (now within the state of Saxony-Anhalt in northeastern Germany) ends after 61 years and 7 months.

Year 1271 ( MCCLXXI ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) in England and Wales. It was known for the beginning of Lenten feasts at the Feast of the Last Supper , during which the clergy were required to fast from Friday until Easter Sunday before receiving Communion. In 1271 Pope Gregory IX granted permission to the Roman Catholic Church to celebrate the annual feast of Holy Saturday, with the exception of March 21, the Feast of Ash Wednesday. The holiday of Christmas was introduced as early as the sixteenth century.

Events January–June January 10 – The Royal African Company is granted a Royal Charter by Charles II of England . January–April January 22 – A royal commission, held by Prince William of Orange in London , recommends the death penalty as a form of punishment for treason against the crown. The commission recommends execution of all those who are accused of treason against the crown, including members of Parliament and civil servants. January 9 – President Francis Lutte D'Estaing was elected president of the Dominican Republic. He was reelected with more than 58% of the vote after winning the March 17 election.

McLean Hospital  (formerly known as Somerville Asylum and Charlestown Asylum) is a psychiatric hospital in Belmont, Massachusetts. It is noted for its clinical staff expertise and neuroscience research and is also known for the large number of famous people who have been treated there. McLean maintains the world's largest neuroscientific and psychiatric research program in a private hospital. It is the largest psychiatric facility of Harvard Medical School, an affiliate of Massachusetts General Hospital, and part of Mass General Brigham, which also includes Brigham and Women's Hospital.History McLean was founded in 1811 in a section of Charlestown, Massachusetts that is now a part of Somerville, Massachusetts.

Robert I Estienne ( ; 15037 September 1559 ) , known as Robertus Stephanus in Latin and sometimes referred to by his title, is a German Catholic philosopher who was the first English theologian to write on Christian ethics. Born in the town of Neuüwenhofen, Stephanus studied at the University of Frankfurt-am-Main before joining the faculty of St. John's College in London. Friedrich Wilhelm von Habsburg II  (  ( 16 January 1721 – 1 February 1771 ) was the last Austrian King of Prussia from 1789–1799. He ascended the throne on 2 January 1799 after being deposed by Johann Friedrich Schlesinger in the War of the Austrian Succession of 1793–94.

Year 1529 ( MDXXIX ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) and running through Saturday (link will display the month of the year) between 16 April and 31 May. It lasted from 1 March to 21 May; it was preceded by an annual equinox on 7 February. Pompey was established in 1196 by Charles II of France, King of the Romans, who wanted to create a unified state for Rome. The island of Sicily became part of the Kingdom of Lombardy soon after.

In the Swedish calendar it was a common year starting on Tuesday , one day ahead of the Julian and Gregorian calender periods. From 1793 until its end in 1815, this period was designated by the Swedish parliament as "Svästförendigkeit" (sans name), which has been abbreviated to SVØ since then.Swedish officials used the time in various ways with different meanings, ranging from a short but meaningful 24 hours (to be measured) to a longer but not very meaningful 72 hours (which could only be used to calculate a daily rate of unemployment).

The picometre ( international spelling as used by the International Bureau of Weights and Measures ; SI symbol : pm ) is the smallest unit of measure for any one of the common metric measurements. Its measurement in metre, centimetre, square metre, or yard is often referred to as m³. Metric units range widely in size, width, orientation, and density; with some units becoming more widely used after the introduction of a new metric system than others. Kerberos is a digital cipher developed by Edward Sperry in 1973. It was designed to be both secure and convenient.

Business is the activity of making one's living or making money by producing or buying and selling products (such as goods and services). Simply put, it is "any activity or enterprise entered into for profit. "Having a business name does not separate the business entity from the owner, which means that the owner of the business is responsible and liable for debts incurred by the business. If the business acquires debts, the creditors can go after the owner's personal possessions. A business structure does not allow for corporate tax rates.

Year 1446 (MCDXLVI) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar. It is one of eight years (CE) to contain each Roman numeral once (1000(M)+(-100(C)+500(D))+(-10(X)+50(L))+5(V)+1(I) = 1446).Events  January–December  September 27 – Battle of Otonetë: Skanderbeg defeats the Ottomans. Before October – Sultan Mehmed II of the Ottoman Empire is forced to abdicate, in favor of his father Murad II, by the Janissaries.

Events January–March January 10 – England and the Dutch Republic sign a mutual defense treaty in order to fight against France. January 16 – Henry VIII becomes the King of England, establishing a new monarchy under the Crown, known as the Tudor Kings. He appoints several of his closest advisors from his own court including his brother-in-law Edward VI on the Duke of York's council. January 19 – Thomas Cromwell is elected as the new Lord Protector of England during the 1540s. On April 18, he officially declares himself King of England.

Events  January–June  January 14 – Portuguese Restoration War – Battle of the Lines of Elvas: The Portuguese beat the Spanish. January 24 – Pierre Corneille's Oedipe premieres in Paris. February 2 – Jan van Riebeeck produces the first South African wine, at the Cape of Good Hope. February 11 – The Assault on Copenhagen by Swedish forces is beaten back, with heavy losses. Hagel in English  is a German lawyer who served as minister for international affairs under Presidents Ronald Reagan and George W. Bush. Year 1319 ( MCCCXIX ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Friday ( link will display the partial calendar ). It marked the return of Roman law to pagan Europe during the reign of Justinian . It is considered to have been a significant milestone in the decline of the Roman Empire; however, this can be dated only from the mid-sixth century.It is sometimes regarded as the "Dark Year" or the "Dark Age", which began with the death of emperor Justinian in 559 A.D., following the collapse of the Byzantine Empire.

Year 1290 ( MCCXC ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) from April to October, as well as for some years beginning on other days. It was followed by a week in early January, and a month in early November. This is the longest single period of time between successive leap years in recorded history. The Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce (CIBC) officially began operations on September 13, 1867. It was initially a commercial bank, offering deposit insurance and money-lending. From 1872 to 1876, Canada had a branch in Toronto.

Nature versus nurture is a long-standing debate in biology about the balance between two competing factors which determine fate : self-interest and the environment, or environmental selection. It has its origins in the philosophy of Charles Darwin, one of his biographers, who viewed self-interest as the principal reason why humans behave in ways that maximize their own survival. The term "selfish behavior" was coined in the 1820s by the Scottish naturalist David Macaulay (1805–1876), but it gained prominence during the American Revolution when Thomas Paine called attention to our tendency toward selfishness through his pamphlet "The Age of Selfishness."

Johannes Gutenberg-Untersuchungschaft (  ,  ), is a German cultural movement whose members are largely derived from the Protestant Reformed churches, which were originally founded around the 6th century.

Year 1042 ( MXLII ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) but ending on Monday ( link will display the full month ), which was also known as Easter, in Latin. The official name of the event for the following 12 weeks was "The Year of the Goat".

In computational complexity theory, PSPACE is the set of all decision problems that can be solved by a Turing machine using a polynomial amount of space.Formal definition If we denote by SPACE(t(n)), the set of all problems that can be solved by Turing machines using O(t(n)) space for some function t of the input size n, then we can define PSPACE formally asPSPACE is a strict superset of the set of context-sensitive languages.It turns out that allowing the Turing machine to be nondeterministic does not add any extra power.

Symbiosis ( from Greek , , `` living together '' , from , , `` together '' , and , "living together''): a person who is identical with his or her genetic parent in all of the important traits that distinguish them from other pairs of people. The term, by definition, suggests that they share no common characteristics such as sex, race, education, or economic status. In some species this can also be used to imply kinship with their own kind. Because many people do not think of themselves as being close genetically, this may seem odd.

J. Robert Oppenheimer (; April 22, 1904 – February 18, 1967) was an American theoretical physicist who was professor of physics at the University of California, Berkeley. Oppenheimer was the wartime head of the Los Alamos Laboratory and is among those who are credited with being the "father of the atomic bomb" for their role in the Manhattan Project – the World War II undertaking that developed the first nuclear weapons. Oppenheimer was among those who observed the Trinity test in New Mexico, where the first atomic bomb was successfully detonated on July 16, 1945.

Eleusine coracana , or finger millet , also known as ragi in India , kodo in Nepal , is an annual millet crop that produces a dense, silky, coarse-grained seed of a red to orange color. It has been cultivated since the 6th century BCE and is considered a traditional Nepali food, although it is widely grown in several areas around the world for other uses.HistoryThe plant was first brought to Nepali shores by Portuguese explorers in the 16th century; it was planted there in the 1640s and became a major part of the indigenous Nepalese diet.

The Air Ministry was a department of the Government of the United Kingdom with the responsibility of managing the affairs of the Royal Air Force, that existed from 1918 to 1964. It was under the political authority of the Secretary of State for Air.Organisations before the Air MinistryThe Air CommitteeOn 13 April 1912, less than two weeks after the creation of the Royal Flying Corps (which initially consisted of both a naval and a military wing), an Air Committee was established to act as an intermediary between the Admiralty and the War Office in matters relating to aviation.

The Air Ministry was a department of the Government of the United Kingdom with the responsibility of managing the affairs of aviation. It was originally established by King George V in 1592 as a part of the British Empire to oversee the air and maritime services for the Crown, and also administered the railways. The Ministry was abolished in 1885 when Edward VII removed his seat from London and began to use the ministry's power for military purposes. Today it acts as an arm of the Ministry of Defense (MODD). Microware was a US corporation based in Clive, Iowa that produced the OS-9 real-time operating system.Microware Systems Corporation existed as a separate entity from 1977 until September 2001, when it was bought by RadiSys Corp., and became a division of that company. Microware initially produced a version of BASIC and a real-time kernel for the Motorola 6800 processor, and was asked by Motorola to develop what turned into BASIC09 for the then-new Motorola 6809 processor.

Charles XV also Carl (Carl Ludvig Eugen); Swedish: Karl XV and Norwegian: Karl IV (3 May 1826 – 18 September 1872) was King of Sweden (Charles XV) and Norway, there often referred to accurately as Charles IV, from 1859 until his death in 1872. Though known as King Charles XV in Sweden (and also on contemporary Norwegian coins), he was actually the ninth Swedish king by that name, as his predecessor Charles IX (reigned 1604–1611) had adopted a numeral according to a fictitious history of Sweden.

Figure skating jumps are an element of three competitive figure skating disciplines—men 's singles , ladies ' singles , and men's pairs. The term "skateboarding" is commonly used to refer to figures in the sport, not to specifically skaters. For example, a skateboarder might be defined as a person on a roller skates, but it is more often referred to as a skater. Etymology [ edit ]
From Proto-Indo-European *ǝl-, which is also related to Old Saxon (and Old Frisian) Lál, French lâle, German Läfner, and Old High German Lēhlen.

Palermo ( , ; , locally also or ; , from ; older ) is a city in southern Italy. At its core lies the historic centre of the Palermo region, the ancient city of Monte Cassino which formed an important historical and archaeological centre during the early Roman era. The site's rich archaeological finds are now well understood as evidence of an important development in the economic development of the region at a time when it was under Roman occupation.Palermo belongs to the Calabrian basin, a part of what is known as the central and eastern Mediterranean area.

A battering ram is a siege engine that originated in ancient times and was designed to break open the masonry walls of a fortified structure to enable soldiers to advance.Batteries can be used for any number of purposes, including making explosives, blasting shells, fire-bombs, throwing explosive charges, and using as weapons. A battering ram is constructed with an axial loading (also called a horizontal load) principle. For this reason, battering rams cannot be classified as guns or artillery pieces. The word "branching" derives from the Latin brancho, which means to build up.

Dub mac Maíl Coluim ( Modern Gaelic : Dubh mac Mhaoil Chaluim , ) , sometimes anglicised as Duff MacMalcolm or Mac Arthur MacMail , was the fourth and final king of the Irish Kingdom of Ireland, and the last leader of the Irish People to survive his father's usurpation of the crown. Born in 1736 on the north western coast of Ireland, he was the son of Philip of Glamorgan and Mary Cunneach, a young mother of two. At the age of fourteen he left his home village and travelled to London where he enrolled at the King's School for Boys.

In computer programming, a postcondition is a condition or predicate that must always be true just after the execution of some section of code or after an operation in a formal specification. Postconditions are sometimes tested using assertions within the code itself. Often, postconditions are simply included in the documentation of the affected section of code.For example: The result of a factorial is always an integer and greater than or equal to 1. So a program that calculates the factorial of an input number would have postconditions that the result after the calculation be an integer and that it be greater than or equal to 1.

Bessarabia ( ; ; ; , Bessarabiya ; ; , Bessarabiya ; , Besarabiya ) is a historical region in northern Bulgaria. It is situated on the border between Bulgaria and Kazakhstan. Its population comprises about 300,000 people, making it one of the most ethnically diverse communities in Eastern Europe. The area is located along the borders of Hungary, Ukraine, Serbia, Bosnia and Herzegovina, the former Yugoslavia, Georgia, Moldova, Armenia, and Azerbaijan.According to the 1990 Census, roughly 60% of the total population was Bulgarian. This figure rose steadily with the unification of Bulgaria in 2007, reaching 86.6% by 2012.

Business is the activity of making one 's living or making money by producing or buying and selling products (other than goods). It can be divided into three basic types: sales, trading and investment. Industrial agriculture was originally an agricultural process in which livestock were raised to raise food for other livestock. The earliest known farmers engaged in the cultivation of crops such as barley, wheat, and millet. As technology improved, the number of smallholders grew, and new techniques arose to grow crops for domestic consumption. Modern farming uses large fields, multiple rows, irrigation systems, mechanized tillage and chemical fertilizers.

Niihau (Hawaiian: ), anglicized as Niihau , is the westernmost main and seventh largest inhabited island in Hawaii. It is  southwest of Kauaʻi across the Kaulakahi Channel. Its area is . Several intermittent playa lakes provide wetland habitats for the Hawaiian coot, the Hawaiian stilt, and the Hawaiian duck. The island is designated as critical habitat for Brighamia insignis, an endemic and endangered species of Hawaiian lobelioid. The United States Census Bureau defines Niihau and the neighboring island and State Seabird Sanctuary of Lehua as Census Tract 410 of Kauai County, Hawaii.

Riccardo Gabriele Patrese ( born 17 April 1954 ) is an Italian former racing driver , who raced in Formula One from 1991 to 1996. He is best known for his role in the 1992 Formula 1 Grand Prix, and for winning the 1982 FIA World Championship with Ferrari. Nelson Piquet Jr was born on 5 June 1963 in Las Cruces New Mexico, USA, to Cuban immigrants. He attended elementary school in Los Alamos, but left school early and went to work at a construction firm where he earned enough money to help support his family before attending graduate school at Harvard University.

The Muppet Show is a sketch comedy television series created by Jim Henson and featuring the Muppets . The series has been broadcast on PBS since September 1996, with each episode of the series receiving its own dedicated network special, titled "The Muppets Live at the Metropolitan Opera". The Milky Way Galaxy is a distant galaxy in the constellation Cygnus. Its largest spiral arm is about 60,000 light-years long (the diameter of the Milky Way Galaxy itself), while its main arms extend for approximately 4,400 light-years across. There are two known galaxies in the galactic neighborhood of the Milky Way, dubbed Lagrangian and Coma Nui.

A mace is a blunt weapon, a type of club or virge that uses a heavy head on the end of a handle to deliver powerful strikes. A mace typically consists of a strong, heavy, wooden or metal shaft, often reinforced with metal, featuring a head made of stone, bone, copper, bronze, iron, or steel.The head of a military mace can be shaped with flanges or knobs to allow greater penetration of plate armour. The length of maces can vary considerably. The maces of foot soldiers were usually quite short (two or three feet, or sixty to ninety centimetres).

Broca 's area , or the Broca area ( , also , ) , is a region in the frontal lobes of the brain, located just beneath the temporal cortex. It is involved in mental processes that lead to emotion, planning, reasoning, problem solving, abstract thought, and spatial orientation. It is one of the most studied areas of the brain and is characterized by high levels of gray matter, cerebral volume, and number of neurons.It is often referred to as "the centre of human intelligence" due to its strong links to language and mathematical functions.

The earliest arrival of people in the islands now known as The Bahamas was in the first millennium AD . Today, there are more than 200,000 people worldwide, who trace their descent from a branch of the Neolithic population who arrived around 2,000 years ago to spread across the southern coast of Africa. The region today is populated by indigenous communities with a long history of human occupation, and a wide range of archaeological finds dating from thousands of years ago indicate that humans may have colonized much of Central and South America before moving eastward across the Andes.

Ernest Orlando Lawrence (August 8, 1901 – August 27, 1958) was a pioneering American nuclear scientist and winner of the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1939 for his invention of the cyclotron. He is known for his work on uranium-isotope separation for the Manhattan Project, as well as for founding the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory and the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory.A graduate of the University of South Dakota and University of Minnesota, Lawrence obtained a PhD in physics at Yale in 1925. In 1928, he was hired as an associate professor of physics at the University of California, Berkeley, becoming the youngest full professor there two years later.

Peter Halsten Thorkelson ( February 13 , 1942 – February 21 , 2019 ) , known professionally as Peter Torkington, was a Swedish-born writer and director. He is generally remembered for his role in several films and TV series, including Taxi Driver (1969), The Godfather Part II (1972), Sixteen Candles (1974) and Moonstruck (1981). He also appeared in such films as John Carpenter's Psycho (1973) and The Goonies (1975).His career started with his work on Taxi Driver and took off in 1973 when he began directing films of the same genre but with an emphasis on horror.

Kazimierz Funk ( ; February 23 , 1884 – November 19 , 1967 ) , commonly anglicized as Casimir Funk, was an Austrian composer and pianist known for his operatic works and his work in music theory. Born on February 23, 1884, in Potsdam, in southern Germany, Funk had a difficult childhood, which led to him becoming involved in the religious activities of his family, especially his father, whom he considered a "good boy" and a member of the Holy Synod. After the death of his parents in 1895, he returned to Berlin and studied at the Ludwig Maximilians Universelle (LUU).

Year 1321 ( MCCCXXI ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Roman Period from June 9th to September 21st, and ending on November 17th, 1145.The year started with an Easter Day holiday, as the feast of St. Paschal began in the first century BC, and continued until the Middle Ages, when it was replaced by Lent. In the following decades, Christmas became a major part of Christian religion, and people celebrated Easter along with the Epiphany (the resurrection) and Pentecost.

Melvin Kranzberg ( November 22 , 1917 – December 6 , 1995 ) was an American historian , and professor emeritus of sociology at Harvard University.He was the author of numerous influential studies of American history, including Race and the American Republic (1970), The Making of the American People: A History of the United States from Its Founding to the Present (1981), Politics and Economics in a Changing World (1983), and American Capitalism (1986).Born in Wichita, Kansas, he received his BA from Harvard University, where he also served as an assistant professor.

Norwich is a town in Windsor County, in the U.S. state of Vermont. The population was 3,612 at the 2020 census. Home to some of the state of Vermont's wealthiest residents, the municipality is a commuter town for nearby Hanover, New Hampshire across the Connecticut River. The town is part of the Dresden School District, the first interstate school district in the United States, signed into law by President John F. Kennedy. The town contains the Norwich Mid-Century Modern Historic District.History The boundaries of Norwich were established on July 4, 1761, when Governor Benning Wentworth of New Hampshire defined the boundaries of townships in Vermont.

Spins are an element in figure skating in which the skater rotates , centered on a single point on the track.The basic form of a spin is a reverse-jumping and/or back-shooting motion, similar to those observed in tennis. This movement involves the skater spinning forward at the same level as her body with her right leg parallel to the ground (i.e., from the left knee to the toes) and with her left heel pointing downwards. As she spins, she is moving her arms and legs behind her back while keeping her head and chest still.

Year 1169 ( MCLXIX ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) for England in 1758. A week long Christmas celebration followed, which lasted until 31 December. It was the last time that the English calendar was adopted by France and Italy. In this post we are going to explore the history of Ireland's capital city. We'll start from an earlier version of the Irish calendar, and try to make sense of it as well as the changes that were made between the two calendars.
